<FIRST>r w PM-PresidentialDucks     02-01 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Ducks,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Duck Talk Sweeps the White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush may be getting his ducks in a
row on the federal budget, but he certainly doesn't want any of his
budget lines to turn up as ducks.
   That's because a duck by any other name in Washington these days
is a tax increase.
   And Bush administration officials insist there'll be no ducks _
new taxes _ in the budget plan Bush sends Congress on Feb. 9.
   This duck business started when budget director Richard G. Darman
wrote a letter to the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
reaffirming Bush's intention to resist new taxes.
   On whether the administration might hide a tax under another
name, Darman suggested that wouldn't wash. Most Americans, he
suggested, know that ``if it walks like a duck and quacks like a
duck, it must be a duck.''
   That's an old line, but Darman gave it new currency.
   Now it has joined the lexicon of other budget cliches, mentioned
almost as frequently these days as that mythical budget ``table''
that items are always described as being off or on.
   As in, nothing's ``off the table.'' Or everything's ``on the
table.''
   ``Not to mix metaphors, but ducks are off the table,'' Darman
told Congress.
   Bush himself has picked up on the duck talk.
   At his first news conference, he was asked whether a Treasury
proposal for a depositor fee to assist troubled savings-and-loans
might violate his anti-tax stand.
   ``I would refer you to Richard Darman,'' the president responded.
``He's the guy that defined that very well up there with the duck
test on the Hill.''
   Darman repeatedly used the duck analogy during his confirmation
hearings. He was presented at one point with a mock trophy by
committee Chairman Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio.
   It consisted of three bright yellow toy ducks and the label, ``if
it quacks, it's a tax.''
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu threw yet another
ingredient into the duck soup _ a rose.
   Asked at a news conference whether he thought the savings and
loan fee was a tax, Sununu responded obliquely: ``Yesterday's rose
is tomorrow's rose.''
   When he did not elaborate further, he was asked: ``A rose is a
rose?'' and ``It passes the rose test?''
   ``Let's put it this way,'' Sununu said. ``Yesterday's duck is
tomorrow's duck.''
   Actually today's duck is not yesterday's duck, so far as Bush is
concerned. Bush's duck of yesteryear was not a tax increase but a
Sandinista.
   When running for re-election in 1984, then-Vice President Bush
caused something of a stir in a campaign speech at Texas A&amp;M
University as he portrayed the Sandinista government in Nicaragua as
Marxist.
   ``If you walk like a duck and you quack like a duck and you say
you're a duck, you're a duck,'' he said.
   But so far, the new Bush administration hasn't reported any
conversations with tax ducks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Raum covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
