<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     02-01 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many People Missing out on SSI Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost half of the nation's senior citizens who
may be eligible for Supplemental Security Income benefits are not
enrolled in the program, according to the American Association of
Retired Persons.
   SSI provides monthly cash payments to eligible low-income people
who are 65 years and older, blind or disabled. The maximum federal
SSI benefit this year is $368 a month for an individual and $553 a
month for a couple.
   Some states supplement the payments with their own funds. The
Department of Health and Human Services estimates that 36 percent of
SSI recipients receive state supplements.
   The study, conducted for AARP by ICF Inc., a research and
consulting firm, said its finding was consistent with other surveys
that have put the SSI participation rate at about 50 percent.
   Another study conducted for AARP by Louis Harris and Associates
found that one-third of the eligible older people who are not
receiving SSI benefits have never heard of the program, and many
others are misinformed about eligibility requirements.
   SSI paid about $12.3 billion in federal benefits last fiscal year
and is budgeted to pay out $12.5 billion this year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Tutu Praises Baker</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu says he is impressed
that Secretary of State James A. Baker III appears open-minded to
ideas on pressing South Africa to abolish its system of apartheid.
   ``I don't want to be euphoric, but we certainly have been
impressed,'' said the Nobel Peace Prize winner, who attended a
meeting Tuesday between Baker and a delegation sponsored by the
World Council of Churches.
   Tutu said Baker made no promises, but indicated the new
administration is reviewing its policy toward South Africa.
   Asked to compare his meeting with Baker and past sessions with
former Secretary of State George Shultz, Tutu said, ``I was very
impressed by the fact that he was not dogmatic, he actually was
discussing with the group and was interested in any initiative that
the United States might actively take to pressure the South African
government to the negotiating table.''
   ``They are ... involved in a review process. He did not dismiss
us, he listened to us with very considerable interest,'' Tutu said
after the half-hour session at the State Department.
   Tutu joined a delegation that has been on a three-week tour of
the United States, several West European capitals and Japan to
convince government officials to take a stronger stand against South
Africa's apartheid policy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>FDA Panel Develops Guidelines on Dental X-rays</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Food and Drug Administration panel has set
new guidelines on how often people need dental X-rays, saying its
goal is to eliminate any unneeded radiation exposure.
   Children with healthy teeth may need dental X-rays no more than
once every year or two, and dentally healthy adults once every two
or three years, the panel said.
   The guidelines, reported in the current issue of the Journal of
the American Dental Association, were prompted by concern among some
experts about the frequency of dental X-rays, both overuse and
underuse.
   ``Although the radiation risk from a dental X-ray is extremely
low, our goal is to eliminate any unneeded radiation exposure,'' FDA
Commissioner Frank E. Young said in statement Tuesday.
   ``Until these guidelines were developed, there were few concrete
criteria a dentist could use in deciding when X-rays were needed,''
he said.
   Young also stressed the flexibility of the guidelines, saying,
``These are not hard and fast rules. In deciding whether an X-ray is
needed, the dentist must use clinical judgment in evaluating the
patient's needs.''
</TEXT>
