<FIRST>r a PM-AirTanker-Facts     02-01 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Tanker-Facts,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Facts About the KC-135A</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Air Tanker Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force KC-135A, a modified version of a Boeing 707 that
refuels planes in the air, crashed near Abilene, Texas, killing all
19 aboard. Here are some facts about the KC-135A.
   _ First model flown in 1956.
   _ Powered by four Pratt &amp; Whitney jet engines.
   _ Wingspan, 130 feet, 10 inches.
   _ Length, 136 feet, 3 inches.
   _ Height, 41 feet, 8 inches.
   _ Weight, 98,466 pounds.
   _ Maximum takeoff weight, 297,000 pounds.
   _ Maximum speed, 600 mph.
   _ Range, 1,150 miles while carrying 120,000 pounds of transfer
fuel. Can fly up to 9,200 miles on a ferry mission.
   _ Normally flies at or below 50,000 feet.
   _ Normal crew pilot, co-pilot, navigator, boom operator; able to
carry many more passengers.
   _ Cost, $20.1 million.
   _ Air Force nickname, Stratotanker.
</TEXT>
