<FIRST>r a PM-People-AlanLaddJr     02-01 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Alan Ladd Jr,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alan Ladd Jr. to Head New Movie Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movie producer Alan Ladd Jr., who last year
quit his job as top moviemaker at MGM-UA Communications Co., has
formed a new movie company backed by Italian financier and Hollywood
buff Giancarlo Parretti.
   Ladd, who made his name guiding ``Star Wars'' through 20th
Century Fox when he was president there, will be chairman of the new
Pathe Entertainment Co. The company will produce 14 to 16 movies
during the next four years, he predicted Monday.
   The company apparently takes its name from Pathe France, a big
French movie company that Parretti and associated companies bought
last year.
   Parretti, who heads a partnership that controls 40 percent of
struggling moviemaker Cannon Group Inc., is rumored to be interested
in buying MGM-UA. Investor Kirk Kerkorian, who controls MGM-UA, has
the company up for sale, and has said he prefers to split the firm
and sell an interest in MGM.
   Ladd, son of the late actor and Marjorie Jane Ladd, resigned in
September as chairman of the MGM portion of MGM-UA amid the turmoil
brought on by Kerkorian's attempts to sell parts of the company.
   During his MGM tenure, he was credited with overseeing such
movies as ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' ``Willow,'' and ``Moonstruck.''
   Previously, his The Ladd Co. made two critically favored but
commercially unsuccessful movies, ``The Right Stuff'' and ``Blade
Runner,'' as well as such moneymakers as the ``Police Academy''
series.
</TEXT>
