<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     02-01 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Scores Another Smashing Victory in TV Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC extended its domination of the A.C.
Nielsen Co. ratings to 32 weeks, and ABC dropped from first to third
in the news category.
   NBC's victory for the week that ended Sunday was accomplished
almost entirely with regular series programming. The week before NBC
won big with its coverage of the Super Bowl.
   NBC placed six prime-time shows in the top 10 last week. The
network did not have a single show in the bottom 25. Its only
non-regular show high in the ratings was the second half of the
miniseries ``Brotherhood of the Rose.'' The first part, which
followed the Super Bowl, was ninth the previous week.
   ``The Cosby Show'' on NBC was first, followed by ABC's
``Roseanne''; NBC's ``A Different World''; CBS' ``60 Minutes'';
ABC's ``Who's the Boss?''; NBC's ``Cheers''; CBS' ``Murder, She
Wrote''; and NBC's ``Golden Girls''; ``ALF''; and ``Unsolved
Mysteries.''
   NBC's average prime-time rating for last week was 17.1; CBS' was
13.1 and ABC's was 12.0.
   For the season to date, NBC leads with an average of 15.7 to
ABC's 12.9 and CBS's 12.4.
   Each ratings point represents 904,000 homes with television.
   The ratings for the networks' nightly news shows were close
again, but CBS moved ahead of ABC, last week's winner, which fell to
third place. The ratings: CBS 11.7, NBC 11.6, ABC 11.5.
   ABC's ``Studio 5B'' on Sunday was the lowest-rated show among the
three networks. The five lowest network shows were ABC's
``Incredible Sunday,'' ABC's ``Murphy's Law,'' ABC's ``A Fine
Romance,'' CBS' ``TV 101'' and ABC's ``Studio 5B.''
   Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``America's Most Wanted'' was in 62 place,
placing higher than 10 shows from the networks. Fox's ``21 Jump
Street'' was 71st, which put it just ahead of ABC's ``A Fine
Romance.''
 
</TEXT>
