<FIRST>u a AM-GrandMarshal 1stLd-Writethru a0829 02-01 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grand Marshal, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0829,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman To Lead St. Patrick's Day Parade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts 3rd graf to CORRECT by deleting reference to WEVD, which
no long carries program, now on WNWK-FM.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Broadcaster Dorothy Hayden Cudahy was selected
Tuesday night as grand marshal of the St. Patrick's Day parade, the
first woman chosen to lead the annual march in its 226-year history.
   Mrs. Cudahy was picked by about 600 delegates from the
approximately 200 affiliated organizations that march in the parade,
including the Ancient Order of Hibernians, the United Irish Counties
and schools and fraternal organizations.
   ``It will be in honor of your mother and my mother and all the
Irish women who did so much,'' said Mrs. Cudahy, who is known as the
First Lady of Irish radio for her ``Irish Memories'' program, which
has been broadcast on New York area radio stations for more than 40
years.
   ``This achievement was really your achievement,'' she told the
delegates who crowded into a hotel ballroom in mid-Manhattan.
   A Bank of Ireland executive was elected grand marshal last year,
the third straight year Mrs. Cudahy had lost.
</TEXT>
