<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 0141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Brady-LBOs     02-01 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brady-LBOs,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Reluctantly Supports Cutting Deduction on Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is giving qualified
support to cutting the tax deduction for interest on debt incurred
in leveraged buyouts, saying it prefers fairer tax treatment of
traditional forms of raising capital.
   ``If you're going to make a change _ and clearly we're not
suggesting one _ we would suggest that you look in the area of
perhaps limiting interest deductions and using that money to give a
break to corporate owners of stock,'' Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady told the tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee on Tuesday.
   Brady said the ``driving force'' behind the LBO phenomenon is
that companies can avoid a 34 percent corporate income tax rate by
raising capital through debt rather than stock.
   He said the Treasury Department also has been attempting to find
a way through Internal Revenue Service regulations or a legislative
proposal to make the tax treatment of stock-equity and bond-debt
financing more equal.
   ``The LBO problem would disappear with a level playing field,''
he said. ``But so far we haven't been able to come up with a way to
do it.''
   Brady also suggested that the best action might be inaction.
   ``We have a habit of correcting things just as they are about to
correct themselves,'' Brady said. ``If we wait a little longer, this
thing is not going to gobble us up.''
   But Brady conceded the administration is concerned about the
rapid rate with which companies are going into debt to launch
takeovers or defend against them through stock buybacks _ both often
financed by high-interest junk bonds.
   Rep. J.J. Pickle, D-Texas, likened Brady's qualified endorsement
of taxing interest on takeover-related debt to ``a kiss through a
veil'' and criticized him for not coming up with specific
suggestions or data on the impact of the buyouts on the federal
treasury.
   With a ``that depends'' answer, Brady evaded a question on
whether President Bush's desire to reduce the capital gains tax
would only encourage more buyouts since shareholders would have to
pay less tax on the 35 percent to 45 percent above-market prices
they often get in the transactions.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said it is ironic the outcry for
congressional action to curb takeovers ``has become deafening'' in
the past 16 months.
   In 1987 the House had approved similar legislation to limit the
tax deductibility of interest on junk bonds and other borrowing used
in financing takeovers.
   But it suffered a quick death in negotiations with the Senate
after then-Treasury Secretary and now Secretary of State James A.
Baker tried to blame the bill as the cause of the October 1987 stock
market crash.
   Since then, the size of companies being taken over through junk
bonds has increased several times. And instead of just plants
closing and workers losing jobs, owners of more traditional
long-term, investment-grade bonds in the companies being acquired
have seen the value of their holdings diminished in some takeovers.
   For example, holders of some $5 billion in long-term bonds in
RJR-Nabisco Co., lost $1 billion overnight when credit agencies
downgraded their rating upon the announcement of the company's
takeover by LBO specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   Rostenkowski and other lawmakers also have questioned whether
many of the newly restructured companies will be able to make the
interest payments on their much higher debt and avoid bankruptcy if
and when a recession occurs.
   ``I have a feeling that we're looking at a Richter scale that's
showing zero and then we have an eruption of 7 or 8 on the scale and
it's too late,'' said Rep. Thomas J. Downey, D-N.Y., using a major
earthquake as a metaphor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
