<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PrairieFire     02-01 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prairie Fire,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prairie Fire Burns Thousands of Panhandle Acres</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGORA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranchers armed with blankets and shovels
helped more than 100 firefighters battle a prairie fire that raced
through the Panhandle Tuesday, consuming 8,000 acres of grassland,
farm buildings and at least one home.
   Firefighters said a 25-foot wall of flames was fueled by winds
gusting in excess of 45 mph as it made its way across Morrill and
Garden counties for more than eight hours into Tuesday night.
   No injuries were reported. Some hot spots were still burning late
Tuesday night, but authorities said the fire was under control by
about 8:30 p.m.
   Ken Loxterkamp, Broadwater's assistant fire chief, said minimal
damage was reported because few buildings exist in the area.
   ``This is all ranch country. It's all grassland. It burned up
into some of the yards. In one place there were two houses in the
same area. They saved the one house but lost the other,'' Loxterkamp
said.
   He said more than 100 firefighters were at the scene at one time.
   Cyndi Messersmith of the Alliance Fire Department said the fire
started east of Angora about noon and burned more than 8,000 acres.
   Most of the damage to farm buildings, including the burned house,
was reported north of Bridgeport, about 25 miles south of Alliance.
   Al Kosel of the National Weather Service in Scottsbluff said
winds across the Panhandle gusted at up to 47 mph Tuesday afternoon.
He said conditions had been very dry in the area.
   ``We had only a trace of precipitation all month,'' he said.
</TEXT>
