<FIRST>r w PM-Wright-Baker     02-01 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Baker,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House, Wright Reach Accord on Timely Notification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House will put off legislation tightening
congressional control over covert intelligence actions and instead
rely on the Bush administration's good faith to keep lawmakers
informed about such activity, says Speaker Jim Wright.
   Wright made the offer Tuesday to Bush's new secretary of state,
James A. Baker III, at a meeting designed to open doors to the
administration and lay the groundwork for bipartisan cooperation on
foreign policy.
   In return, Wright said Baker promised him that the administration
``will abide by the letter and the spirit of the law'' that requires
the president to give Congress timely notice of planned covert
actions overseas.
   That law has been a sore point in congressional-administration
relations, especially since the Iran-Contra affair, when President
Reagan failed for more than 10 months to tell Congress about arms
sales to Iran designed to win freedom for American hostages.
   ``It was the intent of Congress that `timely' should mean hours,
or days at most, not weeks or months,'' Wright said.
   Legislation that grew out of Congress' Iran-Contra investigation
was introduced last year to erase the law's ambiguity over what
constitutes ``timely'' notice by placing a firm 48-hour notification
requirement on the president.
   The bill's primary sponsor, Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said he
had no problem with Wright's pledge so long as the White House
voluntarily honors the 48-hour standard in all but the most extreme
circumstances where notice is impossible.
   The Senate passed the measure last year, but it was pulled from
the House calendar late in the year after Wright ran into
accusations that he had improperly publicly disclosed a covert CIA
operation in Nicaragua.
   A House ethics committee inquiry into Wright's conduct remains
open.
   ``There is no point in opening old wounds if we can start afresh
and act on a mutual assumption of good faith,'' Wright told
reporters.
   Wright also set up a bipartisan task force to meet with Baker and
arrange regular consultation between the administration and Congress
on foreign policy matters, trying to head off the confrontations
that dogged relations between Capitol Hill and the Reagan White
House.
   The task force he created includes House Majority Leader Tom
Foley, D-Wash., Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman Dante Fascell,
D-Fla., Judiciary Committee Chairman Jack Brooks, D-Texas, and
Intelligence Committee Chairman Anthony Beilenson, D-Calif.
Republican members are to be appointed by House Minority Leader
Robert Michel, R-Ill.
   Their job will be to meet with Baker periodically to find ways to
build trust and overcome longstanding disputes with the executive
branch, including the circumstances under which U.S. military forces
will be deployed and the notification issue in covert operations
cases, Wright said.
   He said Baker is seeking a mechanism by which the two branches
can work out diputes over the War Powers Act and avoid the
constitutional collision over congressional and White House
authority that can occur when the president deploys U.S. troops.
   ``We've begun a process which may be constructive,'' Wright said,
one which he hopes will ``reduce the level of confrontation that has
sometimes marred our relationships in the past couple of years.''
</TEXT>
