<FIRST>r w PM-Soviets-Loans Bjt   02-01 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviets-Loans, Bjt,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Book: Soviets Use Western Money to Avoid Dealing with Problems at
Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is trying to finance its
reforms with loans from the West while postponing tough decisions
needed at home to curb its budget deficit, says the author of a new
book on the Soviet economy.
   Author Judy Shelton has joined a chorus of skeptics, including
many on Capitol Hill, who worry that Western banks and governments
are extending credits to the Kremlin without reviewing the strategic
implications.
   Shelton's new book, ``The Coming Soviet Crash: Gorbachev's
Desperate Pursuit of Credit in Western Financial Markets,'' includes
a detailed analysis of published Soviet budget data.
   She concluded that Kremlin accountants have been fudging the
country's economic figures for years, steadily reporting budget
surpluses when in fact there were growing deficits. The Soviets
finally admitted to a budget deficit last October.
   The foremost spokesman in Congress on the issue, Sen. Bill
Bradley, D-N.J., has cautioned that giving the Kremlin easy credits
could undercut U.S. interests and harm rather than help the reforms
of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Nevertheless, said Shelton, under Gorbachev the Soviets have
turned increasingly to the West for financing.
   As part of the reforms, the Soviets are publishing many
previously secret economic statistics, but Shelton and others
question the data.
   One respected Soviet economist, for example, has said the deficit
is three times higher than the Kremlin has acknowledged.
   Last August, in a prospectus for its first foreign bond issue,
the Soviet government said it had a budget surplus, putting the
figure at 3 billion rubles, or $1.8 billion.
   ``It was revealed three months later that the Soviets had been
running a deficit for years,'' Shelton said. The revelation, she
said, did not prompt a protest from the Swiss bank that sponsored
the loan or from those who bought the issue.
   The continued cloudiness of Soviet financial figures does not
augur well for the West as the Soviets seek to join such Western
financial institutions as the International Monetary Fund, World
Bank and the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs, which require
``transparent'' reporting in which no numbers are hidden, Shelton
said.
   ``Gorbachev's onslaught of financial maneuvers seems to have left
the United States dazed,'' sh wrote.
   Although the Soviet Union has increased its international
borrowing, the credits do not come close to covering the deficit,
meaning that the Kremlin has simply printed more money to cover the
gap.
   Prices remain under government control, however, disguising or at
least postponing an inflationary spiral.
   And, Shelton said in a Capitol Hill presentation this week,
Gorbachev has not taken one of the major promised steps of his
``perestroika'' campaign to restructure the Soviet economy, a price
reform that would eliminate subsidies on many commodities.
   For the West, the greatest concern is that the Soviets are
borrowing money abroad while postponing tough political decisions at
home.
   ``The correlation between Gorbachev's reign in the Kremlin and
the escalation of Soviet borrowing activities in Western financial
markets is striking,'' wrote Shelton, a researcher at the Hoover
Institution of Stanford University.
   ``Within two years after Gorbachev took power in March 1985,
Soviet debt to the West shot up from about $25 billion to over $37
billion, an increase of 50 percent,'' she wrote.
   Bradley, in a New York Times column on Jan. 6, cautioned that
``the notion that Western governments can help Mr. Gorbachev through
cheap credit is ... flawed.''
   ``Reform means making tough choices _ butter not weapons,
efficiency not useless output, consumption not forced saving. The
real reformers know this. They also know it means higher prices,
less job security and harder work today in exchange for the promise
of a better life tomorrow,'' Bradley said.
   Continuing shortages of basic goods and revelations about the
Soviet budget deficit have tempered optimism about that better life.
   Soviet Finance Minister Boris I. Gostev last October estimated
the budget deficit at 35 billion rubles, about $58 billion at
current exchange rates.
   Another well-known Soviet economist, Leonid Abalkin, last week
said that the actual deficit was nearly three times Gostev's
estimate, about $165 billion, or 11 percent of the gross national
product. By comparison, the U.S. government deficit runs at about 4
percent of GNP.
   Other Soviet officials have been more optimistic. Mikhail
Korolev, chairman of the State Committee for Statistics, wrote in
Pravda on Monday that the GNP grew 5 percent last year and was 13.3
percent higher than in 1985.
   The government announced this month that Soviet GNP in 1988
totaled 866 billion rubles, or $1.4 trillion. That was less than
half of the 1985 U.S. GNP of $3.8 trillion.
</TEXT>
