<FIRST>r a BC-Dance     02-01 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feld Ballet Opens With Minimalist Premier</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American ballet premier, scheduled for the
third night of the Feld Ballet's Jan. 31 to March 12 season, was
pushed up to opening night because of an injury to a dancer.
   So the Joyce Theater audience on Tuesday saw ``Petipa
Notwithstanding,'' choreographed by Eliot Feld to composer Terry
Riley's 1964 ``In C.''
   The minimalist music set the dancers to relentless motion and had
a physical effect on this viewer, too. The throat closed and nails
were chewed. Stages of viewing went from admiration for the dancers'
skill and stamina to a wish for it to end.
   The dancers, in white leotards with black lines and dots, didn't
look like people. To a steady 4-4 beat, they began moving across the
stage, heads dangling forward like rag dolls. The music changed to
clang-clang, first heard over bells then over a drone, and the
dancers reached up and out, to draw air toward themselves, like
robots on a fantasy assembly line.
   The choreography followed the music. When the beat was fast, the
dancers were frantic. But even when the men were jumping up in
unison and scrabbling under their armpits, there was something
static about the whole thing.
   Marius Petipa, choreographer of ``The Sleeping Beauty,''
mentioned in the title, is considered the originator of classical
ballet.
   Arts need to move forward and modern music must surely inspire
choreographers in new directions. This viewer, who found ``Petipa
Notwithstanding'' neither attractive nor exciting, isn't
appreciating this new direction yet.
   Thomas Lemanski, one of six dancers scheduled for ``Intermezzo
No. 1,'' sustained a lower back injury, causing that dance to be
replaced.
   The evening began with Feld's 1970 ``The Consort.'' It begins in
a courtly way and moves into earthier peasant fare. The women tuck
up their skirts. The men change fitted jackets for homespun and toss
the women in the air and down in a dance that becomes quite sexy
just before the curtain falls. It ended with Feld's 1986 ``Skara
Brae'' set to traditional Scottish, Irish and Breton airs.
   Following its season at the Joyce Theater, the Feld Ballet
company will perform in Providence, R.I.; Storrs, Conn.; Hempstead,
N.Y.; Lyndon, Vt.; Durham, N.H; Orono, Maine; Easton, Pa., and San
Diego.
   Next summer's performance sites include Athens, Greece.
</TEXT>
