<FIRST>r w PM-US-Afghanistan     02-01 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Afghanistan,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Expects Rebels to Lay Siege to Kabul After Soviets Withdraw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels are likely to lay siege to Kabul
after the last Soviet troops quit Afghanistan and could bring the
pro-Moscow government down within weeks, a State Department official
says.
   The ``choke 'em'' tactics are designed to force the city's
defenders to surrender or to defect once their Soviet military
support is gone, the official said Tuesday.
   In the past few weeks, the Soviets have bombed rebel positions
throughout the country, partly in an attempt to keep the Mujahedeen
dispersed and to protect a continuing convoy of food and fuel
supplies to Kabul.
   ``When the last Soviet soldier steps across the border they know
in their heart of hearts it's going to unravel,'' said the official,
who spoke only on condition he would not be identified.
   Kabul, already burdened by more than 1 million refugees from the
provinces, has only enough fuel and food to last for a few days, the
official said.
   The rebels, who will continue to receive U.S. arms through
Pakistan, plan to keep ``tightening the noose'' around Kabul and
other urban centers, using a ``siege magnified'' strategy, the
official said..
   The aim is to try to persuade the city's defenders to surrender
or to defect, but many of them are ``of the hard-core type,''
including members of the Afghan secret police, and will stay and
fight because there is little chance of amnesty, the official said.
   ``So it will be difficult,'' he said. ``The crystal ball is
murky. At one time we were talking of them lasting 6 to 12 months,
and then 3 to 6 months. Estimates vary. But it's going to be sooner
rather than later.
   ``If that strangle effect works, and I see no reason why it
should not, the government could unravel very quickly, in a matter
of weeks, not months.''
   The Soviet troops are departing under a Feb. 15 deadline set in
the Geneva accords of last April. The State Department on Monday
accused the Soviets of engaging in a ``scorched earth policy'' of
bombing rebel positions as the Red Army exits.
   The official said the Soviets claim to be retaliating for a rebel
blockade of food and fuel convoys, but were bombing positions as far
away as 30 miles to the east of the main supply route.
   ``So far as we can tell, the resistance has been fairly
restrained about interfering with supplies,'' he said. ``There has
been some interdiction, but not to the extent that the Soviets
suggest.''
   However, the official said, ``the interference is going to grow
if they don't quit this stupidity.''
   He said one aim of the bombing, missile and artillery attacks is
to punish Ahmed Shah Massoud, a rebel leader in the Panjsher Valley
east of Kabul, who has refused to promise not to interdict food and
fuel shipments to the capital.
   Most of the Mujahedeen leaders agreed last November under U.S.
pressure to permit the Soviets to depart without interference.
   ``By taking this bombing action, the Soviets run the risk of the
resistance not letting them withdraw more or less in peace,'' the
official said.
   With tensions rising, the U.S. embassy in Kabul closed on Monday
and the remaining diplomats and security guards were flown out of
the country.
   One reason, he said, was to prevent Afghan officials from seeking
asylum there as political refugees. On the other hand, the State
Department and the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service are
consider an application from former Deputy Foreign Minister Abdul
Ghaffar Lakanwal, who defected last November on a trip to New York.
   Last week, the official said, the State Department sent a formal
note to U.S. embassies in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia
instructing them to deny visas to anyone attached to the pro-Moscow
government of President Najibullah.
</TEXT>
