<FIRST>r w PM-Baker-Europe     02-01 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Europe,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker to Visit NATO Ministers This Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is
planning a fast-paced swing to possibly more than a dozen NATO
capitals this month in an attempt to strengthen contacts in the
beleaguered alliance.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman described the tour on
Tuesday as as ``a very complicated arrangement'' that could take the
new secretary to 14 cities in five days.
   It would be Baker's debut tour abroad as President Bush's chief
adviser on foreign affairs.
   The visit comes as tensions are rising within the alliance on
developing a response to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
disarmament overtures and the military cutbacks announced by his
Warsaw Pact allies.
   Another major issue is the dispute over the U.S. contribution to
the alliance and pressure for Europeans members to pick up more of
their own defense costs.
   Recent surveys have shown Gorbachev's so-called ``charm
offensive'' to be highly effective in Western Europe, with fewer
citizens there viewing the 40-year-old alliance as necessary in
light of the Soviet leader's public relations offensive.
   Redman said Baker intends to meet with ``as many of his NATO
colleagues as possible'' and wants to do so in each of the foreign
minister's home capitals because the new secretary attaches a very
high priority to the sessions.
   Redman noted that Baker is scheduled to accompany President Bush
to Canada for a day-long meeting on Feb. 10, as well as to Japan for
the Feb. 24 funeral of Emperor Hirohito and the one-day visits that
weekend to China and Korea.
   Baker intends to sandwich the European tour between the Canada
and Far East swing, the spokesman said.
   The alliance is composed of Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France,
West Germany, Greece, Iceland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands,
Norway, Portugal, Spain, Turkey, the United Kingdom and the United
States.
</TEXT>
