<FIRST>r a PM-AirTanker-Sawyer     02-01 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Tanker-Sawyer,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Crash Is Third Involving Michigan Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Air Tanker Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GWINN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families gathered in a chapel at K.I. Sawyer
Air Force Base after learning of the crash of a KC-135A tanker plane
in Texas, the third air accident in four months involving Sawyer
personnel.
   Of the 19 people who died in Tuesday's crash at Dyess Air Force
Base near Abilene, seven were crew members from Sawyer, 10 were
passengers from Sawyer and two were passengers from Dyess,
authorities said.
   Names were withheld pending notification of families.
   The news hit hard at Sawyer, a small northern Michigan base where
nearly 1,900 families live.
   ``We're a very small, tight-knit community,'' said a base
spokeswoman, Anita Bailey. ``Part of the anxiety is knowing that
these are the people you trained with, went to school with, and work
with.''
   ``It's pretty quiet here. The mood is not good,'' Michelle Clark
said from the Sawyer NCO Club, where she works. ``They've got the
news on in the back, and everyone is sitting back there, just
watching and listening and not talking.''
   ``I think everyone's going to know somebody who was on that
plane,'' said Clark, whose husband is stationed at Sawyer. ``My
husband wanted to go on that mission. Now I'm glad he wasn't
picked.''
   Sawyer personnel have been involved in two other crashes,
including the explosive crash of another KC-135 trying to land at
Paul B. Wurtsmith Air Force Base near Oscoda on Oct. 11.
   Six Wurtsmith crew members died in that crash. Ten Sawyer
personnel aboard were able to leap clear of the burning plane. The
tanker had been ferrying Sawyer personnel to Wurtsmith so they could
inspect the base's nuclear facilities.
   The Air Force's Strategic Air Command has completed its
investigation of that crash, but the report is not ready for public
release, said Major Ken St. John, a SAC spokesman at Barksdale Air
Force Base in Shreveport, La.
   On Dec. 6, a B-52 bomber burst into flames as its crew attempted
touch-and-go landings on Sawyer's main runway. All eight Sawyer
airmen survived.
   The Air Force report on that crash also remains unavailable,
although Sawyer personnel have since been ordered to watch for
overheating fuel pumps in B-52s.
</TEXT>
