<SECOND>PM-Hearst-Lewis,0129</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0409 to fix numbering.</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP Washington Bureau Chief Moves To Hearst</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles J. Lewis, Washington bureau chief for The
Associated Press, has been named head of the Hearst Newspapers
bureau in the nation's capital, effective March 1.
   In a 14-year career with the AP, Lewis, 48, has also served in
executive positions in Hartford, Conn., Los Angeles and New York.
   He succeeds Robert E. Thompson as Hearst bureau chief in
Washington. Thompson, who is retiring, will continue an affiliation
as a columnist for the Hearst bureau.
   The announcement was made Tuesday by Frank A. Bennack Jr.,
president and chief executive officer of The Hearst Corporation, and
Robert J. Danzig, vice president and general manager of the Hearst
Newspapers.
