<FIRST>r i PM-AssaultRifles     02-01 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Assault Rifles,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0413 to fix numbering.</HEAD>
<HEAD>British Government Offers To Buy AK-47s, Which Become Illegal Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is offering to buy Kalashnikov
assault rifles and other high-powered guns that become illegal today
under a new firearms law.
   Owners have until April 30 to apply for the $265 payment, Home
Secretary Douglas Hurd said Tuesday. The sum is based on the price
such rifles fetched at auction before parliament took up the measure
in September 1987.
   Under the new law, the penalty for possessing a prohibited weapon
is up to five years in jail or a $3,500 fine.
   The Firearms (Amendment) Act was introduced after Michael Ryan
killed 16 people as he strolled through the small town of Hungerford
in August 1987 before taking his own life. It bans the private use
of high-powered self-loading rifles like the Kalashnikov, which Ryan
used in the massacre, and other weapons including short-barreled,
smooth-bore guns.
   Fully automatic weapons are already prohibited in Britain.
   The government payment applies to owners who acquired the newly
banned weapons before September 23, 1987.
   Calls in the United States for greater restrictions on the sale
of semi-automatic weapons have increased since last month's
shootings in a Stockton, Calif., elementary school yard.
   Patrick Purdy killed five children and wounded 30 people with a
Kalashnikov AK-47 assault rifle before ending his own life, police
say.
</TEXT>
