<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Press Institute is urging the
Peruvian government to investigate the murder of a journalist and do
more to safeguard other threatened members of the press.
   The respected London-based organization, in a message to
President Alan Garcia Perez on Tuesday, called violence against
journalists a ``gross violation'' of their right to work.
   The institute's director, Peter Galliner, wrote that the
institute is ``extremely concerned'' at the lack of any
investigation into the murder of Hugo Bustios, 34, a local
correspondent for the Lima news magazine Caretas.
   Bustios and another journalist, 27-year-old Eduardo Rojas, were
shot by gunmen in November while traveling by motorcycle on the
outskirts of the Peruvian city of Huanta. Rojas was seriously
wounded.
   ``Furthermore, we deplore the recent increase in violence against
journalists in general,'' the message says.
   ``Whilst we are aware of the current complex situation in Peru,
we would remind you that such attacks are a gross violation of the
right of journalists to gather information and the right of people
everywhere to receive information,'' it says.
   ``We strongly urge an immediate and rigorous enquiry into the
murder of the Caretas' correspondent and that your government acts
at once to ensure that journalists may pursue their work without
interference or fear of their physical safety,'' it says.
   Peruvian officials said they had not determined whether Bustios'
murder was carried out by the Shining Path insurgency, a
Mao-inspired group which has been fighting to overthrow the
government for eight years, or a new anti-rebel death squad called
the Rodigo Franco Command.
   Both groups have threatened journalists in and around Ayacucho,
the birthplace of the Shining Path, 30 miles south of Huanta.
