<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg     02-01 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Will Appeal Manslaughter Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg will appeal his manslaughter
conviction by arguing that the judge in the child-killing case was
prejudiced from the start, an attorney said.
   Attorney Ira London said Tuesday he remembered that state Judge
Harold Rothwax predicted at a pretrial bail hearing that Steinberg
was ``probably guilty, probably would be found guilty and probably
would be sentenced to life in prison.''
   London said Rothwax used prejudicial rulings and inflammatory
evidence to coax the jury toward a conviction on a more serious
charge so he would not seem wrong.
   ``After all,'' London said, ``if there were a second-degree
manslaughter conviction here, it certainly would have made his
earlier opinion look foolish.''
   Steinberg, 47, was convicted of first-degree manslaughter Monday
in the death of Lisa Steinberg, the 6-year-old girl he illegally
adopted at birth.
   London said Rothwax prejudiced the case by repeatedly letting the
jury view a videotape of a seriously beaten Hedda Nussbaum, the
defendant's former live-in companion, and by his instructions to the
jury regarding the definition of intent.
   ``There is no question in my mind from the length of the
deliberations and from talking to the jurors ... that Joel got a
fair shake from the jurors,'' London said at his Brooklyn office.
But ``it is a serious issue whether Joel got a fair trial because of
the judge's rulings.''
   London said neither he nor his co-counsel at the trial, Adrian
DiLuzio, had spoken to Steinberg since the verdict.
   ``We're going to have to make a provision for him to be kept in
protective custody in upstate New York assuming he gets a serious
jail sentence, and I would anticipate that happening,'' London said.
   But he said Steinberg is not afraid. ``Joel is not a fearing
person,'' London said. ``He's been able to handle himself in a safe
way at Rikers Island (jail). Rikers Island has not been without
incident, but he's done OK there.''
   Also Tuesday, Ms. Nussbaum's attorneys, Barry Scheck and Betty
Levinson, said their client was ``relieved and gratified'' that
Steinberg had been convicted and ``will now try to make herself into
a useful person.''
   Scheck said Ms. Nussbaum will remain at the Four Winds
psychiatric facility in Katonah, N.Y., for a while.
   Ms. Levinson, Ms. Nussbaum's civil attorney, noted that she had
filed a multimillion-dollar lawsuit against Steinberg ``basically
for the destruction of her life.''
   ``She needs the wherewithal to put her life together again,'' Ms.
Levinson said, ``and that includes financial ability.''
</TEXT>
