<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Pardons     02-01 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Pardons,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 400 Prisoners Pardoned on Revolution Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has pardoned 423 prisoners and
commuted the prison terms of another 50 under an amnesty issued for
the 10th anniversary of the Islamic Revolution, the Iranian
government said today.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said those pardoned
have been released in the past two days.
   It said amnesty for other prisoners is expected to be issued
during the 10-day celebrations that began today, the anniversary of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's return to Iran from exile in 1979.
   The brief report, monitored in Nicosia, did not give any other
details.
   IRNA reported last week that Khomeini would pardon prisoners on
the national holiday that marks the overthrow of the Iranian
monarchy by the Islamic Revolution.
   It said Iran would also suspend executions of prisoners sentenced
to death during the 10 days.
   At least 132 alleged drug traffickers have been executed this
month in Iran. Another five men, all of them Afghan nationals, were
executed Tuesday after they were convicted of armed robberies and
rape.
   More than 1,500 people have been arrested in a nationwide
anti-narcotics campaign. A law passed in early December mandates the
death penalty for anyone found in the possession of even small
qunatities of drugs.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights group, on
Monday appealed to the world to put pressure on the Khomeini regime
to halt what it called a campaign of political executions.
   Amnesty said about 1,000 political prisoners have been executed
in the past six months.
</TEXT>
