<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-01 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Big Chill Heads South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The arctic air that gave Alaska a record cold wave headed south
across the Plains and Mississippi Valley today, dropping
temperatures to 20 below zero, as blizzards buffeted the northern
Plains.
   In contrast, sections of the country ahead of the cold front that
heralded the cold-air mass enjoyed continued warm weather.
   By early today, the cold air had reached as far south as Kansas
and Missouri. Temperatures were 10 to 20 degrees below zero in North
Dakota, Minnesota, Montana and Wyoming, and winds produced wind
chills of 50 to 60 below in the Dakotas and Montana.
   The drop in temperatures was dramatic. Valentine, Neb., had a
record high of 70 degrees Tuesday before the mercury plunged to zero
in 10 hours. The temperature dropped 33 degrees in just one hour
after the front passed through town.
   In addition to the cold, blizzards hit northwest Minnesota,
southeast North Dakota and southern Montana. Cut Bank, Mont., had 5
inches of snow and Helena, Mont., received 4. Blowing, drifting snow
dropped visibilities to almost zero in parts of Montana and
Minnesota.
   Snow also fell in Washington state. Snohomish had 5 inches of
snow, Spokane got 4 to 5, Everett had 4 and over a foot of snow was
considered possible in the Cascade Mountains. In Bellingham, winds
gusted to 60 mph.
   Unseasonably warm weather continued south of the cold air, with
temperatures in the 50s and 60s from the southern Plains to the Ohio
Valley and the middle and southern Atlantic Coast. It was 55 degrees
in Buffalo, N.Y., early today, topping the record high for the date
set in 1988 by 1 degree. Grand Rapids, Mich., reported a
record-tying 51 degrees. On Tuesday, high-temperature records were
broken or tied in 64 cities.
   Today's forecast called for snow from much of the Pacific
Northwest to the northern and central Rockies, the Dakotas and
Nebraska; snow showers in northern New England and parts of the
upper Great Lakes; rain along the central Pacific Coast; and strong,
gusty winds over the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were expected to be almost 25 below zero in
north central Montana, nearly 10 below zero in North Dakota and near
zero in northwest Minnesota; in the single digits and teens in upper
Michigan, much of Wisconsin, the upper Misssissippi Valley, the
northern Plains and the northern Rockies; the 20s and 30s in
northern New England, lower Michigan, the rest of Iowa, the central
Rockies and the northern Pacific Coast; the 40s and 50s from the
central Pacific Coast to the southern Rockies, Missouri, Kansas,
Ohio, the northern Appalachians, northern New Jersey and central New
England; the 80s in central and southern Florida and much of Texas
and Louisiana; and in the 60s and 70s in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 21
degrees below zero at Havre, Mont., to 70 degrees at Key West Naval
Air Station, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 49 fair; Boston 46 cloudy; Buffalo 55 windy;
Charleston, S.C. 49 fair; Cincinnati 51 fair; Cleveland 53 windy;
Detroit 46 fair; Miami 63 foggy; New York 42 fair; Philadelphia 38
fair; Pittsburgh 51 fair; Portland, Maine 42 cloudy; Washington 43
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 11 snow; Chicago 48 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 65
partly cloudy; Denver 18 snow; Des Moines 25 cloudy; Indianapolis 54
fair; Kansas City 35 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 14 snow; Nashville
54 fair; New Orleans 68 partly cloudy; St. Louis 56 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 35 fair; Anchorage 2 fair; Las Vegas 45 partly
cloudy; Los Angeles 52 foggy; Phoenix 59 partly cloudy; Salt Lake
City 44 windy; San Diego 50 fair; San Francisco 49 cloudy; Seattle
30 snow.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 cloudy; Toronto 45 fair.
</TEXT>
