<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-01 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mostly higher in light, early
European trading today, and its strength pushed down gold prices,
currency and bullion dealers said.
   European currency dealers attributed the dollar's rise to
comments by U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan on
Tuesday that current exchange rates were tolerable.
   They predicted little movement until finance ministers and
central bankers of the Group of Seven industrialized nations meet in
Washington later this week.
   ``At the moment, the dollar is trading in a very narrow range,''
said a dealer at a large German bank in Frankfurt. ``I see it moving
higher very, very slowly.''
   Dealers in Milan, Italy, said the market also appeared confident
that President Bush would act to reduce the U.S. deficit.
   ``This is honeymoon time for Bush and that's certainly helping
the dollar,'' said one trader at a major European commercial bank in
Milan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar surged 1.27 yen to a closing 130.40. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 130.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8719 West German marks, up from 1.8710
   _1.5952 Swiss francs, down from 1.5985
   _6.3720 French francs, up from 6.3580
   _2.1154 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1100
   _1,370.75 Italian lire, up from 1,365.00
   _1.1840 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, one British pound cost 1.7475 dollars, cheaper for
buyers than 1.7535 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $390.20 a troy ounce,
down from $394.25 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $392.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $391.75, down from $394.20 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.25 to close at a bid $392.30.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.81 a troy ounce,
down from Tuesday's $5.85.
</TEXT>
