<FIRST>r a PM-AlaskaCold     02-01 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska Cold,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Slowly Emerges from The Cold</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slowly, gingerly, benumbed Alaskans
emerged from their shuttered homes and shops as a mass of bitterly
cold air that broke temperature records blew southward into Canada
and the lower 48 states today.
   With the icy weather went high winds that raked much of the state
earlier in the week, resulting in at least one death. On Tuesday,
the body of a man whose skiff was swamped by high seas and strong
winds off the coast of southeast Alaska was found on a beach.
   Anchorage, helped by sunny skies, recorded a toasty high of minus
2 degrees, substantially above the double-digit, sub-zero lows that
plagued Alaska's largest city during the two-week cold snap.
   Joe Inderbitzen, the owner of Alaska Cab, said his drivers still
were scrambling to keep up with a nonstop demand for rides, but the
destinations changed a bit with the warmer weather Tuesday night.
   ``People are starting to go out a little more,'' Inderbitzen
said. ``They're going to the bars and the restaurants a little more.
I noticed it tonight.''
   Business also was getting back to normal in Valdez, North
America's northernmost ice-free harbor, where winds gusting to 93
mph had shut down the trans-Alaska oil pipeline terminal and caused
officials to reduce the flow of oil from the North Slope by 65
percent.
   Tankers, banned earlier from the harbor because the wind made the
Valdez Narrows dangerous, were allowed to pick up loads at the
terminal Tuesday and flow in the pipeline was expected to increase
to normal levels of more than 2 million barrels daily, said Alyeska
Pipeline Service Co. spokesman Tom Brennan. The National Weather
Service said temperatures in much of Alaska would moderate toward
the end of the week, but remain well below normal for this time of
year.
   The arctic air lingered over Alaska for more than a week, locked
in place by a warm-air jet stream that blew more northerly than
usual, the weather service said. When the jet stream shifted south,
the icy mass broke free, sending balmy temperatures plunging in
Canada, the northern Plains and the Midwest.
   Eagle Village Store owner Frank Robbins said residents in that
tiny Yukon River village 360 miles northeast of Anchorage were
taking the cold in stride.
   ``Most of the people are accustomed to this,'' he said. ``Our
average temperature for this time of year is 25 or 30 below. It's
not that bad. We haven't had any cold weather like this in six
years. But it used to be pretty normal.''
   Major hospitals in the state reported only minor increases in
emergency-room cases related to the cold.
   Most of the frostbite victims who went to the Fairbanks Memorial
Hospital emergency room in recent weeks were adults who had to walk
in the cold after their cars quit running, said Susan McLane, a
nursing supervisor.
   The victim of the boating accident was identified as 35-year-old
Scott St. Clair. A companion who was in another skiff told the Coast
Guard that St. Clair was caught in 10- to 15-foot seas and 55 mph
winds Monday evening.
   In Anchorage, firefighters remained busier than usual responding
to reports of water-spewing pipes that broke with the cold, and a
surge in residential fires, many traced to attempts to thaw frozen
pipes.
</TEXT>
