<FIRST>r a PM-LukensProbe     02-01 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lukens Probe,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor to Consider Allegations Against Congressman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A county prosecutor said he'll review a
police investigation involving U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens which a
television station says dealt with the congressman's alleged
involvement with a teen-age girl.
   Franklin County Prosecutor Michael Miller confirmed that Lukens,
R-Ohio, was under investigation. Miller told Columbus television
station WBNS-TV the investigation was sexual in nature but would not
elaborate.
   ``As things stand now, the finalized report should be on my desk
late (this) morning,'' Miller told The Associated Press on Tuesday
night. ``We'll go through it, look at some things and decide what
action to take.''
   Miller said it would probably take a week to review the report.
   ``Until then, I wouldn't want to speculate further,'' he said.
   Lukens, reached at his Washington home by The Associated Press
Tuesday night, said, ``I have no comment.''
   WBNS-TV quoted a Columbus woman, Annie Coffman, as saying Lukens
has been involved with her teen-age daughter over a period of years,
beginning when she was 13. The girl is now 17, the station said.
   The station reported that Ms. Coffman wore a hidden microphone
when she confronted Lukens at a fast-food restaurant in Columbus
last November. She said Lukens admitted being with her daughter and
other girls, according to the report. Police have heard a tape of
the conversation but would not comment on its contents, the station
reported.
   The woman claims Lukens offered her a government job as a bribe,
the station reported.
   Ms. Coffman said she would not discuss the case.
   ``My daughter has been through enough. She's feeling a lot of
pressure right now,'' Ms. Coffman told The Columbus Dispatch in a
story published today.
   Lukens served two terms in Congress, beginning in 1966. His
district was eliminated in 1970, and he lost a 1970 bid for governor
in the Republican primary. Lukens is from Middletown, about 35 miles
north of Cincinnati.
   After that race, he was barred from seeking public office for
five years for not filing campaign reports on time. However, that
campaign law was changed before the five-year period expired and he
was elected to the state Senate in 1974.
   He served in the state Senate until he returned to Congress in
1986, representing the 8th Congressional District in southwestern
Ohio. He was re-elected in 1988.
   In 1974, while in the state Senate, he fought allegations that he
accepted $1,000 in campaign contributions from Korean businessman
Tongsun Park during his first stint on Capitol Hill.
   He denied the charge, presenting the results of a voluntary lie
detector test he took after the allegations surfaced. Those results
indicated Lukens was not lying when he said he had not received a
campaign contribution from Park.
   Park told investigators he had contributed $850,000 in
contributions to selected congressmen in the late 1960s and early
1970s, but denied repeatedly that he was acting as an agent of the
South Korean government.
</TEXT>
