<DOCNO> AP890201-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 0646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Rebels     02-01 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>43 Killed After Moslem Rebels Attack Village</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops killed at least 32 Moslem
rebels in their biggest battle with the insurgents since 1986, the
army said today. The guerrillas had attacked a remote village in the
southern Philippines.
   Field reports radioed to army's headquarters in Manila said at
least 11 other people _ eight civilians, two militiamen and a
soldier _ were killed in Tuesday's fighting.
   The casualties brought to at least 62 the number of people killed
in fighting in Mindanao island's Zamboanga Peninsula since Saturday.
   Military officials said 18 communist New People's Army guerrillas
and one soldier were killed in six battles Saturday and Sunday in
Zamboanga del Sur and Zamboanga del Norte provinces.
   The area has a mixed Moslem and Christian population and is
roamed not only by rebels but also by bands of outlaws.
   Col. Antonio Nale, a brigade commander who led the government
troops, said the daylong battle began after about 300 rebels
attacked the village of Kulasian in Zamboanga del Sur, 510 miles
southeast of the capital, burning three houses.
   Nale said the rebels, members of the Moro National Liberation
Front and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, were avenging the
deaths of friends. He did not elaborate.
   The two rebel groups have been fighting for Moslem rule on
Mindanao and other southern islands since 1972, but the fighting was
reduced to occassional skirmishes during much of the 1980s. Rebel
leaders signed a cease-fire with President Corazon Aquino in 1986.
   Officials say more than 50,000 people were killed at the height
of the fighting in the mid-1970s.
   In his report, Nale said that shortly after hearing of the
attack, military officials sent gunboats to the coastal village to
prevent a sea escape by the rebels. Eight hours after the initial
rebel attack, Nale reported he was aboard a helicopter gunship which
strafed rebel positions and inflicted ``heavy casualties.''
   On the ground, a company of soldiers encountered 35 rebels and
killed one guerrilla in a brief firefight. Other troops chased the
main rebel band and had an eight-hour ``decisive engagement'' near
the village of Tinyapan, the report said.
   The latest report from the field said troops completed mopping up
operations today and recovered the bodies of at least 32 rebels.
   The report said government forces also recovered 24 firearms,
including five M-79 grenade launchers.
</TEXT>
