<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 0706EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-History     02-01 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-History,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Given More Freedom To Interpret History In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet students will for the first time be allowed
to present their own interpretations of history at exam time, a
newspaper reported.
   History exams were canceled last year because textbooks have been
outpaced by media reports making new revelations about the country's
past.
   Under a new system this year, teachers will be allowed to devise
their own tests and students will be permitted to disagree with
teachers and textbooks without being penalized, the national
teacher's newspaper Uchitelskaya Gazeta said.
   Final history exams were called off last year because the
textbooks on which they were based were at odds with accounts of
Soviet history being printed by the more-open Soviet media,
including the exposure of some of the atrocities under dictator
Josef V. Stalin.
   Students finishing the 10th and final grade of Soviet middle
school last year had oral discussions with their teachers instead of
exams.
   Gennady A. Yagodin, chairman of the State Education Committee,
decided history tests would resume this school year but students
will be given more leeway to interpret history, Uchitelskaya Gazeta
said in its report Tuesday.
   ``Various opinions in all questions of the history of the country
are not only allowed, they are completely natural,'' Vladimir
Shadrikov, the vice chairman of the State Education Committee, wrote
in the article.
   The old tests were part of the rigid Soviet educational system
that was based on rote learning. In the past, Soviet high school
students were expected to repeat what their textbooks told them on
given subjects, for example, on the foreign policy guidelines laid
down by the 27th Communist Party Congress.
   Shadrikov said the only criterion for the new history exams is
that they be structured to show the maximum knowledge of a
particular student.
</TEXT>
