<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Sharansky 1stLd-Writethru   02-01 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Sharansky, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0502,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criticism Over Plan To Make Sharansky Ambassador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS five new grafs to include wife's reported opposition to
move, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to appoint former Soviet human rights
activist Natan Sharansky as Israel's ambassador to the United
Nations met with considerable opposition today.
   But some news reports indicated it was likely that the
41-year-old Sharansky would win the Cabinet's approval for the post.
   In announcing Sharansky's candidacy, senior officials said Israel
hoped his international popularity could boost Israel's image, which
has been tarnished by the Palestinian uprising.
   Arguments against Sharansky's appointment have focused on the
short time he has spent in Israel _ he arrived from the Soviet Union
on Feb. 11, 1986 _ and his past. Sharansky served nine years in
Soviet prisons and labor camps on charges of spying for the United
States, charges he denies.
   The fear is that the choice of Sharansky's for the high-profile
post could insult Moscow just as Israel is trying to rebuild ties
the Soviets severed 21 years ago over its seizure of Arab lands in
the 1967 Middle East war.
   Two Israeli newspapers quoted unnamed officials in the U.S. State
Department as warning that giving Sharansky such a high-ranking
diplomatic post could derailing efforts to restore ties with Moscow.
   Israeli officials expressed similar concerns and a popular
columnist for the Haaretz newspaper compared the Sharansky
designation with appointing Jonathan Pollard, an American convicted
of spying for Israel, as ambassador to Washington if he were freed
from jail.
   The Hadashot and Maariv newspapers asserted, however, that the
Soviets would not be offended by Sharansky's appointment because the
Kremlin now has a more liberal emigration policy.
   Israel radio said Foreign Ministry officials objected to the move
both out of diplomatic concerns and because it would violate a
longstanding practice of requiring a new immigrant to live at least
11 years in the country before becoming a foreign diplomat.
   Right-wing Israeli officials were concerned that Sharansky was
not well enough versed on the Arab-Israeli conflict, citing meetings
he once held with Faisal Husseini, a pro-PLO leader in the occupied
territories. Sharansky had said he was not aware of Hussein's ties
to the PLO.
   Sharansky, the symbol of the Soviet Jewry emigration struggle,
immigrated after a dramatic East-West swap of people imprisoned on
spying charges.
   Despite the criticism, Hadashot predicted Sharansky would win the
appointment and said Foreign Minister Moshe Arens was simply waiting
for Sharansky's response to the bid.
   Sharansky said Tuesday he had not been officially offered the job
and declined to comment.
   Today, Sharansky indicated he would consider the offer seriously.
He was quoted by the Hadashot daily as saying:
   ``The job of U.N. ambassador is honorable and important and in
the meantime I thank everyone who is proposing me for this lofty
job. When there is really something to talk about, I will talk.''
   But a government official said Sharansky had also indicated he
was hesitant about the offer.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Sharansky
was concerned about whether he could succeed despite his lack of
diplomatic experience, and that his wife, Avital, objects to leaving
Jerusalem.
   Mrs. Sharansky was also quoted by the Yediot Ahronot newspaper as
saying, ``I want to have a lot of children and would prefer to do so
here in Jerusalem.'' The couple now has two daughters, Rachel, 2,
and Hannah, two months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
