<SECOND>PM-Drug-School,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>11-Year-Old Arrested With 411 Crack Vials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old showed up for class carrying a bag
stuffed with 411 vials of crack that he claimed to have brought from
home, police said.
   ``It looked almost like a lunch bag,'' housing police Officer
Joseph DeLuca said after the boy's arrest Tuesday.
   The boy, Mark Birmingham, is in a class for the severely
emotionally handicapped, said Paul Berczeller, a teachers union
spokesman.
   It was unclear whether the boy was being used as a drug courier
or simply took the crack to the Bronx school to show his fifth-grade
classmates, housing police Capt. Samuel Hellman said.
   Police today sought Mark's 17-year-old brother, Michael, who Mark
claimed had given him the drugs.
   ``I got it from home,'' DeLuca quoted the boy as saying.
   Several students saw the boy take the bag from his coat and slip
it into a desk drawer, said Principal Joseph Cordasco.
   The boy was brought to the school office clutching the bag, he
said. A teacher asked to look inside and found the $5 vials of
crack, mostly in packs of 10.
   Mark's mother, Beverly, was summoned to the school and ``was very
upset but she just wanted to talk to a lawyer,'' DeLuca said.
   Mark was charged as a juvenile with possession of narcotics and
taken to a youth detention center. He was to appear today in Family
Court.
   A 12-year-old brother was turned over to the Bureau of Child
Welfare, said Sgt. Pete Berry, a police spokesman.
   Schools Chancellor Richard Green said the arrest ``reaffirms my
belief that drugs are the most serious problem our young must
confront.''
