<FIRST>r a PM-WhiffofWar     02-01 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whiff of War,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor Wants To Smell Success With Ad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weapons manufacturer is about to give buyers a
whiff of war.
   BEI Defense Systems is promoting its ``extraordinarily lethal''
Flechette rockets with scratch-and-sniff advertisements in trade
publications.
   The ads, emblazoned with the slogan ``The Smell of Victory,''
release the smell of cordite, the aroma that follows a rocket
explosion.
   ``My advertising usually gets lost in magazines,'' said George
Coutoumanos, director of U.S. government programs for BEI, who came
up with the idea.
   ``I usually get buried by the big guys _ the Boeings and the
General Dynamics. Who's going to read my ad when they can look at a
beautiful F-16 going over the countryside?''
   The rocket and electronics manufacturer is small by defense
industry standards. Last year, it handled about $47 million in
defense contracts.
   Specifically, Coutoumanos is trying to convince U.S. military
buyers and other defense hardware shoppers that his $400-$800
rockets are a better value than more high-profile missiles such as
Stingers.
   ``I'd really like to hire a major star and get them to sing and
dance, but it doesn't work that way,'' Coutoumanos said. ``And
shooting off rockets on television isn't really appropriate, I
think.''
   BEI was helped in producing its advertisement by the firm Bozell,
Jacobs, Kenyon &amp; Eckhardt.
   Coutoumanos said the ad will debut in the Feb. 1 international
editions of the Armed Forces Journal.
   ``Next year, I'm going to do the `Sound of Victory,''' he said.
``You're going to run your thumbnail across some kind of strip and
you will hear the explosions.''
</TEXT>
