<FIRST>r i PM-Hijack     02-01 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijack,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Costa Rica May Send Hijacker Back To Colombia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who hijacked a Colombian
airliner and threatened to set fire to one of the 122 people aboard
was overpowered by the co-pilot before the plane landed in Costa
Rica, a passenger said.
   Police arrested the hijacker after the Boeing 727 landed Tuesday
at the Juan Santamaria airport near San Jose, said Interior Minister
Carlos Disanti.
   The Red Cross treated some passengers for shock, officials said,
but no other injuries were reported to them or the six-member crew.
   The hijacker, who reportedly carried two orange juice cartons of
gasoline fitted with wicks, commandeered the Ace airlines flight
about 10 minutes after it left San Andres Island, Colombia, for
Medellin, Colombia.
   The Public Security Ministry identified the hijacker as
Nicaraguan exile Alvin Antonio Siu and said he will either be
charged in Costa Rica or deported to Colombia. Three other
passengers were questioned and released, it said.
   ``The hijacker during the flight told the pilot, Jaime Perez, he
would burn a passenger alive if he did not divert the flight to
Costa Rica,'' said a Costa Rican air traffic controller, Carlos
Paniagua.
   Humberto Campos, a passenger who was sitting toward the front of
the plane, said passengers noticed the man when they saw he was
carrying orange juice cartons and speaking nervously with a flight
attendant.
   ``Then he spoke with the captain and told him to divert the plane
to any Central American country, Jamaica or Miami, but the captain
persuaded him to land somewhere close because of lack of fuel,''
Campos said. He said the cabin door was open and passengers could
hear the conversation.
   The co-pilot overpowered the hijacker and took the cartons away
when the man looked out one of the cabin windows shortly before
landing, Campos said.
   The hijacker's motives were unclear, but Radio Reloj reported it
received an anonymous telephone call saying the hijacker was seeking
the release an American and several Colombians held in Costa Rica on
drug charges.
   The report did not identify those being held.
   Hernan Garron, the Public Security minister, said Siu was a
Miskito Indian living on San Andres Island. Thousands of Miskito,
Sumo and Rama Indians fled Nicaragua's Atlantic region in 1981 after
the Sandinista government tried to impose control on their
traditionally autonomous area.
   Some Indians remained behind to fight the government, and the
Sandinistas eventually reached peace agreements with some Indian
groups.
</TEXT>
