<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Priest     02-01 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Priest,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electric Stove Caused Fire That Killed Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electric stove caused the fire that
killed a pro-Solidarity priest, a church official said today.
   ``The final results of an inspection of the scene are not
available yet, but I can say the cause of the fire was an electric
stove in a little room next to the bedroom,'' said the Rev. Cezary
Potocki.
   ``It even caused the floor boards to burn up. There are still a
lot of questions, but to a great extent one can say the stove caused
the fire,'' Potocki said.
   The Rev. Stanislaw Suchowolec, 31, died Monday from smoke
inhalation in the northeastern city of Bialystok. His death provoked
controversy because another priest, the Rev. Stefan Niedzielak, 74,
died of a broken neck Jan. 21.
   The government said today that the inquiry was continuing into
the Niedzielak's death. Niedzielak was primarily known for a shrine
he maintained to Poles killed in the Soviet Union during World War
II, but also was sympathetic to Solidarity.
   The government said Tuesday it has no evidence the priests'
deaths were politically provoked.
   ``There is no ground to suppose that there is someone going
around Poland and spreading death among priests,'' government
spokesman Jerzy Urban said. ``There is no evidence to assume or
suppose the existence of a political provocation.''
   A housekeeper sounded the alarm after smelling smoke early
Monday, Urban said. Another priest found Suchowolec and his dead dog
lying next to a couch in the bedroom, he said.
   Potocki said Suchowolec's funeral would be held Friday at the
Immaculate Heart of Mary's Church in Bialystok, a city 120 miles
north of Warsaw.
   Potocki, chancellor of the Bialystok Curia, attended the autopsy
on Suchowolec's body.
   Suchowolec was an active supporter of the banned trade movement
Solidarity.
   Early in his six years as a priest, he served for three years as
a vicar in Suchowola, home village of the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, a
pro-Solidarity priest who was murdered by security police in 1984.
Suchowolec had organized pilgrimages to Popieluszko's grave in
Warsaw.
   Zofia Romaszewka, of the Solidarity Commission on Intervention
and Law Abidance, said Suchowolec had told the commission he had
been assaulted and that his car had been tampered with at least
twice.
   Zbigniew Romaszewski, another member of the commission which
records human rights' violations, said Suchowolec's car was stoned
Aug. 4, 1988 and two days later his parents' apartment was burned.
   Urban said no threats had been reported to authorities.
</TEXT>
