<FIRST>r a PM-People-Sadler     02-01 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Sadler,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Sadler's Feuding Family Agrees To Independent Guardian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a month of public feuding, the family of
brain-damaged singer-composer Barry Sadler of ``Ballad of Green
Berets'' fame has agreed to the appointment of an independent
guardian to handle his affairs.
   The agreement was announced Tuesday by Probate Judge John J.
Donnelly following two days of hearings on Sadler's mental
competence.
   While the judge agreed Sadler was incompetent to handle his
affairs, he said he had no jurisdiction to rule in the case because
Sadler is not an Ohio resident.
   At the same time, Sadler's family has agreed to let a probate
judge in Nashville, Tenn., name an independent guardian, Donnelly
said.
   Sadler's mother, Bebe, and son, Thor, 24, had made competing
appeals to be named his guardian.
   Under the agreement, the guardian must consult with family
members before making major decisions for Sadler, according to
Donnelly, who said relatives indicated a preference for naming as
guardian a Vietnam veteran like Sadler.
   Sadler, a former member of the Army's Special Forces unit, wrote
and performed ``The Ballad of the Green Berets'' in 1965 in honor of
the unit. He since has written a series of books on military themes.
   He was interviewed by Donnelly at Southwest General Hospital in
suburban Middleburg Heights on Monday. ``The responses were
confusing,'' said Donnelly.
   The 48-year-old Sadler, who has a home in suburban Nashville,
repeatedly referred to this year as 1980 even after being told the
correct date, and could name only two of his three children, the
judge said.
   Sadler was shot in the head last year in Guatemala City, where he
had lived for five years. The circumstances of the shooting have
never been disclosed.
   Psychologist Gintautas Z. Sabataitis testified that Sadler was
competent but ``severely limited'' in his abilities and needed a
guardian.
   Sadler had been treated at the Nashville Veterans Administration
hospital before being sent to Cleveland Nov. 8 for further treatment
and rehabilitation.
</TEXT>
