<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 0950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-INS-AsylumLawsuit     02-01 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-INS-Asylum Lawsuit,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Warns INS, But Says He'll Probably Rule In Favor Of The Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge extended his order
allowing Central American refugees to travel beyond southern Texas
while their asylum requests are reviewed but said he probably will
revoke it in three weeks.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela, however, warned immigration
officials not to let political asylum applicants overwhelm the area
again. And he said local communities should not have to bear the
brunt of federal immigration policy.
   ``I'm disturbed about the proposition that you're saying, in
effect, it's not my problem,'' Vela told attorneys representing the
Immigration and Naturalization Service at a hearing Tuesday in a
lawsuit against the INS.
   The judge extended until Feb. 20 an order blocking the INS from
requiring asylum-seekers to stay in southern Texas while their cases
were under review.
   But he added, ``It is very likely that in 20 days this injunction
will no longer be in effect.'' He said he needed time to study the
case.
   A group of immigration attorneys sued the INS on Jan. 6, and Vela
on Jan. 9 issued a temporary restraining order blocking the INS
procedure.
   The travel restriction resulted in a squalid campsite east of
Brownsville, where more than 300 Central Americans took shelter
under cardboard and sheets of plastic.
   After Vela issued his order, hundreds of immigrants fled southern
Texas, many ending up in the Miami area.
   The only issue Vela agreed to consider in the class-action
lawsuit on behalf of asylum-seekers in southern Texas was whether
the INS enacted the change without allowing time for public comment
as required by federal law.
   Vela said he doubted whether notice and comment were required in
this case.
   Prior to Dec. 16, the INS allowed asylum-seekers who presented
themselves to the agency's Harlingen District office to travel on to
their U.S. destinations, where they often were allowed to work while
pursuing their cases.
   The district on Dec. 16 began requiring applicants to file claims
in Harlingen and await decisions there for at least 30 days, during
which they were not allowed to work.
   Justice Department attorney Allen Hausman argued for the INS that
the new procedure did not deny immigrants the right to apply for
asylum, only changed the location for applying.
   Robert Rubin, one of the attorneys suing the INS, said
asylum-seekers are better able to pursue their claims to refugee
status in cities where they have relatives and friends to help them.
</TEXT>
