<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Shamir 1stLd-Writethru   02-01 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Shamir, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0529,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Offers Partial Withdrawal of Israeli Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 3rd graf, ``At a...' to CORRECT that statements made to
reporters sted rabbis. Pickup 4th, `Shamir pointed...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir today offered to
withdraw Israeli troops from some cities in the occupied territories
if Palestinians accept autonomy as a step toward solving the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   It was Shamir's most conciliatory statement yet on Israel's
future role in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``At a certain stage, when there is autonomy, the army will leave
several urban centers and be focused in some other areas,'' he told
reporters after addressing a group of visiting American rabbis.
   Shamir pointed out that a troop redeployment is called for in the
U.S.-brokered Camp David accords, which he supports.
   The 1978 accords call for electing local Palestinian
representatives to hold peace talks with Israel, along with
representatives of Egypt and Jordan.
   There would then be a five-year period of autonomy, followed by
further negotiations on the final status of the territories.
   The PLO and many Palestinians in the territories occupied in the
1967 Middle East war reject the Camp David accords and the concept
of autonomy, maintaining these ideas are intended to circumvent the
PLO and contradict Palestinian demands for an independent state.
   Shamir said the most crucial step in the peace process is to
begin negotiations. ``Once we get to this stage, positive results
will come,'' he said.
   But he reiterated that Israel will not speak to the Palestine
Liberation Organization and will not accept an independent
Palestinian state.
   Shamir outlined his views as paralleling the Camp David accords,
which led to Israel's peace treaty with Egypt.
   ``The peace process will be comprised of two stages,'' he said.
``First an interim condition and this will include full autonomy. In
the second stage (there will be) direct negotiations without
preconditions between Israel, Palestinian Arabs and Arab countries.''
   Shamir's government has been under increasing pressure to pursue
a peace initiative because of international criticism of its strong
policies in putting down the 13-month uprising in the occupied
territories and PLO chief Yasser Arafat's latest diplomatic
initiative.
   At least 370 Palestinians have been killed, most by Israeli army
gunfire, since Palestinians began their rebellion against Israel's
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Arafat made a series of statements last fall saying the PLO
accepted Israel's right to exist and renounced terrorism.
   In December, the United States agreed to open a dialogue with the
PLO based on Arafat's statements, and several of Israel's European
allies have urged Israel to open talks with Arafat's representatives.
</TEXT>
