<FIRST>r w PM-North-Prayer     02-01 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Prayer,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Says Remember the Past in Relation to Gorbachev and Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver L. North urged a religious group today
to ``remember the past'' before embracing Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
   North, delivering a hard-line anti-communist speech less than an
hour before the second day of his trial in the Iran-Contra case was
to resume in U.S. District Court, said he has ``watched in absolute
amazement'' as politicians, the media and intellectual leaders
praised Gorbachev's reforms.
   ``Until we see real changes, we must be wary of what is taking
place'' in the Soviet Union, North told a packed audience at a
downtown hotel. The theme of the prayer breakfast was underscoring
the ties between the United States and Israel.
   ``Today we are being asked to ... believe that Gorbachev is good
and Arafat is all right,'' North said. ``It would be better to
remember the past.''
   But North called Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, ``one of the world's most brutal terrorists'' who has
played a role in fomenting terrorist incidents in which Americans
died. The United States recently began a dialogue with the PLO.
   North, a former Marine lieutenant colonel, is the first person to
go on trial on charges stemming from the sale of U.S. weapons to
Iran and the diversion of profits to the Nicaraguan Contras. He is
charged with 12 felonies, and has pleaded innocent to the charges.
   At the breakfast, North cracked a few jokes about the trial,
saying he could only stay a few minutes because, ``I have an
appearance elsewhere that I have been invited to.'' Then he said,
``Normally in order to speak, I have to have a subpoena.''
   Breakfast organizers said the event had been planned since last
summer. Since he left the government, North has been speaking around
the country.
   North praised the idea of providing military assistance to groups
seeking to overthrow Soviet-backed governments.
   The Afghan rebels ``drove the Red army'' out of the country
because they were given U.S. military aid, he said.
</TEXT>
