<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Expels More Lebanese from Security Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied militiamen
today expelled two Lebanese women from the Israeli security zone in
south Lebanon, and placed four people under house arrest, police
reported.
   The expulsions raise to 76 the number of people deported from the
area this year.
   A police spokesman said Itaf Nakfour and Jamila Shoueiry were
expelled from the Christian town of Deir Mimas by Saeed Mansour,
commander of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia in the
town.
   Mansour drove the women to the Zommaraya crossing at the
northeastern edge of the zone, and the deportees walked to the
Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley.
   The police spokesman, who by custom is not identified, said
Mansour also confined three women and a man to their homes in Deir
Mimas. The four _ Nuhad al-Ghazzi, Georgette Morqos, Malakah Mansour
and Karim Bishara _ are to be questioned about the Nov. 7 attempt to
assassinate the militia's commander, Gen. Antoine Lahd.
   According to the police spokesman, Bishara is a distant relative
of Soha Bishara, the woman who shot and seriously wounded Lahd at
his home in Marjayoun. The Lebanese National Resistance Front, a
coalition of Syrian-backed groups, claimed responsibility for the
attempt.
   Lahd was released from an Israeli hospital Jan. 2 and returned to
the security zone Jan. 22.
   Israel created the zone as a buffer against cross-border attacks
in 1985 after it withdrew most of its army three years after
invading Lebanon.
