<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia     02-01 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslav Party Chief Refuses To Step Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Stipe Suvar
rejected demands for his resignation at a key party meeting and
called today for an end to feuding between political factions.
   The session of the policy-setting Central Committee, which ended
today, was marked by deep divisions between reformers and
conservatives over ways to overcome the country's worst economic and
political crisis.
   Suvar, a reformer, is supported by Slovenia and his native
Croatia, which favor political pluralism, more democracy and radical
market-oriented reforms.
   The conservatives are led by Serbia's party chief, Slobodan
Milosevic. He has the support of poorer regions, which believe
market-oriented economic reforms will cause layoffs at
state-subsidized enterprises.
   After three days of quarreling, the two factions of the Central
Committee agreed to hold an emergency party congress before the end
of this year.
   The congress was called to solve the political and economic
crisis and to choose a new party leadership for the next four years.
   Yugoslavia, which is trying to repay a $21 billion foreign debt
and reduce a 250 percent inflation rate, is seeking to implement
basic market-oriented economic laws. The nation also is trying to
cope with a drop in living standards and an alarming increase in
labor and ethnic unrest.
   On Tuesday, the military warned it will intervene if the crisis
continues.
   Efforts to oust Suvar were defeated Tuesday when conservatives
failed to force vote on the issue in the 165-member Central
Committee. But the meeting ended in a deadlock over major political
and economic issues.
   The final decision on Suvar's responsibility was left to the
23-member ruling Politburo, but it was highly unlikely that the body
will relieve him of his duties before his term expires in June.
   ``We are divided on fundamental questions,'' Josip Vrhovec, a
Central Committee member, said late Tuesday.
   He said the split was so bad that ``within the Communist Party we
already have two different, clearly ideologically defined parties.''
   Suvar said today the party must resolve its differences and
implement ``the reforms necessary to overcome the difficult
situation in the country and to enable the Communist Party to stop
losing battle after battle.''
   The debate before his speech was broadcast live by state
television.
   ``We have to overcome the quarrelsome and intolerant thinking
that only one truth exists and that all other opinions must be
defeated,'' he said in an apparent reference to the conservatives
pushing for his resignation.
   Earlier, Suvar dismissed as ``pure fabrication'' accusations made
by supporters of Milosevic that he is biased against Serbian
interests.
   The session was marked by heated exchanges on the question of
Suvar's responsibility for alleged anti-Serbian statements made
between his political allies, mainly from the liberal northern
republics of Slovenia and Croatia, and Milosevic's supporters.
   Suvar also has drawn support from the central republic of Bosnia
and the southern region of Macedonia, as well as from some delegates
of Serbia's largely Albanian-inhabited province of Kosovo.
   Mihajlo Pesic, a Serbian Central Committee member, said that
``patriotic people and Communist Party members are asking themselves
where this leadership, which has lost confidence of the people, is
leading us.''
   ``Can this leadership take us out of the crisis?'' he asked.
   The next scheduled party congress, the highest organ of the
ruling Communist Party, was to take place in 1990. The extraordinary
congress is to take place at an unspecified date later this year.
</TEXT>
