<FIRST>r a PM-Lab-Marijuana     02-01 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lab-Marijuana,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Amount Of Pot Found In Plutonium Research Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory
said it has tested and interviewed employees to determine who
brought a small amount of marijuana into its high-security plutonium
research facility.
   The building where scientists try to convert fuel-grade plutonium
into weapons-grade material and conduct other research has been
closed since Monday, when a tenth of a gram of pot was found in a
small plastic packet on the floor.
   The building will remain closed until the investigation is
completed, said plutonium facilities manager Arthur Toy, who could
not say how long it might take.
   The drug had been brought in past six security checkpoints and a
computer-controlled security gate, Toy said.
   The probe centered on 10 people who had been in the plutonium lab
about the time the drug was found, Toy said. The workers were
interviewed by security and took voluntary drug tests, but no
suspect has been identified, he said.
   Last year, a congressional oversight committee accused the lab of
failing to thoroughly investigate allegations of widespread drug
abuse.
   An undercover investigation led to the arrest of six lab
employees in 1986, but members of Congress and lab security
officials said the probe was stopped before it reached sensitive
areas of the lab, including the plutonium building.
