<FIRST>r w PM-Judges-Pay 1stLd-Writethru a0434 02-01 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judges-Pay, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0434,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Chairman Reviewing Judicial Pay Increases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 4 to CORRECT, saying Kastenmeier has made no decision
on whether to try to block pay raises for senior judges.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House subcommittee that
oversees federal courts says he will review proposed big pay raises
for senior judges who do no legal work.
   Rep. Robert Kastenmeier, D-Wis., ``believes he will have to look
further into the senior judge question,'' staff member Mary Dixon
said Tuesday.
   Dozens of federal judges who technically are semi-retired but who
do not hear cases stand to gain large pay raises unless Congress
rejects a government salary package due to take effect a week from
today. The Associated Press reported earlier this week that as many
as a fifth of the federal judiciary's ``senior judges'' no longer
hear cases but are in line for the increases anyway.
   Ms. Dixon said Kastenmeier plans to review the matter soon with
the subcommittee's lawyer, but ``believes he has at least a month''
to study it. Asked if Kastenmeier plans an attempt to block the
proposed raises, Ms. Dixon said he has not yet made such a decision.
   Kastenmeier heads the House Judiciary subcommittee on courts and
the administration of justice.
   The pay package includes raises of about 50 percent for some
2,500 top federal officials, including members of Congress and top
executive branch employees.
   The Constitution forbids lowering judicial salaries. Ms. Dixon
said Kastenmeier is studying whether the pay raises for the senior
judges can be killed after next Wednesday but before the bigger
paychecks go out.
   A Republican member of Kastenmeier's subcommittee, Rep. Carlos
Moorhead of California, previously questioned the wisdom of raising
the salaries of those senior federal judges who no longer handle any
cases.
   ``It doesn't seem fair,'' Moorhead said, adding that the
subcommittee may want to study ``establishing some minimum work to
qualify for the raises.''
   Older federal judges who opt for senior status qualify for
active-duty pay raises even after stepping down from full-time duty.
If those judges choose the other option provided by Congress _ full
retirement through resignation _ they keep for life the same salary
they received on their last day of work.
   Most senior judges, although lightening their workload, help the
federal court system cope with the increasing number of cases. But
records indicate that as many as one-fifth of the nation's 306
senior judges, including former Chief Justice Warren E. Burger, no
longer do any judicial work.
   Burger, who has not wielded a gavel since taking senior status in
1986, is in line for a $60,000 pay raise _ to $175,000 a year.
Salaries would rise from $89,500 to $135,000 for federal trial
judges; from $95,000 to $145,000 for federal appellate judges; and
from $110,000 to $165,000 for Supreme Court justices.
   Any attempts to limit or block the raises could be covered by a
1980 Supreme Court opinion written by Burger. In that case, the
court held that although Congress may not thwart judicial pay raises
once they take effect, it may do away with planned increases
``before they ... become a part of the compensation due.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
