<FIRST>r w PM-Meese-Book     02-01 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Meese-Book,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meese Signs Deal To Write Memoirs of Years With Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fortchoming book by Edwin Meese will focus on
``the Reagan era in modern political history,'' a spokesman for the
former attorney general said today.
   Henry Holt and Co. announced in New York on Tuesday that Meese
has signed a contract to write his memoirs, and they will appear in
November.
   The publishing company declined to disclose the amount of the
advance that Meese received, and spokesman Patrick Korten said he
did not know how much it was.
   Korten said Meese ``has been actively engaged in the process of
assembling material and scoping it out for the last several weeks.''
   The spokesman said he would not be assisting Meese in writing the
book.
   ``I know that he has got somebody working with him, but I think
it is more research and assemblage,'' Korten said. ``He really
intends to do a lot of the writing himself.''
   ``It is going to be focused on (former President) Reagan and
really the Reagan era in modern politics going back to his days as
governor,'' he said. ``I would be very surprised if there is an
awful lot in there about Ed Meese personally.''
   The Henry Holt announcement in New York said the book would draw
upon Meese's 22-year relationship with Reagan, which began at the
start of Reagan's political career in California in the 1960s, but
would focus on his eight-year presidency.
   In a statement released through Henry Holt, Meese said, ``There
has been much written about the Reagan administration, both by the
media and other members of his administration, and about my
activities within it. Now that that chapter is closed, I feel a
responsibility to tell everything I know about the operations of the
eight-year administration.''
   Meese, who was named attorney general after serving as White
House counselor, resigned last summer in the wake of a 14-month
criminal investigation by an independent counsel, which ended in a
decision not to prosecute. Meese declared he had been vindicated,
but a report by the Justice Department's Office of Professional
Responsibility, issued last month, said Meese violated ethical
standards in his actions on behalf of lobbyist E. Robert Wallach.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan still believed
his longtime friend did nothing wrong.
   The Henry Holt announcement said the rights to the book were
acquired during a dinner meeting in Washington in November, attended
by Meese; his wife, Ursula; Jack Macrae, Holt's editor in chief, and
Meese's agent.
</TEXT>
