<FIRST>r a PM-AmishRobberies     02-01 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amish Robberies,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amish Subjected To Rash of Robberies But Often Unwilling To Prosecute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ETHRIDGE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four members of an Amish community have
been robbed since Jan. 22 but won't file charges, police said.
   ``They don't like to prosecute if it will cause somebody to get
arrested.'' said Sheriff Tom Pyrdum. ``By doing this, they more or
less encourage more to happen.''
   The latest robbery occurred Monday when two men pulled a gun on
Enos Gingerich and took $300 as he drove his horse and buggy, Pyrdum
said.
   ``What they would do is hide in a ditch in the dark, and when one
came by, jump on the buggy and rob them,'' the sheriff said.
   The Amish are noted for their sober dress and simple lifestyle.
They reject automobiles and other modern conveniences, making them
easy prey for robbers.
   Police have some suspects and may press charges, Pyrdum said.
   ``They won't sign a warrant, but we will. We'll prosecute. We'll
use the Amish as witnesses,'' he said. ``They will testify under
subpoena. They won't swear, but they will affirm.''
</TEXT>
