<FIRST>u i PM-China-Shevardnadze 1stLd-Writethru   02-01 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Shevardnadze, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0532,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Arrives To Make Summit Preparations</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with new quotes, correct that visit three
days sted two.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze said
today he was ``full of good expectations and great hopes'' as he
arrived to discuss a summit to heal the 30-year-old China-Soviet
breach.
   ``We are starting our negotiations fully aware of the scale of
the forthcoming event,'' Shevardnadze said in a statement
distributed by the Soviet Embassy. ``The title theme of the
Soviet-Chinese dialogue is peace and development.''
   Shevardnadze arrived on a special Aeroflot plane that landed at
Beijing's old airport, now used only by top Chinese and foreign
leaders. He was met by his Chinese counterpart, Qian Qichen. The two
shook hands warmly as they stood bareheaded in a biting wind.
   Shevardnadze told reporters before stepping into his limousine he
was carrying a letter from Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev to
Chinese leaders. He did not reveal the contents.
   ``I reached an agreement in principle with my comrade Qian Qichen
in Moscow'' on holding a summit, he said. ``Now we're going to talk
concretely about the matter.'' Qian visited Moscow in December.
   In his written statement, Shevardnadze called Qian's visit a
``major step forward'' and added, ``We have stepped on the soil of
the People's Republic of China full of good expectations and great
hopes.''
   Shevardnadze will meet with Qian on Thursday morning. He flies to
Shanghai on Friday and meets the following day with Deng, who is in
the east coast city for the upcoming Lunar New Year.
   Shevardnadze told the Soviet news agency Tass on Tuesday he was
ready to conclude the agenda for a summit this year between
Gorbachev and Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping. He said he was bringing
concrete suggestions for a date.
   Both sides have indicated they want such a meeting in the first
half of the year. The Soviets have been courting China for several
years in an effort to heal their ideological and political quarrel,
but only in the past year has China shown equal eagerness.
   Factors include changes in Soviet policy and a sense that not
much time remains for Deng, who is 84.
   Vietnam's 10-year occupation of Cambodia has been one of the main
issues dividing China and the Soviet Union.
   However, under apparent pressure from its main ally, the Soviet
Union, Vietnam said in December it was willing to pull out by
September, and China agreed in principle to end its aid to Cambodian
rebels by then.
   The two other issues that have stood in the way of a
Chinese-Soviet reconciliation also appear nearing resolution. The
Soviet Union is scheduled to complete its troop pullout from
Afghanistan in two weeks and has announced plans to pull some troops
out of Mongolia, its ally on the Chinese border.
   The last Soviet foreign minister to visit Beijing was Andrei
Gromyko, who accompanied Nikita Khrushchev in 1959. The next year
the two countries split bitterly over leadership of the world
communist movement and a border dispute.
</TEXT>
