<FIRST>u a PM-JobSelling     02-01 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Job Selling,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auditor General Fires 18 Employees in Job-Buying Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania's auditor general today fired
18 people in her department who she said had bought jobs or
promotions under previous administrations.
   The 18 people ranged from management down to the staff level in
the 800-member department, and many worked in the field as auditors,
Auditor General Barbara Hafer said.
   Jobs and promotions were priced between $1,000 and $5,000, Ms.
Hafer said.
   Investigations by the U.S. attorney and her staff developed a
list of 25 people suspected of either buying jobs or promotions or
having jobs bought for them, Ms. Hafer said.
   ``Today's action was the only way to lift the cloud of suspicion
that has hung over those hard-working and dedicated employees of the
Auditor General's Office,'' said Ms. Hafer, a Republican who took
office two weeks ago.
   Former Auditor General Al Benedict and two top aides were among
those convicted and sentenced to prison in the job-selling case.
   Ms. Hafer's predecessor, Don Bailey, said there was not enough
evidence to fire 21 workers whose names were supplied to him by
Acting U.S. Attorney James West.
   Of the 25, one was former Deputy Auditor General Harold Imber,
who is in prison for his role in the job-selling scheme; four have
resigned or retired; two were fired under previous administrations
but won reinstatement, and 18 were dismissed.
   Ms. Hafer said she could not release any other names because of
concern that would jeopardize any legal action to uphold the firings.
   The auditor general's office audits government operations at the
state and local levels.
</TEXT>
