<FIRST>r i PM-Switzerland-Cabinet     02-01 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Switzerland-Cabinet,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Elects Successor to Justice Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire industrialist Kaspar
Villiger was elected to Cabinet today to replace Justice Minister
Elisabeth Kopp, who resigned over a drug money scandal.
   The multilingual Villiger, 47, official candidate of the
conservative Radical Democratic Party, received 124 votes from the
Federal Assembly, six more than the required absolute majority.
   Mrs. Kopp, Switzerland's first woman minister, stepped down after
admitting she warned her lawyer husband to cut his ties with a
Zurich-based, Lebanese-controlled company after she saw a
confidential report identifying it as a suspect in a billion-dollar
drug money laundering affair.
   Villiger was virtually certain of succeeding his fellow party
member in the seven-member Federal Council, Switzerland's Cabinet.
   His candidacy had formal support from the governing coalition of
Switzerland's four biggest parties, which has monopolized Cabinet
seats since 1959 under a platform promising political stability.
They are the Radical Democrats, the Christian Democrats, the Social
Democrats, and the centrist Swiss People's Party, which control 201
seats in the 246-member assembly.
   Monika Weber, a nationally popular advocate of consumer
interests, drew 33 votes from the assembly. She was nominated by the
opposition Alliance of Independents and anti-establishment Greens
party, which have a combined 17 seats in the assembly. The rest of
the votes went to other members of Villiger's party.
   With his election, Villiger's announced his 50 percent share in
the diversified family enterprise is taken over by his brother. The
company produces a variety of goods from cigarillos to bicycles and
reported sales totaling $27 million in 1988.
   Villiger also said the company will withdraw its bid to supply
the Swiss army with a new range of bicycles, to ensure no conflict
of interest.
   The new Cabinet member is expected to become defense minister,
taking over from Christian Democrat Arnold Koller, who has taken
charge of the Justice Ministry.
</TEXT>
