<FIRST>u w PM-Sawyer-ABC     02-01 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sawyer-ABC,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sawyer Said Leaving ``60 Minutes'' for ABC News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diane Sawyer is leaving CBS-TV's long-running
``60 Minutes'' program to take a job at ABC News, The Washington
Post said today.
   The newspaper said ``60 Minutes'' executive producer Don Hewitt
on Tuesday night confirmed rumors of Sawyer's possible departure
from the show, where she has been a correspondent since 1986.
   ``It's true,'' Hewitt told the Post. ``She's my friend and I'm
going to miss her.''
   There was no immediate confirmation from ABC, the Post said.
   The newspaper said ABC News President Roone Arledge had discussed
with Sawyer's agent, Richard Leibner, the possibility that Sawyer
could be a co-anchor with Sam Donaldson on an upcoming Thursday
night magazine show.
   ABC News reportedly has been after Sawyer for some time, the Post
said, adding that NBC two years ago made two separate offers to her.
One was for a program of her own, and the other was for
co-anchorship of the ``NBC Nightly News'' with Tom Brokaw, the Post
said.
   CBS kept her services with a contract reported to be worth $1.3
million a year, the newspaper said.
   When she renewed her contract, CBS reportedly said she could host
a revived version of the old ``Person to Person'' show that had been
hosted by the late Edward R. Murrow.
   She also was to be given the chance to be co-anchor on other
specials, the Post said. Those offers died in the midst of recent
personnel changes, it said.
   Hewitt said he has not yet considered who would be Sawyer's
replacement on the show.
</TEXT>
