<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MongoDeath     02-01 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mongo Death,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mongo the Pit Bull, Neighborhood Bully, Shot to Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STREATOR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took five shotgun blasts from police to
drop a 70-pound pit bull named Mongo after it terrorized a newspaper
carrier and charged officers.
   ``It sounded like World War III,'' Mongo's owner, Gale Sneath,
said after police killed his pet in the neighborhood.
   Sneath described the animal as an excellent watchdog and ``simply
mean'' to strangers; police said it was the neighborhood bully whose
nasty disposition prompted the City Council to enact a strict
ordinance governing pit bulls.
   Police Chief Ken Sangston ordered officers to destroy the dog on
Friday after it chased 11-year-old Kara Danko as she delivered
newspapers in this town of 15,000 located about 100 miles southwest
of Chicago.
   ``We'd had an ongoing ordeal with the same dog over the last two
years,'' Sangston said Tuesday. ``We'd had several citizens
complaints and its owner was arrested on a previous occasion for
letting the dog run at large.
   ``We had reports of the dog chasing kids, pedestrians, the
mailman and a newspaper carrier. We knew the dog was vicious and I
told my officers that if the dog attacked, I wanted the dog
destroyed.''
   The showdown came after Miss Danko was trapped on a screened-in
porch, holding the door shut to protect herself from the growling,
barking animal, Sangston said. The girl called her mother, who
summoned police.
   ``It had become a menace to public safety,'' Sangston said. ``We
sent out an officer and it charged my officer, who shot the dog with
a shotgun.''
   Four times police shot Mongo in the body, only to see it get up
and continue to advance. ``It finally had to be shot in the head,''
Sangston said.
   The new city ordinance requires pit bulls be chained and caged,
with warning signs posted to alert passersby of the animal's
presence. Police have issued no citations against Sneath in Friday's
attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
