<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   02-01 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: get better.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 30
   The Sun, Baltimore, on Bush and star wars:
   George Bush has folded Ronald Reagan's star-wars umbrella. Reagan
unveiled his Strategic Defense Initiative speaking of space-based
weapons to ``intercept and destroy strategic ballistic weapons
before they reach our shore.''
   Bush signaled skepticism (by) naming Gen. Brent Scowcroft, who
denied the feasibility of a perfect defense, as his national
security adviser. Further, John Tower, Bush's choice to head the
Pentagon, said the administration considers it impossible to
``devise an umbrella that can protect the entire American population
from nuclear incineration.'' ...
   Two Reagan legacies destroy star wars. A deficit that will not
permit a $100 billion-plus SDI program and the pending
American-Soviet START treaty, a pact halving offensive arsenals,
which could founder over ballistic missile defense. To chop the
budget and get a START treaty, Bush must contain star wars. ...
   Bush is not being rushed into negotiations with Moscow. Nor is he
a prisoner of Reagan fantasies. He is counting on a comprehensive
strategic review as a basis for later decisions on weapons systems
and arms control positions. His watchwords should be flexibility,
realism and prudence.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 27
   Philadelphia Daily News on the savings and loan crisis:
   Read George's lips.
   Saying the fools, knaves and blunderers who have turned the
American savings and loan industry into the banking equivalent of
the Bangladesh economy is going to cost you money. Lots of money.
   (The) trial balloon _ charging everybody who's got money in an
account at a bank or S&amp;L one-quarter of a percent for ``insurance''
_ is not a tax because the president says it isn't. Good thing. If
it were a tax, it would be a remarkably unfair, regressive one.
   It's probably too chancey to re-regulate. Why not then go all the
way with deregulation?
   Instead of beefing up insurance, take it away. Let the market
handle its own abusers. Any stockholder, officer or depositor in
some lean-to Texas S&amp;L could be expected to know that the greater
the return, the greater the risk.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 28
   Green Bay (Wis.) Press-Gazette on Dan Quayle:
   So, what did you think of Dan Quayle's presidency?
   You missed it? That was easy enough to do.
   Quayle was president for only about three minutes. If he was
president, that is.
   There is a question because of the way the law on presidential
succession is worded.
   Ronald Reagan's term expired at noon Jan. 20. The Constitution
says that the vice president-elect takes over if ``a president shall
not have been chosen by the time fixed for the beginning of his
term.''
   George Bush was to be inaugurated at noon. But the ceremony ran
late. Some legalists contend that Quayle was president between noon
and the time Bush took the oath three minutes later.
   So, what do we think of Quayle's presidency? That it was
mercifully short, that's what.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 30
   Elk City (Okla.) Daily News on education in the United States:
   Across America, emphasis is being placed on upgrading educational
systems.
   At the public school level, not only are educators, parents and
school patrons expressing this, but the economic necessities of the
world are a factor.
   Emphasis is again being focused on higher education as well.
   The issue is not just the grades students make but what and how
much they are learning. ...
   A recognition has arrived that this nation, to compete in the
world in the decades ahead, must have the brainpower as well as the
will not just to survive but also to succeed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 25
   Saginaw (Mich.) News on Salvador Dali:
   Well, goodbye, Dali. It was surreal, man.
   Cheap puns, yes, but in contemplating the Spanish artist who died
(Jan. 23) at 84, the mind is tempted down that strange and twisted
path where the subconscious overtakes rational thought. ...
   Dali's ... dramatic version of modernism explored the
subterranean workings of human perception.
   He delved into dreams and raised to the surface, and onto canvas,
whatever he found. Like that special sleeping life of the night,
they could be lovely visions, or nightmares of abject terror. It all
lay in what we thought we saw _ or, alternatively, in what we did
not wish to remember beyond those first few moments after waking.
   To those who like their art plain and pretty, Dali and his whole
genre seem crazy. ...
   The critics may differ on Dali's rank among the greats, but there
is no question that he was one of the true originals of the 20th
century _ and that for possessors of an original Dali, partin' is a
sweet sorrow indeed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
