<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Angels     02-01 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Angels,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guardian Angels Threaten To Pull Out of Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guardian Angels leader Curtis Sliwa said today
local officials are preventing the organization from training its
British recruits.
   Sliwa accused London borough councils of ``giving in to political
pressure'' by refusing to let the Guardian Angels use their premises.
   He said attempts to train in public parks, including London's
Hyde Park, were frustrated by police who accused them of creating a
disturbance and ordered them to move.
   ``It is getting increasingly desperate,'' Sliwa said. ``How long
can we continue this nomadic existence without trainees becoming
depressed?''
   British police and some politicians oppose the New York-based
Guardian Angels coming to Britain, saying law enforcement should be
left to professionals.
   The government last week announced it will temporarily assign an
additional 80 police officers to patrol crime-plagued stretches of
the London subway.
   A legal briefing for Guardian Angel trainees had to be canceled
Tuesday night when one local council refused the group permission to
use a hall, Sliwa said.
   ``That was the icing on the cake. I haven't gotten mad up to now,
but this has made me angry,'' Sliwa said.
   ``I have had people tell me that they have had meetings in their
halls by people who advocate the overthrow of the government. We are
not a clandestine, subversive organization, but we cannot assemble,
we cannot train,'' he said.
   ``We have approached people who say they think it will be OK to
use their hall, but when they go to their boards they come back and
say, `Boy, those people don't want you anywhere.'''
</TEXT>
