<DOCNO> AP890201-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TunnelDeaths     02-01 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tunnel Deaths,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contractor Decided Against Safety Device, Records Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials decided against installing a
remote-control gas detection system for a Milwaukee sewer project
weeks before an explosion killed three men checking methane levels
inside a tunnel, a newspaper reported.
   The Milwaukee Journal said Tuesday that a memo showed that
officials of the Program Management Office, which supervises
Milwaukee sewer construction, decided Sept. 16 not to order the
contractor to install the $12,257 system.
   The three men assigned to check the tunnel for methane died in an
explosion Nov. 10.
   The Program Management Office, a group of consulting firms, was
created to direct construction of a Milwaukee Metropolitan Sewerage
District $2.1 billion project that includes building huge tunnels
for holding sewage for treatment.
   The report said a Sept. 9 memo from PMO engineer Chuck Kennedy to
Barry Doyle, another PMO official, asked: ``Do you think we should
direct the contractor to proceed with installation of methane gas
recorder? We still have approximately 2,000 feet of tunneling
remaining. Please comment.''
   A handwritten, one-word answer _ ``No,'' along with the initials
B.D. and J.R. _ was returned to Kennedy on Sept. 16. The initials
are those of PMO officials Barry Doyle and John Ramage, the
newspaper reported.
   Philip Santacroce, a PMO official, said the contractor on the
project did not feel the safety system was necessary. Santacroce
said the mining would have been more than half completed by the time
the system could have been installed.
   ``The contractor felt he had enough monitoring equipment in the
hole, that he didn't need this recording device,'' Santacroce said.
``At the time, we felt, as long as (the contractor) felt he didn't
need it, we weren't going to go ahead and direct him to put it in.''
   But Santacroce stressed that the contractor, not the PMO or the
sewerage district, makes final decisions on how to build a project
and what safety equipment is necessary. ``We never told him he
shouldn't put it in,'' he said.
   The contractor, S.A. Healy Co. of McCook, Ill., has a $12 million
contract to build the 10-foot diameter sewer. Attorneys for the
company said Healy will not comment until local and federal
investigations are completed later this year.
   In September, Patrick Doig, Healy's project manager in Milwaukee,
wrote the PMO, requesting its advice on whether to install the
remote system.
   A sensor in the proposed system would have advanced with the
tunnel boring machine, transmitting continuous readings of methane
levels to an above-ground recorder, Doig said. ``We await your
direction,'' he wrote.
   An existing methane detector on the tunnel boring machine was
programmed to shut off the machine automatically when methane
accumulated to a certain level.
   Shutdowns occurred Nov. 7 and the day of the accident, Nov. 10,
when the detector found high levels of the combustible gas. Work was
halted and miners were evacuated.
   But because the sensor was not attached to a remote recorder,
workers carried hand-held methane detectors into the tunnel after
each evacuation to check gas levels.
</TEXT>
