<SECOND>PM-Lincoln Home, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0577,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lincoln Home Site Hit by Vandals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to CORRECT that vandalism occurred late
Monday or early Tuesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals spray-painted obscenities and
racial slurs on two buildings and a fence at Abraham Lincoln's home,
officials said.
   The vandalism where Lincoln lived during his years in the
Legislature occurred late Monday or early Tuesday, police said.
Damage was estimated at $500.
   Pink and blue fluorescent paint was sprayed on the carriage
house, a shed and a white wooden fence. Meters and an air
conditioner also were damaged.
   Because the damage to the Lincoln Home National Historic Site
occurred on federal property, the FBI is investigating along with
police, said Larry Blake, acting site superintendent for the
National Park Service.
   Similar incidents of vandalism were reported over the weekend at
a condominium and an Illinois Bell Co. parking lot a few blocks from
the home, police said.
   The Lincoln home, the only house the 16th president ever owned,
was reopened last year after a year-long, $2.2 million renovation.
Lincoln bought the home in 1844.
   In 1987, Lincoln's Tomb, situated in Oak Ridge Cemetery several
miles from the home, was vandalized with spray paint. Five
teen-agers and an adult were convicted or pleaded guilty in the
vandalism and damage to nearby graves.
</TEXT>
