<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--GulfAir     02-01 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gulf Air,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf Air Resumes Flights to Baghdad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Gulf Air flight to Baghdad in
more than eight years took off from Abu Dhabi on Wednesday, marking
the resumption of flights halted by the Iran-Iraq war.
   The Bahrain-based Gulf News Agency said the airliner plans three
flights a week to the Iraqi capital from the United Arab Emirates'
capital of Abu Dhabi, Bahrain's capital, Manama, and Doha, capital
of Qatar.
   Gulf Air is owned by the governments of Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and
Abu Dhabi, the biggest of the seven emirates of the United Arab
Emirates. They suspended flights to Baghdad shortly after the
outbreak of the war in September 1980.
   A U.N.-sponsored cease-fire halted hostilities Aug. 20.
   Gulf Air flights to Tehran were suspended during the internal
strife following the Islamic revolution that overthrew the Iranian
monarchy in 1979.
   Airline sources said contacts are being made to resume flights to
Iran.
</TEXT>
