<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-Homeless     02-01 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Homeless,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>All Homeless Housed 13 Years after Massive Quake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moving 500 families into new apartments in the
city of Tangshan ended a 12-year effort to find housing for victims
of the most disastrous earthquake this century, an official report
said Wednesday.
   Xinhua state news agency quoted Mayor Chen Liyou as saying
reconstruction of the devastated northeastern city was completed
when the last families were transferred from temporary shelters. It
gave no date for the final move.
   The July 28, 1976, quake, measured 7.8 on the Richter scale and
killed 242,000 people. It destroyed 97 percent of buildings in the
city of 1 million.
   Chen said the government has spent $1.35 billion on constructions
since 1979.
   More than 200,000 apartments have replaced makeshift homes of
brick, broken tile and plastic sheeting that housed most city
residents for years after the quake.
   Xinhua quoted one man who was buried under rubble for six hours
as saying he feels safe because his new apartment has been built to
withstand quakes of up to 8.0 on the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
