<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-AIDS     02-01 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Uganda-AIDS,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugandans Flee AIDS-Monitoring Doctors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Villagers in southern Uganda are fleeing
into the bush to avoid contact with a medical team monitoring the
spread of AIDS and counseling victims of the killer disease, a
doctor said Wednesday.
   ``They think we are going to give them injections that will
eventually kill them, and that the injections would keep others
sexually impotent for the next nine years,'' said Dr. David
Sserwadda, leader of the team.
   AIDS is considered widespread in Rakai, the district 124 miles
south of Kampala.
   The team is working on a joint program by Kampala's Makerere
University and Columbia University in New York City to determine the
number of AIDS victims in the area.
   Robina Kasada, Rakai district administrator, has told the doctors
to be patient because it takes time for the people to accept new
ideas.
   Uganda has reported 6,000 AIDS cases, the highest number in any
African country. But the government is far more open than other
African governments, which are wary that high AIDS figures will harm
a lucrative tourist trade.
</TEXT>
