<SECOND>AM-BRF--Colombia-Choppers,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Selling Helicopters to Colombia for Anti-Drug Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress on Wednesday it
had approved the sale of five UH-60 transport helicopters to
Colombia for use in fighting drug trafficking.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Pentagon said
Colombia would be offered the five Blackhawk choppers for $36
million. Colombia already has five of the helicopters.
   ``The primary use of these helicopters will be to transport
Colombia soldiers or police in air mobile operations against
narcotics traffickers and insurgent forces,'' the Pentagon said. It
said the sale will help Colombia in its efforts to stem the flow of
drugs into the United States.
   The Pentagon said the Army would be responsible for overseeing
the transaction. The prime contractor will be the Sikorsky Aircraft
Division of the United Technologies Corp. in Stratford, Conn.
