<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Japan     02-01 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita May Make New Proposal for Solving U.S.-Japan Trade Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noburo Takeshita may
bring to the United States a new proposal for handling U.S.-Japanese
trade disputes, the Bush administration said Wednesday.
   A senior administration official said exact contents of such a
plan were not known, but that the administration generally was
content with existing trade arrangements and laws.
   ``But that doesn't mean we're not willing to look at any new
suggestions the prime minister may bring with him,'' the official
said. ``And we certainly will do that.''
   The official briefed reporters at the White House on Takeshita's
upcoming visit under ground rules that his name not be used.
   Takeshita, the first foreign leader to meet with President Bush,
arrives Thursday for a two-day ``working visit.'' After leaving
Washington, he plans to visit Bush's predecessor, President Reagan,
in California.
   The administration official was asked about news reports in Japan
that Takeshita would bring along a new proposal for setting up a
U.S.-Japanese panel to oversee trade dispute between the world's two
largest economies.
   ``He may be. We don't have them (the proposals) as of now. We'll
see what he comes with. We have indications that he may have
something, but I don't know what it is.''
   However, the official said, ``We believe we do have a great many
mechanisms now that are working in the ways in which we negotiate
and discuss and try to settle the issues we have in the trade area.''
   The United States has special trade-dispute settlement agreements
with two nations: Israel and Canada.
   The U.S. trade deficit with Japan is the world's largest trading
imbalance _ more than $50 billion annually for the past several
years.
   At Wednesday's briefing, the U.S. official said that ``given the
scale of our relationship, it's only natural that we have problems
and specific complaints that must be handled.''
   He said that while the trade shortfall with Japan had eased
slightly in recent months, ``it is still very enormous. And we still
have to work on it.''
   ``We have specific issues with Japan in terms of opening their
markets,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
