<FIRST>u w PM-ConfirmationRdp 5thLd-Writethru a0600 02-01 0983</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Confirmation Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0600,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Denies Personal Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf, He added, with end of hearings,
vote Thursday; deletes pvs 15th graf, Nunn said, outdated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary-designate John Tower today
denied allegations that he has a drinking problem, telling the
Senate Armed Services Committee he is a ``man of some discipline.''
   Conservative activist Paul Weyrich said Tuesday that he had ``on
a number of occasions'' seen Tower publicly inebriated and in the
company of women other than his wife.
   But in a closed committee session this morning, Sen. Malcolm
Wallop, R-Wyo., said Tower denied that he was a womanizer, had
drinking problems or that past business ties with military
contractors would hamper his work.
   Tower later responded to the allegations in an open session.
Asked by Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the committee chairman, if he has
drinking problem, the nominee replied: ``I have none. I'm a man of
some discipline.''
   Tower said it is ``essential that the secretary of defense be at
all times capable of exercising the duties of the office.''
   The nominee was also asked whether he would tolerate
discrimination or sexual harassment of women in the Defense
Department. He replied that he would have ``zero tolerance'' for
such practices and that ``professional women would be afforded the
respect and deference they deserve.''
   He added that he does not envision seeing women in a combat role.
   Nunn said at the conclusion of the hearings that the committee
would vote on the nomination on Thursday.
   Nunn began the open session by reading a letter from C. Boyden
Gray, the counsel who handled President Bush's transition, in which
Gray denied that the office received letters ``containing specific
allegations of impropriety concerning Senator Tower.''
   Weyrich had testified that the office received letters
questioning Tower's moral character but they had not been brought to
the attention of the Armed Services Committee or Bush.
   At the start of this morning's closed session, Tower was allowed
to respond to Weyrich's allegations, Wallop said.
   Tower ``said that he does not feel that he has problems, as have
been characterized by people upstairs (in open session) and
personally feels himself to be a strongly disciplined man,'' he
continued.
   ``I don't know of anybody who suspected that he did have a
drinking problem. He stated his viewpoint that he did not,'' said
Wallop. ``I think everybody in there is quite satisfied about his
lifestyle.''
   Nunn expressed chagrin Tuesday after Weyrich testified that ``on
a number of occasions'' he had seen Tower publicly drunk and in the
company of women other than his wife. Tower has been divorced twice.
   In other confirmation proceedings Tuesday, the Senate approved
the nomination of Robert Mosbacher as Commerce secretary, Samuel
Skinner as Transportation secretary and Carla Hills as special trade
representative. The vote was 100-0 on all three nominations.
   Also Tuesday, the White House asked for a rare delay in
confirmation hearings for Louis Sullivan to be health and human
services secretary, and said it had nothing to do with the flap over
the nominee's views on abortion.
   Tower said last week in two days of testimony that he received
fees of more than $1 million for consulting work for seven defense
contractors, including such industry giants as Rockwell and
Martin-Marietta.
   The committee has been expected to approve Tower to head the
Defense Department, and there was no immediate indication that
Weyrich's remarks would change that.
   Tower, a 63-year-old Texas Republican, served 24 years in the
Senate, and was chairman of the Armed Services Committee from
1981-85.
   Members emerging from Tuesday's closed session sounded
unimpressed with the testimony from Weyrich and another witness,
William Jackson Jr.
   Jackson, a senior fellow at the Fulbright Institute of
International Relations, said he had heard rumors about Tower's
personal life from delegations traveling to Geneva.
   ``A number of allegations prove to be wrong,'' said Nunn, who
added that the committee is ``continuing to pursue all allegations.''
   Tower refused to comment as he left the committee's offices.
   Tower was not present when Weyrich took the witness chair and
uttered in public the allegations that had been the subject of
rumors for several weeks while President Bush was deciding on a
candidate to head the Pentagon.
   ``Over many years, I have encountered the nominee in a condition
lacking sobriety as well as with women to whom he was not married; I
recognize senators' wives because I worked here in the Senate for
many years,'' Weyrich said. ``I did encounter this on a number of
occasions.''
   Tower was dogged by allegations of drinking and womanizing before
his nomination was announced. In divorce papers filed by his second
wife, Lilla Burt Cummings, Tower was accused of ``marital
misconduct.''
   Bush has defended Tower, saying an FBI background check found
nothing that would prevent him from serving as defense secretary.
When he announced the nomination he dismissed ``a lot of rumors that
proved to be groundless.''
   Elsewhere on Capitol Hill, Republicans and Democrats joined in
praising the three Bush administration appointments they approved
Tuesday.
   Mosbacher is a longtime friend of Bush's who raised millions of
dollars for the Republicans in last year's campaign.
   Ms. Hills was the secretary of Housing and Urban Development
during the Ford administration during the mid-1970s, and has
practiced law in Washington since.
   Skinner was the chairman of the Regional Transportation Authority
of Northeastern Illinois, which includes the mass transit system
serving Chicago. He is also a political ally of Illinois Gov. James
Thompson and served as a campaign aide in Bush's bid for the White
House.
   Discussing the request to delay the Sullivan hearing, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the administration has asked for
more time for more background checks.
   Sullivan upset anti-abortion leaders twice in recent weeks when
remarks attributed to him indicated he was not an adamant foe of
abortion.
</TEXT>
