<FIRST>r w AM-SolicitorGeneral     02-01 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solicitor General,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nominates Appeals Court Judge Starr as Solicitor General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday he will nominate
conservative federal appeals judge Kenneth W. Starr to be solicitor
general, the government's chief representative before the Supreme
Court.
   Starr's willingness to give up his lifetime appointment on the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia was seen
in legal circles as a good way to put himself in the running for a
future nomination to the Supreme Court.
   Following a similar route, Thurgood Marshall gave up a federal
judgeship to become solicitor general in 1965, and two years later
he was named by Lyndon B. Johnson to the high court.
   At 42, Starr is regarded by many courthouse observers as too
young to want to spend the rest of his career on the D.C. Circuit.
However, there may be political risks in the solicitor's job if
Starr eventually wants to go to the high court.
   As solicitor general, Starr likely would be the person to urge
the high court to overturn its 1973 abortion-rights decision _ a
position that could elicit strong opposition from pro-abortion
forces if he is later nominated as a justice.
   Starr was a clerk for former Chief Justice Warren E. Burger and
later a partner with the Los Angeles law firm of Gibson, Dunn &amp;
Crutcher. He served as counselor to then-Attorney General William
French Smith from 1981 until his appointment to the D.C. appeals
court in 1983.
   The solicitor general is the government's chief appeals lawyer,
arguing cases before the Supreme Court and deciding whether to
appeal lower court decisions against federal agencies.
   If confirmed by the Senate, Starr would succeed Charles Fried,
who resigned to return to Harvard University Law School.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890201-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sudan     02-01 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sudan,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudanese Rebel Leader Meets U.S. Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sudanese rebel leader met with State
Department officials recently as part of a U.S. effort to end
Sudan's civil war that has left millions in danger of starvation,
officials said Wednesday.
   Mansour Khalid, who serves as the foreign envoy of the Sudanese
People's Liberation Army, arrived in Washington last week and asked
to meet with representatives of President Bush's new administration,
State Department spokesman Charles Redman said.
   Khalid spoke on the telephone with officials of the National
Security Council, said White House officials who spoke on condition
of anonymity. He also met with Julia Taft, who heads the U.S.
government's Foreign Disaster Assistance program and has been
pressing both sides to allow relief convoys safe passage from Kenya
into famine areas, said a State Department official, also speaking
only on condition he not be named.
   Redman said that Khalid has been here before and that his
meetings did not reflect a change in U.S. policy. Khalid has said he
knows Bush from the days both represented their governments at the
United Nations in 1971 and 1972.
   Until recently, the U.S. government had carefully avoided taking
sides in Sudan, angering congressional critics who charged that the
State Department was allowing foreign policy considerations to
overrule humanitarian needs. Congressional delegations to Sudan in
recent weeks have been told that as many as 500,000 Sudanese died
last year of hunger.
   In recent months U.S. officials have been taking a slightly more
critical approach toward the Sudanese government of Sadiq Mahdi
after he refused to support a tentative cease-fire pact signed by
one party in his coalition government. Mahdi has been pressured by
Moslem fundamentalists in his government to reject any pact with the
predominantly Christian and animist rebels.
   The United States has been urging the Ethiopian-backed SPLA and
the government of Mahdi to negotiate an end to their five-year war
and to allow foreign relief supplies to reach starving Sudanese in
the southern part of the country.
   The Sudanese government has supported past U.S. discussions with
the rebel group and was informed of the meetings with Khalid, said
one U.S. official. He said the two sides in Sudan are also talking
with each other.
   In an effort to bring pressure on Mahdi, U.S. diplomats in
Ethiopia have been talking more frequently to SPLA representatives,
and the United States has also been urging the Soviet Union to get
involved in efforts to end the war.
   The United States enjoyed military basing rights and close ties
with the Sudanese government of Gaafar Nimeiri, but relations with
Sudan deteriorated after he was deposed in a 1985 coup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
