<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-PearyHoax 1stLd-Writethru a0623 02-01 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peary Hoax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0623,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navigation Foundation Finds No Evidence of Hoax Based on Document</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Baltimore astronomer ...' to CLARIFY that
worksheet was cited in 1988 only.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A worksheet of calculations by Admiral
Robert E. Peary provides no evidence he faked his claim of reaching
the North Pole in 1909 but doesn't end the debate on whether he
actually reached his destination, the head of a foundation hired by
The National Geographic Society announced today.
   Retired Rear Adm. Thomas D. Davies, president of The Navigation
Foundation, presented a new interpretation of a single sheet of
Peary's handwritten navigational notes.
   Baltimore astronomer and historian Dennis Rawlins, in a 1970
article and a 1973 book, had argued that Peary faked his claim to
have discovered the pole. Most recently, in October, he cited the
worksheet as further evidence of fraud.
   Davies said, ``The piece of paper provides no evidence Peary
faked his claim.''
   But he added, ``This worksheet says absolutely nothing about
whether Peary reached the pole.'' He said debate about Peary will
continue as the foundation reviews other pieces of data from the
expedition in its investigation.
   Davies said three experts _ evaluating the single document only _
found the calculations are not from 1909, as believed from the
envelope in which they were found, but from an earlier polar
expedition made in 1906.
   He said Rawlins' ``sensational claims'' are not proved by the
calculations.
   Further, Davies said that one set of numbers that Rawlins
interpreted as compass readings taken as part of celestial
observations were actually serial numbers found on the face of a
chronometer taken on the polar expedition.
   Gilbert M. Grosvenor, president of the National Geographic
Society, attacked Rawlins' claim that Peary deliberately faked his
results.
   ``Suggesting Peary might not have reached the pole is one thing;
declaring him a fraud is another,'' Grosvenor said.
   Grosvenor said that in commissioning Davies and the foundation to
carry out the study, ``I told him, let the chips fall where they
may.''
   National Geographic previously asked Wally Herbert, a British
polar explorer to investigate Peary's claims. Herbert published an
article last year saying he found that Peary was 30 to 60 nautical
miles off course.
   Rawlins earlier had found Peary came no closer than 121 miles but
because of difficult conditions and low supplies felt pressured to
say he had discovered the North Pole.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890201-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--UN-Sudan     02-01 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--UN-Sudan,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNICEF Appeals for Urgent Aid For Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNICEF appealed Wednesday for $11.5 million in
emergency aid for hundreds of thousands of Sudanese forced to flee
their homes by drought and civil war.
   The main aim is to help provide food, drugs and clean water for
displaced people in war-torn southern Sudan and around the capital,
Khartoum, according to the U.N. Children's fund.
   Vaccination drives are planned, since a measles outbreak killed
all children under five in some villages last year, said Robert
Rogier, a UNICEF representative in Sudan.
   A third of Sudan's children are malnourished, and every 10th baby
dies before its first birthday, said UNICEF.
   Up to 1 million southern Sudanese have migrated north to Khartoum
in the past 18 months, fleeing the worst drought in years and war
between troops of the Moslem-dominated government and rebels from
the minority Christians and animists of the south.
   Heavy rain and floods in August left another 1 million people
homeless in Khartoum, UNICEF said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
