<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Vessey     02-01 0117</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Vessey,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired General to Continue Serving as Emissary to Hanoi for POW-MIA
Affairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Gen. John W. Vessey Jr., former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, will continue to serve as
special presidential emissary to Hanoi for POW-MIA affairs in the
Bush administration, the White House announced Wednesday.
   Vessey was first appointed to the job in February 1987 by
then-President Reagan.
   A White House statement announcing that Vessey will remain on the
job said that beginning with his first visit to Hanoi in August
1987, Vessey's efforts ``have resulted in substantial progress in
resolving this pressing humanitarian issue and ending the
uncertainty for the families of our missing in Southeast Asia.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
