<DOCNO> AP890201-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sharansky     02-01 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sharansky,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan to Appoint Sharansky as Ambassador Gets Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers on Wednesday criticized the
nomination of Natan Sharansky as Israel's next U.N. ambassador,
saying the appointment of the human rights activist and former
Soviet prisoner could hurt relations with Moscow.
   Senior Israeli officials, who announced Sharansky's candidacy
Tuesday, expressed hope that Sharansky's popularity would help boost
Israel's image, which has suffered during the 13-month Palestinian
uprising.
   But leading Israeli newspapers said Sharansky is not the right
man for the job.
   They cited Sharansky's lack of experience in Israel and said the
appointment of a man convicted of anti-Soviet espionage would offend
Moscow, which only recently began to improve ties with Israel after
a 20-year diplomatic break.
   The appointment of Sharansky, 41, would have to be approved by
Finance Minister Shimon Peres, head of the left-leaning Labor Party,
and by the coalition Cabinet.
   Two Israeli newspapers quoted unidentified State Department
officials as warning against derailing efforts to restore ties with
Moscow by giving Sharansky such a high-ranking diplomatic post.
   Sharansky ``has barely managed to become rooted in the country's
landscape and hasn't yet found his proper place in Israeli
society,'' said the mass-circulation daily Yediot Ahronot.
   The appointment ``is liable to be interpreted as a superfluous
provocation of the Soviet Union,'' the newspaper said.
   Other criticism focused on Sharansky's personality, with the
daily Maariv saying the appointment could prove risky because
``Sharansky will not settle for serving as a mouthpiece ... He is an
individualist whose opinions cannot always be foreseen.''
   The paper apparently was referring to Sharansky's somewhat
independent stand on the Palestinian problem, including his meetings
with pro-PLO figures in the occupied lands.
   A popular columnist for the Haaretz daily compared the Sharansky
designation to appointing Jewish spy Jonathan Pollard ambassador to
Washington if he were freed from jail. Pollard, a former U.S. Navy
analyst, is serving a life sentence on treason charges for selling
classified information to Israel.
   The daily Hadashot and Maariv quoted a Soviet U.N. official
identified as Alexander Dinisov as saying Sharansky's appointment
``will not cause any friction between Israel and the Soviet Union.''
   In Moscow, the deputy head of the Soviet Foreign Ministry's press
center, Vadim Perfilyev, said the issue is a matter of Israel's
internal affairs.
   Sharansky, the symbol of the Soviet Jewry emigration struggle,
came to Israel in 1986 after an East-West prisoner exchange that
freed him from jail in the Soviet Union, where he served nine years
on espionage charges. Western observers believe the espionage charge
was in fact punishment for his political views.
   Sharansky dodged reporters' questions Wednesday. Asked about the
reported appointment, he said ``No comment, no comment'' as he left
a Jerusalem hotel after addressing North American rabbis.
   After the speech, one of the rabbis addressed Sharansky as ``Mr.
Ambassador.'' Sharansky smiled and said: ``I'm glad you accept that
I'm the ambassador of Soviet Jews here in Israel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
