<FIRST>r a AM-MeredithJr-Manslaughter     02-01 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meredith Jr-Manslaughter,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son of Civil Rights Leader Pleads No Contest to Manslaughter Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALFRED, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of civil rights leader James H.
Meredith has pleaded no contest to charges of manslaughter and
drunken driving in a 1987 car accident that killed two people.
   In a plea bargain arrangement with prosecutors, James H. Meredith
Jr. changed his plea from innocent on Tuesday, the second day of his
jury trial in York County Superior Court.
   The terms of the agreement called for a one-year prison sentence,
but sentencing was delayed to review a request by Meredith's
attorney for house arrest, rather than jail.
   Meredith, 22, could have faced up to 10 years in prison if
convicted of manslaughter.
   Meredith and two friends were returning from dinner in Saugus,
Mass., on Aug. 26, 1987, when his sports car missed a curve and
struck a boulder. Meredith suffered multiple injuries but recovered.
Paul Huard, 44, and Kevin Jones, 26, were killed.
   The three had lived together while working summer jobs at an
Ogunquit restaurant.
   At the time of the accident, Meredith's blood-alcohol level was
0.11, just above the then-legal intoxication limit of 0.10. The
limit has since been reduced to 0.08.
   Currently a junior business major at the University of
Pennsylvania, Meredith is free on $5,000 bond pending sentencing.
His father, James Meredith Sr., was the first black to gain entrance
to the University of Mississippi in 1962, and went on to lead the
1966 March Against Fear across Mississippi. He is now a businessman
in Cincinnati.
</TEXT>
