<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-NuclearCleanup     02-01 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Cleanup,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE Promises Five-Year Cleanup of Buried Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK WARBIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Energy today agreed to
pay for an accelerated, $456 million cleanup of buried nuclear waste
at its Idaho National Engineering Laboratory, Gov. Cecil Andrus
announced today.
   The agreement came more than three months after the governor
closed Idaho's borders to temporary storage of nuclear waste.
   At a news conference, Andrus said negotiations with DOE since the
Oct. 19 ban led to the commitment to the 5{-year cleanup. Before the
talks began, the department planned to spend only $29.6 million
through fiscal year 1991.
   ``This is a tremendous step forward in the effort to completely
remove years of accumulated buried waste,'' Andrus said. ``The
department's commitment of significant new resources indicates that
DOE understands how important cleanup is to Idaho and to the
nation.''
   However, the governor said he will not reconsider his ban on
waste shipments until legislation is introduced in Congress to begin
the land withdrawal process necessary to open the DOE's permanent
storage site near Carlsbad, N.M.
   ``Until that time, the borders remain closed,'' Andrus said.
   About 2 million cubic feet of transuranic, low-level radioactive
and other hazardous wastes buried beneath the laboratory, some of it
since the 1950s.
   Some cleanup work has been under way since 1987 when tests found
contamination in the aquifer under the site.
   Andrus said today's announcement means the cleanup will be
sharply accelerated.
   The DOE has agreed to spend $33.9 million on cleanup in the
current fiscal year, through Sept. 30; $62 million in fiscal 1990,
and $89.9 million over each of the following four years. The money
is subject to congressional approval.
   The faster cleanup and increased funding, along with DOE's
agreement to conduct an epidemiology study around the lab and its
initiation of land withdrawal action on the plant in New Mexico,
means three of Andrus' four conditions for reassessing his ban on
waste shipments have been met.
   The governor, who previously blasted DOE for failing to keep
repeated promises to clean up the laboratory, said he was confident
he could trust the department to follow through on its latest
commitment.
   ``There are plenty of opportunities for the state of Idaho to see
the DOE keeps its word this time,'' Andrus said, mentioning some
unspecified ``cards that have not been played yet.''
   Laboratory manager Don Ofte said research is under way to find
the safest and most effective ways to get to the buried waste. But
he said it may be two or three years before the first shipments
begin leaving the site.
</TEXT>
