<HEAD>Bundy Interview To Be Released On Tape</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead to delete sale of tapes. Adds 1 graf background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Videotapes of serial killer Ted Bundy's
interview the day before his execution will be offered to the
public, the interviewer said.
   James Dobson said the 29-minute tape would be sold for a
``suggested donation'' under $30. He will feature the interview
Thursday and Friday on his radio program, heard on more than 1,000
stations around the country.
   Paul Hetrick, a vice president for Dobson's Focus on the Family
organization, said a person who asked for a videotape without
enclosing money may or may not get a copy. Because of Internal
Revenue Service Regulations, the California-based ministry can't
sell the tape.
   Bundy told Dobson during the Jan. 23 interview that exposure to
pornography helped fuel his sexual urges to a point that he looked
for satisfaction by mutilating, killing and raping women.
   ``We'll probably put the videotape in the hands of people with
anti-pornography groups,'' Hetrick said. ``We'll meet whatever
demand is there.''
   Bundy confessed to the murders of 23 women in the days shortly
before he was executed for the 1978 murder of 12-year-old Kimberly
Leach of Lake City. Investigators have said he may have killed as
many as 100 people.
