<FIRST>r i PM-QuayleTrip 2ndLd-Writethru a0513 02-01 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle Trip, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0513,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quayle Rejects Idea of ``Debtors' Cartel''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Quayle quotes; picks up 6th graf pvs,
Quayle will.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle, arriving in
Latin America for the Bush Administration's first overseas mission,
said today that any effort by the Latin countries to form a
``debtors' cartel'' would be strongly resisted by the United States.
   Quayle, speaking to reporters aboard Air Force Two just before
landing in Caracas, said the idea being considered by some Latin
leaders to develop a united front to deal with their common debt
crisis is ``counterproductive.''
   ``We are absolutely opposed to the idea of a debtors' cartel,''
Quayle said. ``Our strong position is that a debtors' cartel is a
non-starter'' because each country has different circumstances that
should be addressed on an individual basis.
   Quayle made the comments as he flew here to attend the
inauguration Thursday of Venezuela's new president, Carlos Andres
Perez.
   Upon his arrival, Quayle caused a horn-honking stir at a busy
intersection when he stopped his motorcade for an impromptu shopping
trip at a small corner fruit market.
   Quayle ate a banana and sampled a guava and handed out pins
bearing the U.S. and Venezuelan flags.
   With some two dozen heads of state expected at the inauguration,
the Third World debt drisis is expected to be a major topic of
discussion among the leaders and when they meet with Quayle in
bilateral talks.
   Today, Quayle's packed schedule included meetings with Perez and
with the country's outgoing president, Jaime Lusinchi, and Colombian
President Virgilio Barco.
   Quayle indicated that he would be discouraging efforts by some of
the leaders, including Perez, to coordinate their tactics and
demands for dealing with creditors.
   The vice president said he phoned former President Richard Nixon
for advice the night before his departure.
   Nixon, as vice president in 1958, made a trip to Venezuela where
he faced violent anti-American crowds. Quayle said they chatted
about that.
   Quayle will stop in El Salvador on his way home Friday. During
meetings with political, military and labor leaders there he will
stress the need to curtail human rights violations in the Central
American country, officials said.
   He will meet with outgoing president Jose Napoleon Duarte of the
Christian Democratic Party and with representatives of right-wing
factions, but not with anyone from the leftist party battling for
power in the March 19 election, U.S. officials said.
   One official said it would be awkward for Quayle to meet with
leftist presidential candidate Guillermo Ungo since he is a civilian
ally of rebels fighting to overthrow the U.S.-backed government.
   The vice president will meet with representatives of the rightist
Nationalist Republican Alliance, or ARENA, whose candidate Alfredo
Cristiani has led Christian Democrat Fidel Chavez Mena in opinion
polls, with Ungo trailing.
   No official list of Quayle's meetings has been released.
   But a State Department official involved in planning the trip
said he is scheduled to meet with the presidents of Spain, Portugal,
Brazil, Colombia and Honduras. He will also meet with a group of
Caribbean leaders.
   One of the topics for those meetings will be the status of the
U.S.-backed Contra rebels battling the leftist government of
Nicaragua.
   In El Salvador, an administration official said, Quayle intends
to have ``very straightforward'' conversations emphasizing that the
administration is serious about adherence to human rights.
   Officials have expressed concern that continued human rights
problems will make it difficult for the administration to obtain
further U.S. aid for El Salvador from Congress.
</TEXT>
