<FIRST>r a AM-BannedCritic     02-01 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banned Critic,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Movie Critic Ban May Violate Rights, Attorney General Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLYTHE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ban by the only movie theater in town on
the only movie critic in town may violate a civil rights law, the
state attorney general's office says.
   But the office is advising the editor of Blythe's twice-weekly
Palo Verde Valley Times to work for an amicable settlement to his
dispute with the Blythe Community Cinema.
   Editor Harold Stanford said Tuesday he has been advised by a
deputy to Attorney General John Van de Kamp that the theater's ban
on his movie critic is probably a violation of the state's Unruh
Civil Rights Act, an interpretation disputed Wednesday by an
attorney for the theater owner.
   Stanford said Van de Kamp's office hasn't responded to his
request that the state sue the theater on behalf of the paper and
its part-time movie critic, Cathy Monnett.
   Mrs. Monnett, who works for the price of her tickets and who
refuses to review R-rated movies, was banned from the theater Dec.
14. Managers said her negative reviews were hurting business, but
she has responded that most of her comments have been positive.
   Alan Ashby, a spokesman for Van de Kamp, confirmed the office had
been asked to pursue the case, but indicated the Van de Kamp would
prefer to see the parties settle their differences amicably.
   ``We told him that the California Supreme Court ... held that the
Unruh Act can be broadly interpreted to prohibit all unreasonable
discrimination by private businesses,'' Ashby said.
   Los Angeles attorney Don Davis, brother of theater owner Paul
Davis, said he disagreed that the ban on the critic violates the
state civil rights law, because courts have ruled the law applies to
arbitrary discrimination against classes of people.
   ``If we eliminated all film critics by class, or all children, or
all women, that would be class discrimination and that would be
arbitrary,'' Davis said. ``Those same court rulings say you can
eject somebody from your establishment that's injurious to your
business.''
   Since the ban, Stanford has been sending Mrs. Monnett to Yuma,
Ariz., a round trip of more than 100 miles, to review movies that
will be shown in Blythe, a desert town along on the
California-Arizona border.
   Theater officials said they offered to let Mrs. Monnett return if
the newspaper would run reviews by a theater-hired critic next to
her reviews. Stanford rejected that offer, saying the other critic
would be ``P.R. hype in our newspaper.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
