<FIRST>r a AM-LincolnHome     02-01 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lincoln Home,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lincoln Home Site Hit By Vandals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racial slurs and obscenities
spray-painted on two buildings and a fence at the Lincoln Home
National Historic Site have been removed, officials said Wednesday.
   ``It's all been cleaned up. ... Right after we discovered it we
began cleanup,'' said acting site superintendent Larry Blake.
   Damage was estimated at $500. Pink and blue fluorescent paint was
sprayed Monday or early Tuesday on the carriage house behind
Lincoln's home, an adjacent shed and a white wooden fence behind the
shed. Meters and an air conditioner also were damaged.
   Vandalism at the site is not common, Blake said.
   ``Usually it's fairly uncommon because the Springfield community
has a great deal of respect for the Lincoln sites as a whole, so we
don't really have a lot of problems with vandalism,'' he said.
   Because the damage occurred on federal property, the FBI was
investigating, Blake said. No arrests had been made.
   The Lincoln home, the only house the nation's 16th president ever
owned, was reopened last year after a multimillion-dollar renovation.
   In 1987, Lincoln's Tomb, in Oak Ridge Cemetery several miles from
the home, was vandalized with spray paint. Five teen-agers and an
adult were arrested and later were convicted or pleaded guilty to
charges connected with the vandalism and damage to nearby graves.
