<FIRST>r w AM-ReforgerCuts     02-01 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reforger Cuts,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says U.S. Decides to Reduce Scale of Exercises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon announced Wednesday that the
United States has decided to reduce the scale of NATO's Reforger
exercises in what one defense official called an attempt ``to lower
the heat of political debate in West Germany.''
   Defense officials, who insisted on anonymity, said the changes
would allow the United States and its allies to reduce the impact of
field training on the West German public.
   The Defense Department announced its plans to change Reforger
exercises in a statement Wednesday while denying they were tied in
any way to politics. Indeed, the Pentagon's press release portrayed
the modifications as an ``enhancement'' that would allow U.S. Army
troops to ``train smarter.''
   Pentagon sources said, however, the goal of ``training smarter''
would be reached by reducing the number of troops moved from the
United States to Europe for field maneuvers; reducing the scope of
exercise maneuvers by all troops, including those posted to Europe
full time, and relying to a greater extent on computer simulations
to train battle staffs.
   ``They can call this an enhancement if they want, but we're also
trying to lower the heat of political debate in West Germany,'' said
one official, referring to growing complaints there about low-level
military flight training and plans to modernize nuclear missiles.
   ``We can't afford to lose public opinion to (Soviet President
Mikhail S.) Gorbachev and his PR campaign,'' said another source,
citing announcements by the Soviet leader of unilateral troop cuts.
   ``If we can accomplish our major training aims and lessen the
impact of our training on the populace, then we should do that. And
if we can save some money, given the budget environment back here
and concerns about sharing NATO burdens, so much the better,'' the
source said.
   In December, Gorbachev announced at the United Nations that the
Soviet Union would unilaterally cut its military forces by a
half-million troops and reduce its conventional arms substantially.
   The Reforger (Return of Forces to Germany) exercises have long
been a mainstay of American as well as NATO deterrent policy. They
normally consist of the large-scale movement of Army troops from the
United States to Europe, simulating the type of reinforcement
operation that would be needed to sustain Western forces in the
event of a Warsaw Pact attack.
   Last year's Reforger, conducted in the late summer and early
fall, involved the deployment of about 17,000 soldiers to Europe.
Once they arrived, ground and aerial maneuvers were conducted in
West Germany with a total 97,700 American and allied troops.
   On Wednesday, the Pentagon announced that Reforger 89, set for
September, had been canceled and would be merged with Reforger 90,
which has now been scheduled for January to March 1990.
   In place of Reforger 89, the allies now intend to stage a smaller
exercise dubbed Caravan Guard ``to test the improved training
techniques planned for Reforger 90,'' the Pentagon said.
   The Defense Department refused to say how many soldiers would
cross the Atlantic Ocean for Reforger 90. It did say, however, the
field manuever portion of the exercise would involve about 75,000
allied troops total _ or more than 20,000 fewer than last year.
   ``In a move designed to enable the U.S. Army Europe to `train
smarter' and ultimately improve combat readiness, the U.S. European
Command has announced a major enhancement to the Reforger exercise
program,'' the Pentagon said in its statement.
   ``The Reforger enhancement program will allow U.S. forces to
obtain the maximum training value from major exercises by
integrating new computer simulation technology, command post
exercises and field training exercises.''
   Cmdr. Mel Sundin, a Pentagon spokesman, said the Pentagon was
convinced that computer technology ``can be used to realistically
simulate a wide range of operational and logistical functions
normally carried out by soldiers in the field.''
   ``When properly integrated, these simulations will force
commanders and their staffs to make real-time decisions just as if
they were issuing orders to deployed units,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
