<FIRST>r w AM-DetroitNewspapers     02-01 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Asked to Delay Detroit Newspapers' Partial Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of the partial merger of The Detroit
News and the Detroit Free Press asked a federal appeals court
Wednesday to delay the business deal until a legal battle over the
agreement is resolved.
   The motion, filed by Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press,
a coalition of newspaper advertisers and readers, sought to halt the
newspapers' plan to proceed with the merger on Feb. 6. The group is
asking the full 13-member U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia Circuit to hear arguments for rejecting the proposed merger.
   The motion said implementing the agreement would ``result in the
elimination of approximately 500 jobs, the publication of a single
paper on weekends, increased circulation prices and probably higher
advertising prices as well.''
   The newspapers would suffer ``comparatively little harm'' should
the agreement be delayed, the motion said.
   Knight-Ridder Inc., owner of the News, disputed the contention
that the newspapers would suffer little harm from further delay. A
spokesman for the newspaper group, Frank Hawkins, said in Miami that
the delay is ``costing something in the range of $50,000 a day.''
   ``That turns into a lot of money in a hurry,'' Hawkins said.
   The News' publisher, Louis Weil, said in Detroit, ``Financially,
neither paper is making money right now. For that exact reason we
want to move forward, because all of this has gone on long enough.
   ``But even more importantly, in terms of the employees, it's time
to bring this to a conclusion. That's why we're moving forward,''
Weil said.
   Gannett Co. Inc., owner of the Free Press, declined comment from
its Arlington, Va., headquarters.
   Free Press Publisher David Lawrence said, ``In fact, the great
harm continues. Not only the harm in terms of thousands of dollars
that are lost each day, but the harm in the uncertainty which has
clouded this newspaper's future for almost three years now.''
   ``People here are entitled to know that their jobs are safe, that
their newspaper can go ahead. Readers of the newspaper are entitled
to know their paper has a future.''
   Under the proposed 100-year agreement, the News and Free Press
would combine business and production operations, while maintaining
separate news and editorial departments.
   Gannett initially would take 55 percent of the joint operations'
profits or losses. After six years, the split would be 50-50 between
Gannett and Knight-Ridder. Knight-Ridder has said it will close the
Free Press without a joint operating agreement.
   An three-judge appeals court panel, splitting 2-to-1, on Friday
rejected opponents' arguments that then-Attorney General Edwin Meese
III had gone beyond the intent of the law in approving the joint
operating agreement, an exemption from federal anti-trust laws
allowed when one of the newspapers is in danger of financial failure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
