<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpecialOperations     02-01 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Special Operations,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>2,500 Military Personnel in Nationwide Special Operations Exercise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,500 Army and Air Force
personnel are invading national forests and military bases as part
of a joint exercise designed to improve coordination between
branches of the armed services.
   The six-week training exercise, dubbed Jaguar Bite, began Jan. 9
at seven sites in six states to give troops a taste of different
terrains and climates. It ends Feb. 17.
   The exercise helps improve interservice coordination right down
to combat uniforms worn by commanders at this Army post where the
exercise is headquartered, said Air Force Brig. Gen. Hanson Scott.
   ``If you were to walk in right now you would be hard pressed to
tell who is an Army guy and who is an Air Force guy,'' said Scott,
who is deputy director of the exercise.
   Jaguar Bite is the largest nationwide exercise conducted by the
Defense Department's join special forces command since it was
created nearly two years ago.
   The reason for establishment of the U.S. Special Operations
Command, based at MacDill Air Force Base in Tampa, was to improve
coordination among special forces in the various services such as
the Army's Green Berets and Navy's SEALs.
   ``If you go back some years ago, perhaps all the services were
guilty of not having enough joint training,'' Scott said.
   Poor coordination of special operations became the targe of
congressional criticism after a hostage-rescue mission to Iran in
1980 ended in disaster. A Navy helicopter and an Air Force cargo
plane collided at a desert staging area, killing eight servicemen.
   One important aspect of training side-by-side is that members of
the different service branches learn to understand each other's
jargon and acronyms that are so popular in the military, Scott said.
   Unlike conventional military exercises, Jaguar Bite is primarily
conducted at night and with small units to simulate the unique
missions of special operations, including fast deployment over long
distances and infiltrating enemy lines.
   Scott said the exercise has been going well except for some
severe winter weather in northern states. A deployment to Michigan's
upper peninsula was delayed and troops were withdrawn from the field
in Montana.
   ``We didn't see, for a peacetime exercise, leaving the people out
there,'' he said, although they were equipped to survive the harsh
weather.
   The training sites are Fort Chaffee, Ark.; Fort Bragg, N.C.;
Helena National Forest, Mont.; Ocala National Forest, Fla.; Francis
Marion National Forest, S.C.,, Hiawatha National Forest, Mich., and
Cherry Point Marine Corps Station, N.C., where a battalion of
Marines is playing the role of an aggressor force.
</TEXT>
