<FIRST>r i AM-China-Banquets     02-01 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Banquets,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Paper Blasts Banquets, Says Parties in West Better</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper Wednesday criticized China's ``stupid
habit of banquets,'' saying they waste money and don't compare to
parties in the West.
   The newspaper Economic Information said Chinese officials eat,
drink and waste too much during their ubiquitous feasts,
impoverishing the country's coffers and threatening the health of
the revelers.
   The state-run press is engaged in a campaign to illuminate social
problems resulting from China's economic reforms, designed to open
China to the West.
   A recent article on liquor in the China Youth News, called the
Chinese spirit, maotai, an ``all-purpose grease'' for bribing
officials. Another report in the Peasant's Daily told a short story
about a young woman who became a prostitute because she loved money.
   Sunday marks the start of the Spring Festival, the lunar new year
and China's biggest holiday. Families, enterprises and ministries
regularly hold banquets during the holidays, consuming large amounts
of food and drink.
   ``In the weeks before and after the Spring Festival, who knows
how much food will be waisted and how many people will get sick
because of overindulgence,'' the article said.
   The main reason for overindulgence, the article said, was that
Chinese people are not educated enough.
   ``As soon as a stupid person gets a little money ... the first
thing he thinks about is a banquet, eating and drinking,'' said the
article, titled ``Get Rid of the Stupid Habit of Banquets.'' ``Over
time, this foolishness has become a custom that won't be changed
easily.''
   ``The poorer you are the bigger the banquet,'' the story said,
pointing to weddings.
   ``A couple with an elementary school education will fill 20
tables for their wedding banquet, those with a high school education
will reserve five, a couple who has graduated from college will
handle two tables and those with a doctorate won't even fill one,''
it said.
   Another problem is that too many dishes are served.
   ``We treat our guests as if they're starving to death,'' the
article said. ``First they're eight cold dishes, then eight hot
dishes, then a whole chicken, then a whole duck, then a giant carp,
then a hot pot, then dessert and fruit.''
   By the time the feast is over, about two-thirds of the food
remains.
   Alcohol was cited as another problem.
   ``Revelers won't rest until they make the guests drunk.'' It
said. ``The result is that both guest and host get plastered. The
lighter ones talk nonsense, the heavier ones end up getting sick on
the floor, going home and suffering the curses of their wives or
parents.''
   The story called on Chinese revelers to study parties in the West.
   ``Parties in the West are worth copying in China,'' it said. ``A
host puts some dishes on a table and lets the guest pick and choose
as they please .... Such a method is very convenient.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
