<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     02-01 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Meeting Advanced 10 Days Amid Signs of Party Split</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision to hold a key Central
Committee meeting 10 days earlier than planned fueled speculation
Wednesday about a split in the ruling communist elite over political
reforms and unpopular price increases.
   In a terse announcement after its regular weekly session Tuesday,
the party's Politburo announced the 108-member Central Committee
will meet Feb. 10 to decide ``topical political questions.''
   News that the meeting would take place earlier than the scheduled
Feb. 20 date followed a statement from party leader Karoly Grosz
that differences among the 11 Politburo members are slowing reform.
   Grosz said the Central Committee must decide whether or not it
wants to make leadership changes.
   He and Premier Miklos Nemeth also made clear in separate
statements that they disagree with fellow Politburo member Imre
Pozsgay over the leading reformer's startling weekend statement that
the 1956 anti-Soviet revolt was a popular uprising.
   Only the Central Committee can deliver the final verdict on this
matter, Grosz said, adding that he has seen no new documents backing
Pozsgay's view against the official version that the revolt, quashed
by Soviet troops invited by Hungarian leaders, was a
counterrevolution.
   Grosz also said leadership differences are impeding unpopular
austerity measures and are unsettling Western bankers concerned
about Hungary's timely repayment on its $17 billion foreign debt.
   Two waves of price increases on most consumer staples in January
have prompted strikes and unprecedented protests from the official
trade union organization, which has called for talks with the
government.
   Official statistics in January showed one in five of Hungary's
10.6 million citizens already is living below the poverty line.
   Inflation _ estimated at 12-15 percent by the government and
20-25 percent by economists _ will cut further into Hungarians'
living standards this year.
   Hungarian observers and West and East bloc diplomats noted
Wednesday that while recent political reforms have drawn praise
abroad, they have failed to lift the mood at home. Hungary recently
legalized independent movements and demonstrations.
   Some Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
they saw Grosz's statement as no more than an attempt to unify the
leadership behind reforms.
   Others, however, noted the statement implied criticism of both
Pozsgay and chief party ideologist Janos Berecz, who last weekend
suggested the party was not quite capable of ``directing the
processes'' in Hungarian politics.
   Hungary's increasingly candid state media had no independent
comment Wednesday.
   But they did print long summaries of Western press comment,
highlighting foreign speculation that recent events may presage
leadership changes.
</TEXT>
