<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1919EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev     02-01 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editor Says Gorbachev Makes Much More Than Typical Soviet Worker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev earns $28,800 a
year, about seven times the pay of a typical Soviet worker, the
editor of a muckraking Moscow weekly said Wednesday.
   Vitaly Korotich, editor of the magazine Ogonyok, told The
Associated Press that with his salary, the Soviet leader can afford
to keep his wife dressed in stylish clothes.
   Despite glasnost, Gorbachev's policy of greater openness that has
permitted magazines such as Ogonyok to flourish, the salaries,
perquisites and personal lives of Soviet leaders are not discussed
in its media.
   Korotich said in a telephone interview he had mentioned the
salary figure and Raisa Gorbachev's wardrobe in an informal talk to
student activists in Komsomol, the Young Communist League, and his
remarks were published in a youth newspaper in the republic of
Moldavia.
   Korotich, who is generally viewed as a supporter and beneficiary
of Gorbachev, said he was neither criticizing nor defending
Gorbachev in his talk.
   He said one of the students asked what he thought about Mrs.
Gorbachev wearing fancy clothes and he replied that on the
president's salary of more than 1,500 rubles a month, Gorbachev can
afford to buy her new dresses sometimes. That equals $2,400 a month
at the official rate of exchange.
   Mrs. Gorbachev's clothes, quite fashionable by Soviet standards
and often mentioned during her trips abroad, are the subject of
considerable grumbling among Soviet women who aren't accustomed to
their leaders' wives appearing in public and who suffer from a
chronic lack of food and consumer goods.
   Although Gorbachev's reported salary far exceeds the average wage
of about $350 a month, it couldn't begin to pay for the many
privileges afforded the top Soviet leadership.
   Members of the elite have limousines, special food packages,
access to special stores, summer homes, special schools and camps
for their children and other perquisites that set them apart from
typical citizens.
   While ordinary Soviets wait in long lines for items such as
coffee, detergent, fruit, vegetables and chocolate, the elite can
have such things delivered or pick them up at stores that are
off-limits to average citizens.
   Kremlin leaders and their families also are assigned apartments
that are deluxe and spacious by Soviet standards.
   Such privileges occasionally have been challenged, most recently
at the national Communist Party conference in July by Boris N.
Yeltsin, the ousted Moscow party boss who was entitled to them as a
member of the ruling Politburo. In an address to the conference,
Yeltsin, who still retains some popular support despite losing his
influential posts, called for abolition of special privileges for
the elite.
   ``If there are some shortages in our socialist society, then
everybody should share the same shortage,'' he said. ``We must do
away with elitism, eliminate the word `spets' (special) from our
vocabulary.''
   Gorbachev later said in a televised discussion with conference
delegates that ``we should take a look'' at party privileges because
there are so many popular complaints about them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
