<FIRST>u a AM-AirTanker-Sawyer     02-01 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Tanker-Sawyer,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northern Michigan Base Mourns Third Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GWINN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bitter wind whipped the flags at half staff
Wednesday as people at K.I. Sawyer Air Force Base mourned the deaths
of 17 colleagues.
   ``That's eerie, to see that flag,'' said an airman at the
northern Michigan installation. ``It's even worse to see the
families (of the victims) coming in.''
   A military refueling plane that left Sawyer on Monday crashed and
exploded Tuesday as it tried to take off from Dyess Air Force Base
near Abilene, Texas. All 19 aboard died.
   It was the third fiery crash since October involving planes
originating from Sawyer, one of the Air Force's northern tier posts
by Lake Superior.
   ``We're dealing with a base that has gone through three tragedies
in four months,'' said Capt. Paul Bicking, a Sawyer spokesman.
``I've heard different comments, such as trouble comes in threes and
now that we've had our three, we've had our trouble for awhile.''
   The 26-year-old KC-135 tanker that crashed in Texas on Tuesday
carried 17 people from the Sawyer area, along with two passengers
who boarded at Dyess.
   The plane was to escort and refuel four F-16 jets from Carswell
Air Force Base in Fort Worth, Texas, and land at Hawaii before
reaching its principal destination, Andersen Air Force Base in Guam,
Bicking said.
   Seven of the dead were members of the plane's flight and
maintenance crews from Sawyer. Air Force officials said the rest
included four civilian relatives of military personnel and four
military retirees who were taking advantage of the military's policy
of allowing them to hop overseas flights when there is space on
board.
   ``It's another plane crash,'' said Marquette resident George
Smith, sipping coffee at a local diner. ``It seems like they happen
every day now.''
   Sawyer continued routine operations Wednesday, but the close-knit
base closed ranks and effectively shut out outsiders.
   ``Our family is going through the process of mourning. We're
caring for our people,'' said the base wing commander, Col. Eldon
Joersz, in a very terse meeting with the press. He walked out
without answering questions.
   ``They're pretty devastated. We want to regroup,'' said another
base spokesman, Sgt. Joseph Butera.
   Memorial services at the base chapel were planned for Friday.
   The tension contrasted with the fortunate feeling at Sawyer
following the Dec. 6 explosion of a B-52 bomber as it went through a
touch-and-go landing on the base's main runway. All eight crew
members survived in what base personnel called a miracle.
   Three months earlier, 10 Sawyer personnel had survived the Oct.
11 crash of a KC-135 that killed six people from a sister Michigan
base.
</TEXT>
