<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-US     02-01 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Canal Officials Say They Were Roughed Up By U.S. Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Panamanian officials said they
were struck and threatened with a pistol by two U.S. military
policemen near the Panama Canal.
   A U.S. Army spokesman denied the charges but said there was
pushing and shoving between the Panamanians and the Americans.
   Jorge Luis de Leon and Miguel Tejada, officials with the Panama
Canal Commission, told a news conference on Tuesday they were
victims of ``brutal aggression'' by two military police officers
stationed with the U.S. Southern Command.
   They said they were detained Monday as they were traveling along
the Panama Canal near Gamboa.
   De Leon told reporters he was hit by the police officers. Tejada
said one officers threatened him with a 9mm pistol.
   William Ormsbee, a Southern Command spokesman, said the
Panamanians were interrogated by military police for a ``violation
of rules concerning the control of smuggled goods.''
   Ormsbee said de Leon, 39, and Tejada, 38, tried to enter an army
supply store to which only de Leon had limited access privileges. De
Leon has dual Panamanian-U.S. citizenship, he said.
   De Leon became violent when the military police officers
prevented the Panamanians from entering, Ormsbee said. Both were
questioned and released, he said.
   De Leon and Tejada did not comment on the allegation that they
were trying to enter the store.
   The Panama Canal Commission is charged with supervising the
operations of the Panama Canal. The United States is to turn over
control of the waterway to Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   The Southern Command oversees all U.S. military operations in
Latin America.
   Relations have soured in the past year. The United States has
demanded the resignation of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander
of Panama's Defense Forces and de facto ruler of the country.
   Noriega is under U.S. indictment for drug trafficking and money
laundering. He denies the charges and says the United States is
seeking a pretext to renege on its pledge to turn over the canal.
</TEXT>
