<FIRST>u w AM-Honoraria     02-01 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honoraria,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>House and Senate Prepare New Restrictions Linked to Pay Raise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pay Raise Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators forged ahead
Wednesday with separate but similar proposals to bar speaking fees
and restrict other outside income should a 50 percent congressional
pay raise become law Feb. 8.
   A bipartisan draft document, given out to senators and obtained
by The Associated Press, compares the latest House and Senate
proposals on outside income.
   Both packages would ban honoraria, including fees for speeches,
appearances and articles, upon enactment of the raise that would
boost congressional salaries from $89,500 to $135,000.
   Leaders in both houses have made clear that honoraria would
continue if the pay raise is defeated because members don't want to
suffer a loss of income. Rank-and-file House members currently can
retain $26,850 and Senate members $35,800 in honoraria.
   The Senate plan includes a contingency that would permit
retention of some honoraria if the raise is eventually scaled back.
The pay plan now before Congress can only be defeated if both houses
reject it. The Senate is virtually certain to turn the raise down,
but the question of whether the House will vote on it depends on a
survey of members' intentions ordered by Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Under the honoraria proposals, both houses would permit such fees
to be donated to charity on a member's behalf. The Senate plan would
limit the donation to $2,000 per appearance and require members to
list on financial disclosure forms the amount, the payer and the
recipient of the donation.
   The House and Senate plans would allow groups that invite members
to an event to continue paying for travel. The Senate would direct
its ethics committee to issue rules and regulations defining
acceptable limits.
   House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., has told reporters
there would likely be a time restriction on House members' travel,
with exceptions made for multi-day events.
   The House draft would prohibit members from receiving any pension
benefits from honoraria given as a charitable donation. The Senate
plan would go further, prohibiting conversion of any of the
donations to a member's personal use.
   The House plan would limit all outside earned income to 15
percent of a member's salary, half the current 30 percent.
   The House also would end a provision in federal law that has
allowed 190 House members, in office before 1980, to accumulate $39
million in campaign funds that could be converted to personal use.
The measure would become effective in January 1991, giving House
members one chance to retire with the money.
   The Senate already has a rule prohibiting such conversion.
   The House proposal would incorporate restrictions on members that
already exist under Senate rules.
   The restrictions include a ban on affiliating with business
entities for compensation, a prohibition on practicing a profession
except part-time teaching, and a ban on serving as an officer or
board member on a publicly held or regulated corporation.
   Wright and Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine,
have promised that honoraria packages will be taken up immediately
if the pay raise becomes law next Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
