<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-MassGrave     02-01 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Mass Grave,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Launched Into Allegations of Mass Grave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are probing allegations that
Kurdish guerrillas were buried in a mass grave near the garbage dump
of a southeastern city, the local prosecutor said Wednesday.
   Mustafa Erdogdu said in a telephone interview that a preliminary
investigation is checking allegations published in the Sunday
edition of the leftist weekly 2000ne Dogru (Toward 2000). He did not
elaborate.
   The weekly reported that Kurdish guerrillas killed in shootouts
with security forces, as well as suspects who died in custody, were
buried in a mass grave near the city of Siirt.
   ``The Siirt garbage dump is full of bodies,'' the magazine quoted
Zubeyir Aydar, a lawyer and the former local chief of the main
opposition Social Democrat Populist Party, as saying.
   Kurds comprise an estimated one-fifth of Turkey's 55 million
people. Kurdish guerrillas, members of the Marxist Kurdish Labor
Party, have been fighting government forces in southeast Turkey
since 1984 to set up an independent state, leaving hundreds of
people dead.
   The magazine quoted Bedria Akan, whose son Hasan Akar died in
detention in April 1985, as saying his body was never given to the
family, and she heard rumors it was dumped in the alleged mass grave.
   The report said relatives of missing people in the city had been
demanding that officials dig open the riverbed. It did not say how
many people were missing.
   The weekly said Hayrettin Kozakcioglu, the regional governor for
the southeast provinces, acknowledged that three Kurdish guerrillas,
killed in a shootout last February, were buried near the site when
nobody claimed the bodies.
   ``I have no other knowledge,'' it quoted the governor as saying.
   The governor could not be reached by phone to comment on the
report. officials in Ankara, Turkey's capital, also had no comment.
   Last month, authorities arrested 400 people suspected of aiding
the guerrillas. Opposition parties charged that some of the suspects
were mistreated and a few were forced to eat human excrement. Local
authorities denied the charges.
   Kurds also populate portions of Iran, Iraq, Syria and the Soviet
republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan. Kurdish rebels have also fought
for autonomy in northeastern Iraq.
</TEXT>
