<DOCNO> AP890201-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1927EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     02-01 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warring Factions Fail to Compromise at Communist Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A marathon debate of the Communist
Party's deeply divided Central Committee ended Wednesday with no
compromise and a stern call for the party to adopt reforms.
   ``We are divided on fundamental questions,'' committee member
Josip Vrhovec said late Tuesday. The split was so bad, he said, ``we
already have two different, clearly ideologically defined parties.''
   The first and most important part of Wednesday's meeting ended
with a speech by national party chief Stipe Suvar, who quashed
attempts to oust him by Serbian and other conservatives.
   But the session continued with a laborious discussion of
personnel issues, focusing on Azem Vlasi, a former party chief in
restive Kosovo province.
   The only agreement reached was that the party hold an emergency
congress before the end of this year to try again to overcome the
rift in the leadership over economic and political targets.
   The three-day meeting was marked by verbal clashes between
liberals advocating greater political pluralism and more democracy
and conservatives seeking greater central party control to overcome
Yugoslavia's worst crisis.
   Suvar said the choice facing the country is one of an open market
or a state-controlled one, ``between a state based on the rule of
law or the revolutionary one,'' and between political pluralism or
domination of a single doctrine.
   He urged members to create a political climate for the party to
implement ``the reforms necessary to overcome the difficult
situation in the country and to enable the Communist Party to stop
losing battle after battle.''
   Suvar referred to a statement by Adm. Petar Simic, political
chief of the armed forces, who warned Monday the party is ``losing
battle after battle.''
   ``What some describe as the battle for Yugoslavia will not be
waged without the Yugoslav army,'' Simic said.
   The session also was marked by a sharp clash and heated exchanges
over Suvar's sentiments toward Serbia between the national party
chief's political allies, mainly from the liberal northern republics
of Slovenia and Croatia, and supporters of hard-line Serbian party
chief Slobodan Milosevic.
   Suvar described as ``pure fabrication'' accusations that he is
biased against Serbian interests.
   Apparently referring to Serbian hard-liners, he said: ``We have
to overcome the quarrelsome and intolerant thinking that only one
truth exists and that all other opinions must be defeated.''
   Suvar also has drawn strong support from the central republic of
Bosnia and southern Macedonia region, as well as from some delegates
of Kosovo, where Albanians are a majority.
   ``We don't have time for compromises,'' said Ali Sabani, an
ethnic Albanian. ``A battle is being waged to liquidate this Central
Committee, the Presidium (Politburo) and its president, according to
a well-known scenario.
   ``The same scenario would then be used on the (federal state)
presidency,'' Sabani said in clear reference to Milosevic and his
alleged ambitions in national politics.
   Conversely, a Serbian speaker asked, ``Can this leadership take
us out of the crisis?''
   The final decision was left to the 23-member ruling Politburo,
but it is highly unlikely it will relieve Suvar before his term
expires in June.
   The next scheduled party congress is to take place in 1990. The
extraordinary congress is to take place at an unspecified date later
this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
