<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-StealthMissile     02-01 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Missile,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Approves Test Of Advanced U.S. Cruise Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will let the United States test an
unarmed version of a highly advanced cruise missile over western
Canada, the defense minister said Wednesday.
   The missile will fly from the Beaufort Sea in the Arctic, across
northeastern British Columbia and over northern Alberta to a
military weapons range on the Alberta-Saskatchewan border.
   The missile, known as the AGM-129A, is more advanced than other
U.S. air-launched cruise missiles tested over Canada since 1983.
   The low-flying, cigar-shaped weapon, which uses the stealth
technology being applied to other U.S. defense systems, is better
able to avoid radar detection, officials say.
   Defense Minister Bill McKnight said the missile test is expected
to be conducted before March 31.
   The cruise missile tests have been controversial in Canada since
they began. Opponents of the test argue that the missile could be
used as a first-strike weapon. Supporters say it is a deterrent.
   The defense minister said the Warsaw Pact already has a
significant and improving cruise missile capability.
   ``We support the pursuit of mutual arms reduction, a process that
can only move ahead effectively if both sides are dealing from
equivalent positions,'' McKnight said.
   The missile is capable of carrying conventional or nuclear
warheads.
</TEXT>
