<FIRST>r a AM-Weather-Coping     02-01 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weather-Coping,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents, Farmers Cope With Blast Of Wintry Cold</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Below-zero temperatures in February are not in
themselves big news in the Plains, but residents found the 70-degree
drops in temperatures bracing and farmers found them worrying.
   ``Hot chocolate, hot coffee, donuts and hot dogs, anything that's
hot'' sold big Wednesday at Sapp Bros.-Sidney truck stop in western
Nebraska, said its manager, Mike Machamer.
   Business was up about 20 percent as people came in from the cold,
Mike Machamer said. But no one appeared to be stranded, he said.
   Police expected to give more people rides to shelters as the
homeless try to get off the street, Capt. William Crawford said. And
the Cornhusker Motor Club had a rush of 112 calls from motorists in
the Omaha area Wednesday morning _ 70 percent more than the previous
day, most wanting jump starts, said Rose White, public affairs
director of the AAA motor club.
   Farmers and ranchers faced particular problems, as the
temperature plunge endangered both crops and animals.
   ``It's a shock to anything's system when you have a 100-degree
drop in (wind-chill) temperature,'' said Tom Scott, executive
director of the Nebraska Beef Industry Development Board.
   Barb Rishel of North Platte said her husband, Bill, went to their
ranch south of town Tuesday night to be sure the herd bulls were
properly bedded down and to keep an eye on cows that were calving.
Sheds, straw and heat lamps are used for newborns and their mothers,
Mrs. Rishel said.
   The cold wind had winter wheat growers worried.
   ``The thing that would concern us most is the lack of snow cover,
and then the second part that concerns us is the sudden change in
temperature,'' said Steve Baenziger of the University of
Nebraska-Lincoln agronomy department.
   ``Normally when we have these kinds of temperatures, ... the crop
gets used to being cold,'' he said. ``Now, we've got something
that's unbelieveable _ record highs, and suddenly within one day we
go to cold temperatures.''
</TEXT>
