<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AfghanMines 400   02-01 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan Mines, 400</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Teams Helping in Hunt for Afghan Mines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, at the request of the United
Nations, has sent a small team of military experts to teach Afghan
rebels and refugees how to clear land mines, officials said
Wednesday.
   The U.S. team, consisting of about 30 trainers and support staff,
has been sent to Pakistan and will work with Afghan rebels and
refugees in camps on the Pakistani side of the Afghanistan-Pakistan
border, the officials said.
   Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman, said acting
Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV authorized the deployment ``at
the request of the United Nations' coordinator for humanitarian and
economic assistance programs.
   ``The Defense Department team consists of about 30 military
personnel who will remain in Pakistan for about six months in
support of a U.N. command structure,'' Schneider continued.
   ``The team is to instruct Afghan refugees in mine awareness and
mine-clearing techniques. U.S. military personnel will not be
permitted to enter Afghanistan, and all training activity will be
conducted in Pakistan.''
   Schneider said the American team consisted of Green Berets from
the 2nd Battalion of the 5th Special Forces Group at Fort Campbell,
Ky.
   The disclosure of the deployment came as the State Department
accused the Soviet Union on Wednesday of continuing widespread
bombing attacks inside Afghanistan. Spokesman Charles Redman charged
that ``unprecedented destruction'' has occurred as Soviet troops
withdraw.
   The Soviet Union has agreed under a U.N.-sponsored settlement to
withdraw all of its troops by Feb. 15. Soviet troops invaded
Afghanistan in 1979 to prop up a Marxist government and have been
fighting the Mujahedeen resistance ever since.
   According to the Pentagon, the Soviets have scattered an 10
million to 30 million mines across the country during the past nine
years. United Nations officials are now concerned that thousands of
Afghan refugees will return to their country after the Soviet
withdrawal without realizing the scope of the mine threat.
   ``The training program designed for the refugees is intended to
make the refugees aware of the threat and to provide a cadre of
Afghan refugees trained in mine-clearing,'' Schneider said Wednesday.
   The spokesman added the United Nations had designated the effort
``Operation Salam,'' but the Pentagon is calling its contribution
``Operation Safe Passage.''
</TEXT>
