<HEAD>Police Demand Villagers Turn Over Corpse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with chiefs arrested. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABEOKUTA, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday arrested three
village chiefs in southern Abeokuta state after villagers refused to
hand over the corpse of a slain lawman.
   Police threatened to attack the towns of of Loti, Luwaji and
Ogbere on Tuesday, and most of the villagers fled. On Wednesday,
officers surrounded the towns and arrested the chiefs of each.
   The arrests came one week after three policemen were attacked in
the area while chasing a man suspected of receiving stolen goods.
The bodies of two of them, Inspector Adisa Obawunmi and Constable
Johnson Akinfenwa, were found in a shallow grave.
   Sgt. James Olayinka remained missing. On Tuesday, Abeokuta Police
Commissioner Vincent Ugwumba said: ``So far not a goat or a hut in
the villages has been destroyed. But if we don't see the corpse we
will let our men loose.''
   Police have arrested 28 people from the villages, about 45 miles
northwest of Lagos.
   He said people from the same villages in 1965 killed 35 policemen
whose corpses were never found.
