<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDS-Drugs     02-01 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Drugs,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>New AIDS Aerosol Drug Could Help Tens of Thousands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of AIDS patients could be
helped by an experimental drug soon to be approved in aerosol form
by the Food and Drug Administration, AIDS activists said Wednesday.
   The drug, pentamidine, is believed to have some effect in
preventing pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, which causes an estimated
60 percent of AIDS deaths.
   ``It is a dramatic breakthrough in terms of offering a preventive
treatment for the most deadly'' infections that strike people whose
immune systems have been depleted by AIDS, said Jeffrey Levi,
executive director of the Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
   FDA approval of widespread distribution of the aerosol drug is
``imminent,'' FDA spokesman Donald McLearn said.
   The FDA would not say how many people it expected would have
access to the drug, but Levi estimated ``tens of thousands of people
would be eligible.''
   Pentamidine was approved five years ago for use as an injectable
drug. The spray version under FDA review would make it easier to
take into the lungs where pneumocystis first shows up.
   The FDA decision would be in a special category that allows
widespread distribution of promising drugs before they are approved
for commercial distribution. Normally, the government requires years
of studies before permitting general use of a drug.
   Until a drug receives full approval, its use normally is not
covered by government or private health insurance policies. Often
during experimental use of a drug, the manufacturer distributes it
free to patients.
   LyphoMed Inc. of Rosemont, Ill., the leading supplier of
injectable pentamidine and the company expected to be licensed to
supply the aerosol version, said it would release information about
its plans for the drug next week.
   AIDS activists have complained that the government has moved too
slowly in permitting the use of promising drugs for people who have
the AIDS virus. However, activists praised the FDA action, which is
expected next week.
   ``It's quite important as a symbol, an example of the FDA moving
faster than it has in the past,'' said Thomas Hannon, associate
director of the New York Community Research Initiative, which
conducted one of the studies on the aerosol form of pentamidine.
   ``They've talked a lot about a faster approval process for drugs
for life-threatening diseases like cancer and AIDS, and this is
encouraging,'' he said.
   Levi said, ``It's an indication that the process is working
better.''
   But he added, ``People are cautious because they don't know how
the drug will be available and the conditions'' FDA will place on
its use.
   Not all AIDS activists, however, praised the FDA's work on
pentamidine.
   ``This should have been fully approved by now,'' said Mark
Harrington of a New York-based group called AIDS Coalition to
Unleash Power.
   About 50 members of the group rode a bus to Bethesda, Md., on
Wednesday to attend a meeting of a government panel that is studying
ways to reduce approval time for AIDS and cancer drugs.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The chief
victims of AIDS have been homosexual men and intravenous drug
abusers.
   The Federal Centers for Disease Control said that as of Jan. 30,
84,985 AIDS cases had been reported in America. More than half,
48,582, have died. There have been 2,228 new cases reported since
Jan. 1, the CDC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
