<FIRST>r a AM-ParkSquatter     02-01 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Park Squatter,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Sues In Attempt To Prevent Squatter's Eviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DERBY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 71-year-old woman who maintains a
ramshackle homestead at an undeveloped state park has sued the state
in an effort to prevent her eviction.
   In the lawsuit filed Tuesday in Derby Superior Court, attorney
John Williams said the eviction of Doris Gagnon would be unnecessary
and would shorten her life.
   ``I personally feel if they take her out of there and demolish
that little compound she has put together and put her in a nursing
home, she won't live very long,'' Williams said.
   Williams is seeking an injunction preventing the state from
trying to evict Gagnon, who has cancer, for five years or for the
rest of her life, whichever is shorter.
   Williams said he decided on a five-year time limit because it
would take the state at least that long to come up with funds to
develop the park, on land along Long Island Sound.
   Leslie Carothers, the state's commissioner of environmental
protection, said she had no comment because she hadn't read
Williams' suit. Carothers' department is pursuing eviction of Gagnon.
   Gagnon's homestead is near the site of her former home, which the
state condemned and demolished in 1971 to make way for the park. She
has lived since in a makeshift compound that includes a trailer and
coops where she keeps chickens.
   State authorities servied notice in November that they wanted her
off the land after receiving a complaint from Milford health
officials that her presence represented a nuisance to the public
health.
   During a summer inspection of the property, health officials said
they found bags of human sewage piled up behind her living quarters.
The homestead is served by no public utilities.
   State officials said they also took action at this time because
development work is expected to begin this summer and they want to
avoid delays.
</TEXT>
