<FIRST>r w AM-Japan-AircraftTechnology     02-01 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Aircraft Technology,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urged Not To Make Hasty Decision on U.S.-Japanese Fighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of top-level U.S.-Japanese talks,
five senators on Wednesday urged President Bush to conduct a
complete review of a pending deal under which Japan would receive $8
billion in advanced aircraft technology.
   In a letter to Bush, the senators said the deal involving the FSX
fighter raises serious questions about its ``long-term impact on the
health and competitiveness of the American aerospace industry.''
   Sending the letter were Sens. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.; Alan Dixon,
D-Ill.; Wendell Ford, D-Ky.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; and Frank
Murkowski, R-Alaska.
   They noted that during the visit of Japanese Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita on Thursday and Friday there likely will be
``intense pressure ... to give the full commitment of the president
to the program.''
   ``However, to do so without a full assessment of the program's
long-term impact would not be in the best interests of the United
States,'' the senators told Bush.
   Under the proposed deal, Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries
would develop and produce a new-generation Japanese fighter using
technology for the U.S. F-16 fighter obtained from General Dynamics,
which would serve as a subcontractor to Mitsubishi.
   This ``co-development'' effort would be in lieu of directly
purchasing fighters from the United States or manufacturing them
under U.S. license.
   Critics of the deal contend it would delay strengthening of
Japan's defense forces, due to time needed to design and build the
FSX, and go too far in furthering development of the Japanese
aircraft industry in competition with the United States.
   In their letter to Bush, the senators complained that
negotiations over the FSX have been carried out by the State
Department and Pentagon without involvement of the U.S. Trade
Representative and the Commerce Department.
   ``We are requesting that you order a complete review of the FSX
program within the administration, including the departments of
Commerce, Labor and Energy, as well as the Office of the Trade
Representative and the White House science office,'' the letter said.
   It added: ``We hope that your administration will refrain from
any further commitments on the FSX until that review has been
completed and the Congress has been fully consulted.''
   During his confirmation hearings last week, Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower told senators he would review the
agreement, negotiated during the Reagan administration.
   At the State Department, officials said a review was currently in
progress, after which the department hoped to proceed on the
arrangement by giving Congress the required 30-day formal notice in
which to object to the technology transfer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
