<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Plot     02-01 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Plot,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Claims Foreign Plot Against Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday it has been
the target of foreign secret service plots to destabilize democracy.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos commented on a
pro-government newspaper report that recent scandals were a plot by
the CIA to undermine Socialist Premier Andreas Papandreou, whose
government is driving a hard bargain in talks on a new U.S. bases
treaty.
   ``Greece has certainly been the target of foreign and domestic
circles,'' Kostopoulos said at his daily press briefing. He did not
elaborate.
   The Avriani newspaper alleged that the CIA and the Mafia are
orchestrating a plan to slander slander Papandreou so that ``the
removal of the American bases by 1999 will not be realized.''
   ``Americans don't like him since he is not a yes-man,'' it said.
   The U.S. Embassy refused comment.
   The United States is negotiating a new military bases agreement
with the Greek government after an agreement expired in December.
Thirteen rounds of talks have failed to resolve the major issues,
and another round is scheduled next month to determine whether four
major installations remain or are closed down.
   Avriani said the alleged plot was based on the CIA Psychological
Warfare Manual and involved using the political opposition and the
press to slander the premier and to implicate government officials
in scandals and crimes.
   Multimillion-dollar financial and arms scandals have plagued the
Socialist government for months and have caused the resignation of
seven Cabinet members since November.
   The entire political opposition has called for Papandreou's
resignation so early general elections could be held before the
government's term is up in June. The prime minister has refused to
step down and described the scandals reported by most of the daily
press as slanderous.
   The latest scandal broke out Tuesday over how much was paid to
buy 40 French-made Mirage 2000 jet fighters.
   The conservative New Democracy party reported that the government
said it paid $40.5 million for each aircraft when purchased in 1985.
   The government, however, announced that the price was $19.4
million and angrily denied anti-government newspaper Eleftheros
Typos' allegation that Papandreou kept some of the money earmarked
for the purchase.
   Kostopoulos said this latest allegation was an example of a
``miserable scenario of slandering the premier.''
</TEXT>
