<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineBabies     02-01 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Babies,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Number of Cocaine Babies Up Dramatically</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crack Kids, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of ``cocaine babies'' born in Illinois
rose to 978 during the last half of 1988, a 78.8 percent increase
over the same period a year earlier, officials said.
   ``We had predicted this, but we were astounded that these numbers
were increasing to the point that our fears were answered,'' said
Gordon Johnson, director of the Illinois Department of Children and
Family Services.
   ``Cocaine babies'' are those who have had the drug in their
systems either as fetuses or as infants, ingesting it through their
mother's breast milk, said agency spokesman Dave Schneidman. The
babies aren't addicted, but the drug's effects may linger long after
the narcotic itself is gone, he said.
   No end to the rise is in sight, making it more expensive and
difficult for the department to find foster homes for the children,
Johnson said in a telephone interview Wednesday from Springfield.
   The total of 978 cocaine babies for the last six months of 1988
compares with 547 babies during the same period in 1987, the
department said. About ninth-tenths of cases during both periods
were in Cook County, which includes Chicago and surrounding suburbs.
   In addition to drug abuse, the cases raise concerns about child
abuse.
   Babies whose mothers take cocaine during pregnancy _ even once _
can be born with problems that make them harder to care for once
they are home.
   Besides seizures and breathing problems, such babies are
irritable.
   An addicted mother who comes home with a ``crying, screaming''
baby is much more likely to abuse it or neglect it, Johnson said.
   ``That's the kind of child that ends up in our system,'' he said,
noting that recent increases in child-abuse cases are partly
attributable to drug-affected infants whose parents lose patience in
caring for them.
   Drug-affected babies have a higher rate of premature birth, are
more likely to be retarded and are at an increased risk for crib
death, among other problems, said Dr. Ira J. Chasnoff, director of
the Perinatal Center for Chemical Dependence at Northwestern
Memorial Hospital.
   The problem is not limited to big cities or states where cocaine
is a notorious problem, Chasnoff said Wednesday.
   ``Places you'd never expect are seeing cocaine-exposed infants,''
he said, citing Boise, Idaho; Medford, Ore., and Peoria, Ill.
   ``The numbers are escalating rapidly,'' Chasnoff said. ``There's
no question that stronger prevention programs have to be instituted
across the country.''
   The National Committee for Prevention of Child Abuse estimates
that 375,000 babies _ or 10 percent of those born each year _ have
illegal drugs in their system, said Deborah Daro, research director
for the Chicago-based group.
   Doctors and hospitals are required to report cocaine babies to
the family services department, Schneidman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890201-0196 </DOCNO>
