<FIRST>u w AM-ColoradoCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0734 02-01 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colorado Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0734,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Blames Pilot's Cocaine Use In Colorado Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 to delete duplicate reference to date, show that
investigators determined pilot was not ``high''; ADDS 6 grafs with details
on drug tests, lawsuits.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators on Wednesday for the
first time blamed cocaine use by a pilot as a contributing factor in
a commercial airline crash in which passengers were killed.
   The National Transportation Safety Board concluded that pilot
Stephen Silver, who was killed in a Jan. 19, 1988, Colorado commuter
crash along with eight other people, used cocaine several hours
before the flight from Denver to Durango.
   Although board investigators said Silver, 36, did not have enough
cocaine in his system to be ``high'' and his co-pilot was believed
to be controlling the Trans-Colorado aircraft's descent into
Durango, the board concluded that cocaine contributed to his
``ineffective monitoring of an unstabilized approach.'' The
co-pilot, Ralph D. Harvey, 42, was also killed in the crash. The
plane carried 15 passengers.
   Medical analysis found traces of cocaine in the pilot's blood and
urine, investigators said. They also said a girlfriend of the pilot
reportedly claimed he had taken cocaine the night before the crash,
although she refused to talk to investigators.
   Board officials said it was the first time that cocaine use by a
pilot had been ruled a factor in a crash involving a regularly
scheduled commercial passenger flight. Alcohol use has been blamed
in some previous accidents.
   Board investigator Barry Strauch said evidence showed that Silver
had used cocaine between 10 and 18 hours before the flight. He said
there was not enough evidence to determine whether Silver was a
heavy user of the drug.
   Board chemist Merritt Birky said that regular use of cocaine
could cause fatigue and a preoccupation with cocaine, affecting
performance of a pilot long after the substance was no longer giving
the user a high.
   The Fairchild Metro 3 aircraft operated by now-defunct
Trans-Colorado airlines crashed on a hillside five miles short of
the Durango runway in light snow.
   The board concluded that the plane began its descent at too high
an altitude and speed to land safely.
   The board also said the pilot had falsely obtained a medical
certificate required for flying by denying that he had a record
involving drunken driving. Investigators said Silver had several
traffic citations, including some involving drunken driving.
   The board also said the co-pilot had a prior employment and
training record that indicated ``deficiencies in performing
instrument procedures.'' The plane was landing at night in light
snow and a cloud cover.
   ``The probable cause of this accident was the first officer's
flying and the captain's ineffective monitoring of an unstabilized
approach which resulted in a descent below the published descent
profile,'' the board said in a report adopted after more than three
hours of discussion in an open hearing.
   ``Contributing to the accident was the degradation of the
captain's performance resulting from his use of cocaine before the
accident,'' the board said.
   The board recommended that the Federal Aviation Administration
require inspectors to personally examine special approaches such as
the one into Durango. The approach is over mountainous terrain and
sometimes referred to as a ``slam-dunk'' approach because of the
steep descent that is sometimes necessary.
   Board members said the FAA should help airlines obtain more
information from previous employers about the piloting skills and
abilities of prospective pilots.
   Staff investigators told the board Silver earned about $23,000 a
year and his co-pilot half as much. Board chairman James L. Kolstad
characterized the salaries as ``incredibly low.''
   The board said there was no technical problem with the aircraft
and air traffic control did not contribute to the crash.
   But it said a ground proximity warning device, if the plane had
had one, might have prevented the accident. The FAA is considering
rules to require smaller passenger planes to install the devices
which are used on all larger passenger airliners.
   The NTSB last March released a toxicology report that showed
Silver had .022 micrograms per millileter of benzoylecgonine, the
principle metabolite of cocaine, in his bloodstream.
   The report also said he had 1.8 micrograms per millileter of
metabolized cocaine and .022 micrograms of cocaine in his urine.
   Two negligence lawsuits have been filed against Continental
Airlines as a result of the crash. The plane owned Trans-Colorado
was leased to Rocky Mountain Airways, a Continental subsidiary that
flies under the name Continental Express.
   One suit, filed on behalf of Laura LaVigne, wife of the late
Kevin LaVigne of Denver, who was killed in the crash, seeks
unspecified damages because of the cocaine found in Silver's system.
   LaVigne's lawsuit also alleges the airline failed to check
records of both Silver and Harvey, which ``would have cast serious
doubt upon the propriety of hiring those pilots.''
   The other lawsuit, filed by relatives of the late Don Emergy Cox,
of Corpus Christi, Texas, also cites Silver's cocaine use.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
