<FIRST>r i AM-CostaRica-Hull     02-01 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Hull,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bail Set for Jailed American</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge recommended bail of $12,500
for John Hull, an American linked to the U.S.-backed Nicaraguan
rebels and charged by Costa Rican authorities with drug trafficking,
Hull's attorney said Wednesday.
   Attorney Elda Zuniga also said proceedings against Hull were
ordered transferred to the northern city of San Carlos.
   Costa Rican authorities arrested Hull Jan. 13 on charges of drug
trafficking and violating Costa Rican security.
   A 4th District Court judge in San Jose on Tuesday provisionally
set $12,500 bail, Ms. Zuniga said.
   She said a superior court tribunal in Alejuela Province, where
the trial is being moved, must accept the recommended bail amount.
The tribunal will officially set the bail on Monday, Ms. Zuniga said.
   Hull, 69, suffered a heart attack Jan. 24 as he was awaiting a
hearing in the capital's San Sebastian Jail and was moved to the
Mexico Hospital.
   Hospital director Matias Quezada said n Wednesday that Hull's
condition has improved, and he was recuperating in a regular
hospital room.
   Ms. Zuniga said she asked the court to transfer Hull's case to
San Carlos because that is where the crimes allegedly took place.
   Hull owns a ranch in Los Chiles, near San Carlos, which is about
104 miles north of the capital.
   A native of Indiana, Hull moved to Costa Rica 20 years ago and,
according to Ms. Zuniga, became a naturalized citizen of the Central
American country eight years ago.
   Ms. Zuniga maintains that her client is charged under a drug law
passed in 1987 and that the law is not retroactive. Hull is charged
with actions that allegedly occurred in 1984, she says.
   Sources in the Office of Judicial Investigations have said Hull
was arrested for investigation into charges of drug and weapons
trafficking and spying for the Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras.
   The sources said they acted after residents near Hull's farm in
Los Chiles denounced activities by Hull. The acts were seen as
possibly endagering releations between Nicaragua and Costa Rica,
they said.
   Witnesses testifying before Congress on illegal arms shipments to
the Contras said Hull's ranch was a way station for gun smugglers
and cocaine traffickers.
   Hull was not among 13 men indicted in September in Miami on
charges of running an illegal arms network for the Contras. Reports
said Hull was granted immunity by the special prosecutor in the case.
   Hull has strongly denied any connection to drug trafficking.
   Hull also was among 29 people named in a civil suit filed last
year by two journalists. Tony Avirgan filed the suit with his wife,
Martha Honey, after being wounded in a 1984 bombing blamed on the
defendants.
   A U.S. district judge in Miami ruled in favor of the defendants,
saying the plaintiffs failed to prove their contention that a
conspiracy was behind the new conference bombing.
   Eight people were killed and the apparent target, then-Contra
leader Eden Pastora, was wounded.
