<FIRST>u a AM-FamilyPoisonings     02-01 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Poisonings,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor To Act On Richardson Case, May Hold Clemency Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmworker who claims he was framed in
his 1968 conviction for poisoning his seven children has had his
case taken up by the governor who called Wednesday for a clemency
hearing.
   ``I am convinced there are still many questions about the
Richardson case that need answers,'' Gov. Bob Martinez said at a
news conference. ``The interests of justice compel us to seek those
answers.''
   James Richardson, 53, is challenging his murder conviction on the
grounds that new evidence indicates he was framed and someone else
has confessed to the killings.
   His case given to Dade County state attorney Janet Reno in the
3-month-old investigation because there is conflicting information
in the case and she has subpoena power, Martinez said.
   ``There were seven deaths. We can't forget that,'' Martinez said.
``Seven little ones died and someone was found guilty. If there was
a wrongdoing at that time, we would like to know about it. Justice
ought to prevail, whatever it may be.''
   Three of the six members of the governor's independently elected
Cabinet will have to agree with Martinez's request for a clemency
hearing before one can be scheduled.
   The Cabinet and Martinez, sitting as the board of executive
clemency, have the power to pardon Richardson. Aides to four of the
Cabinet officers said their bosses had not yet been briefed on the
case.
   A fifth, Attorney General Bob Butterworth, was ready to support
Martinez's request, an aide said. The sixth did not immediately
return telephone calls.
   The governor's office and the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement have been investigating the matter since October, when
the credibility of the 20-year-old case came under scrutiny.
   In December, Richardson's defense attorneys filed a petition in
the Florida Supreme Court seeking another trial because of new
evidence, and won a Feb. 9 hearing.
   Defense lawyers Ellis Rubin of Miami and Mark Lane of Washington,
D.C., contend prosecutors framed Richardson and that a neighbor who
frequently baby-sat with the children was the killer.
   Attorneys have said that if a new trial is granted, the passage
of time may make it impossible to assemble a credible case, either
for the defense or prosecution, because witnesses have died and
memories have faded.
   When Richardson and his wife were picking fruit on Oct. 25, 1967,
their children, aged 2 to 8, ate a lunch of beans, rice and grits
laced with the higly toxic pesticide parathion.
   The lunch had been prepared ahead of time, but was served by the
neighbor at the family's Arcadia home.
   Richardson is serving a life sentence in Tomoka Correctional
Institution near Daytona Beach. He is eligible for parole in 1993.
He had been sentenced to death but that was reduced to life in
prison when the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the state's
death-penalty statute in the early 1970s.
   Prosecutors said he murdered all seven children, but he was
convicted of only one first-degree murder count in May 1968 for the
death of his 8-year-old stepdaughter.
   The petition for a new trial includes claims that evidence was
withheld. Also, his attorneys say they have statements from two
nursing home employees caring for the former neighbor, 67, that she
admitted killing the children.
</TEXT>
