<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Japan     02-01 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Japan,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita Offers Namibia Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN AYON LEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita of Japan on
Wednesday offered to send about 30 civilian observers to Namibia
this year to monitor elections, his spokesman said.
   Takeshita made the offer during a meeting with Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar, said Koichi Haraguchi, a Japanese Foreign
Ministry spokesman.
   Japan's previous contributions to U.N. peacekeeping efforts have
been largely financial.
   ``There is a sort of increasing recognition among Japanese people
that simply to supply money is not enough. We should also offer our
sweat,'' Haraguchi told reporters.
   Takeshita, who arrived in New York on Tuesday, made no public
statements at the United Nations. On Thursday, he is to meet in
Washington with President Bush.
   Takeshita, who will be the first foreign head of government to
meet with Bush since his inauguration, is to return to Tokyo on
Tuesday.
   Perez de Cuellar and Takeshita met with U.N. officials in charge
of monitoring Namibia's transition to independence from South Africa.
   Under a U.S.-brokered agreement intended to bring independence to
Namibia and peace to southern Africa, Namibia is to hold its first
free elections for a national assembly on Nov. 1.
   The United Nations is expected to send about 800 election
supervisers to Namibia, a territory South Africa has controlled as
since World War I.
   As part of the agreement, Cuba agreed to withdraw troops helping
Angola's Marxist government fight South Africa- and U.S.-backed
guerrillas.
   Besides offering to send about 30 observers to Namibia, Takeshita
offered $134 million in aid to help Afghan refugees, Haraguchi said.
   He also offered $13.5 million for Namibia peacekeeping efforts
and $2.5 million for general peacekeeping purposes, Japanese
officials said.
