<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PearyHoax     02-01 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peary Hoax,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foundation Says Peary Notes Provide No Evidence of Faked Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A page of calculations made by Admiral
Robert E. Peary provides no evidence that he faked his claim to have
reached the North Pole in 1909, a non-profit navigators group said
Wednesday.
   The findings by The Navigation Foundation leave open to scholarly
debate whether Peary reached his destination.
   ``Properly understood, this worksheet says absolutely nothing
about whether Peary reached the pole,'' said retired Rear Adm.
Thomas D. Davies, president of the foundation, which was
commissioned by the National Geographic Society to look into the
Peary controversy.
   ``The paper provides no evidence Peary faked his claim,'' Davies
said in a presentation at the Naval Academy planetarium _ complete
with laser images to highlight the star Betelgeux that he believes
Peary used as a guide.
   Peary's claim has had many detractors. One of the most vocal is
Dennis Rawlins, an astronomer and historian who grabbed headlines
last fall when he concluded that Peary lied about his location and
used Betelgeux, a star that wouldn't have been visible when the sun
was up 24 hours a day, to hide the truth.
   ``Suggesting Peary might not have reached the pole is one thing;
declaring him a fraud is another,'' said Gilbert M. Grosvenor,
president of the National Geographic Society, which helped
underwrite Peary's 1909 expedition, in attacking Rawlins' contention.
   After publishing a 1970 article and a 1973 book arguing that
Peary was off course, Rawlins went further last October, saying the
worksheet unsealed in 1984 showed Peary 121 miles shy of his
destination.
   Davies said three experts determined the calculations likely were
made in February 1906 during an earlier Arctic expedition, not April
1909 as written on the envelope in which Peary's wife apparently
placed them.
   Davies said Rawlins interpreted one set of numbers as compass
readings when they were ``serial numbers of the watch-type
chronometers Peary carried with him.''
   ``Rawlins assumes that the worksheet shows altitude observations
of the sun taken on April 7, 1909, when Peary says that he was at
the pole,'' Davies wrote in the foundation's report. ``Rawlins'
analysis is clearly incorrect. The numbers Rawlins assumes are
degrees, minutes and seconds of arc can also be interpreted as
hours, minutes and seconds of time,'' he wrote.
   Rawlins interrupted the meeting to defend himself, calling the
Navigation Foundation report ``a very competent presentation,'' and
admitting his error on the chronometer serial numbers.
   ``In terms of the (National) Geographic versus me, this is one
for the Geographic,'' he said.
   However, he maintained that the readings were taken in 1909 and
said he has 10 pieces of evidence that Peary didn't make it to the
North Pole.
   Davies said the foundation will review other data and the Peary
archive as it continues to evaluate Peary's claim.
   Wally Herbert, a British explorer writing in the September 1988
issue of National Geographic, found that Peary was 30 to 60 nautical
miles off course. Rawlins found Peary came no closer than 121 miles
from his goal, but because of difficult conditions and low supplies
felt pressured to say he had reached the North Pole.
   Retired Cmdr. Edward P. Stafford of Chester, Md., Peary's
grandson, defended his grandfather's integrity. ``He was accurate.
He has always been shown to be where he said he was, when he said he
was,'' Stafford said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
