<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Sakharov     02-01 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Sakharov,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Candidacy Subject of Press Debate, Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei D. Sakharov said Wednesday that his defeat
in a bid to represent the Academy of Sciences in a new Soviet
parliament showed the academy's ruling presidium is not ready for
democratic reform.
   But Pravda, the Communist Party daily, rejected suggestions that
undemocratic procedures were used to block Sakharov's nomination.
   The 67-year-old dean of the Soviet human rights movement again
has become a controversial figure in Moscow, but this time he is
being both criticized and defended in the state-run press that once
either ignored or vilified him.
   A band of Sakharov's supporters called a meeting for Thursday to
protest his Jan. 18 electoral defeat, although he was nominated two
days later as a parliamentary candidate from a Moscow district.
   Sakharov is among several thousand candidates for the new
2,250-seat Congress of People's Deputies, a parliamentary body that
will be elected in March and which will in turn elect a full-time
legislature and a president.
   There is little doubt President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who
proposed creation of the new parliamentary body, will be re-elected
head of state.
   Sakharov was quoted in the weekly Literary Gazette, a newspaper
popular among Soviet intellectuals, as saying the nominating process
in the Academy of Sciences worked well at the lower level, where
younger scientists hold sway.
   But when the leadership made its final picks, he said, only top
administrators were picked to represent the prestigious academy in
the new parliament, which will have representatives from both
geographic districts and from professional, political and social
organizations.
   He charged the leadership failed to fulfill its legal obligations
and ignored the popular will in selecting its candidates.
   Pravda, however, said the meeting at which Sakharov was defeated
``was not only fully democratic but benevolent.''
   After his defeat in a bid to represent the academy, he won the
overwhelming support of members of his own institute as a candidate
for a seat in the district where the academy is located.
   Sakharov is a physicist who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen
bomb and later won a Nobel Peace Prize for his human rights
activities.
   The government newspaper Izvestia, meanwhile, criticized Sakharov
for suggesting in an interview with the French newspaper Le Figaro
that Gorbachev could be toppled or stymied by Soviet conservatives.
   It said such statements, unsupported by solid information, cause
confusion and uncertainty and can only harm Gorbachev's reforms.
</TEXT>
