<DOCNO> AP890201-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hess     02-01 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hess,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scotland Yard Investigated Claims Hess Was Murdered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scotland Yard said Wednesday that it investigated
claims Nazi war criminal Rudolf Hess was murdered in a West Berlin
prison, contrary to the official ruling that he committed suicide.
   A Scotland Yard spokesman, who refused to be identified in
keeping with British custom, refused to comment on the outcome or
any other details of the investigation by its serious crimes squad,
made at the request of the Director of Public Prosecutions.
   ``The DPP asked us to investigate suggestions that Hess did not
die by his own hand,'' Scotland Yard, said in a brief statement. ``A
preliminary report has gone to the DPP for his decision on whether
any further action is needed.''
   The statement did not say why Scotland Yard, which coordinates
national police work, was asked to investigate the possibility of
murder.
   The Director of Public Prosecutions directs the Crown Prosecution
Service, which handles the prosecution of criminal proceedings begun
by police forces.
   Hess' family believes Hess, Adolf Hitler's deputy held by Allied
nations in a prison in Spandau in the British sector of West Berlin,
did not commit suicide but was murdered Aug. 17, 1987, at the age of
93.
   The spokesman said Scotland Yard did not investigate a British
doctor's claims that a Hess impostor was murdered in the prison.
   ``It would appear from this (Scotland Yard) statement that we
accept the premise that he was who he said he was,'' he said.
   Dr. Hugh Thomas, who has written two books on Hess, says Hess was
murdered while flying to Scotland on a peace mission in 1941 and
that an impersonator in a second plane was substituted by plotters
among Hitler's deputies.
   Hess parachuted alone into Scotland on May 10, 1941, but concerns
about his identity were raised even then.
   Thomas said he has seen unpublished reports of two autopsies and
unpublished photographs of the body in Spandau showing marks on the
neck inconsistent with a suicide hanging.
   The autopsies, he said, also supported his contention that the
prisoner did not bear scars of a severe chest wound Hess suffered in
World War I.
   He alleges that the prisoner was murdered to stop the leak of
details of a World War II plot by powerful Britons to overthrow
Prime Minister Winston Churchill.
   Thomas, a surgeon who was a British army doctor when he examined
the prisoner in Spandau in 1973, first made his claim that the
prisoner was not Hess in his 1979 book, ``The Murder of Rudolf
Hess.'' The other book he wrote on the subject, ``Prisoner No. 7,''
was published last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
