<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Dali     02-01 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Dali,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dali Leaves Everything to Spanish State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late surrealist painter Salvador Dali
left his entire estate to the Spanish government, the Ministry of
Culture said Wednesday.
   Dali died of heart failure Jan. 23 in his hometown of Figueras at
the age of 84. Media reports have indicated the estate is worth
about $87.7 million, but the ministry made no mention of its value.
   The ministry said it was informed by notary public Jose Maria
Foncillas Casaus that a will dictated to him by Dali in September
1982 named the Spanish state as the painter's sole heir.
   The ministry said it was ``grateful for the great generosity of
the exceptional creator toward the Spanish people and assumes with
full responsibility the obligations that derive from this legacy, in
particular the requirement to `conserve, make known and protect his
works of art.'''
   During the last years of Dali's life, there was speculation his
principal merchant and agent, Robert Descharnes, and Antoni Pixot, a
painter and close family friend, would be named beneficiaries of his
will.
   Dali is survived by his sister, Ana Maria, 80, from whom he had
been estranged many years.
   The Barcelona daily La Vanguardia said Tuesday that the estate
consists of 250 Dali paintings, at least 50 said to be of
``considerable value,'' numerous drawings and works by other
artists, the Pubol castle in the village of La Pera, a house in the
port of Cadaques and some land around Figueras. All the properties
are in the northeastern region of Catalonia.
</TEXT>
