<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland 1stLd-Writethru   02-01 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0736,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Bomb Kills Soldier</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS 6 grafs to UPDATE with two more bombs. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA bomb hidden in a
drainpipe outside a pub exploded, killing a British soldier and
wounding another as the two walked by on patrol, police said
Wednesday.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army, which is fighting British
rule in the province, claimed in a coded message to news
organizations that it was responsible for the Tuesday night attack.
   The bomb exploded as a joint army-police foot patrol passed the
pub Tuesday night in the Falls Road area, a Roman Catholic enclave
and IRA stronghold in west Belfast.
   Police said infantryman Pvt. Nicholas David Peacock, 20, who was
on his second day of duty in Northern Ireland when the attack
occurred, died early Wednesday while undergoing surgery for wounds
to his legs and lower body.
   The other soldier suffered slight injuries, officials said.
   Peacock's father, David, who lives in Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's hometown of Grantham in Lincolnshire, said: ``It is
barbaric that a lad out on peaceful patrol should be blown up like
that. But it won't alter my position one bit. I still believe the
army should stay put. It has my full backing.''
   A police spokesman said on condition of anonymity that the bomb
was concealed in a drainpipe on the wall of the pub and contained
about 2 pounds of explosives ``with a command wire running to an
entry at the rear'' of the pub.
   The predominantly Catholic IRA is fighting to oust the British
and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic Irish
Republic under a leftist administration.
   Later, a bomb attached to a lamppost exploded, injuring one
policeman slightly, as police evacuated an area in Belfast city
center, a police spokesman said.
   Police began clearing an area of Oxford Street after a bomb was
thrown over the wall of a police station Wednesday evening. The bomb
failed to explode but as police evacuated the area, a second bomb
went off, the spokesman said.
   He said the injured policeman was treated at a local hospital and
released.
   No one claimed responsibility, but two men were being questioned
about the bombing, the spokesman said.
   Also Wednesday evening, a bomb was thrown at a joint police and
army patrol in Londonderry city center, the spokesman said.
   Police fired at the bombers but were ``not claiming any hits,''
he said. No one was injured.
</TEXT>
