<DOCNO> AP890201-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle     02-01 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Delays Space Shuttle Launch To Replace Turbopumps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA said Wednesday night it is
delaying the launch of Discovery from late February to mid-March to
replace three suspect turbopumps whose failure could be fatal to a
shuttle and its crew.
   The announcement came following a high-level meeting of shuttle
managers who have debated for several days whether to pull the
high-speed turbopumps, which transform liquid oxygen into gas in the
spaceship's main engines.
   Officials said Discovery will be transported to the launch pad
early Friday and switching of the pumps will be done there in
parallel with other operations. The first pump could be pulled as as
early as Sunday.
   Because of the uncertainty of the availability of new pumps and
the length of time to make the replacements, NASA said it would not
set a firm launch date until a flight readiness review in late
February.
   It said the earliest the launch could take place would be in
mid-March. The agency had been aiming for a Feb. 23 liftoff, but a
series of technical delays not related to the pumps already had
delayed that date several days.
   If the date slips past mid-March, the planned April 28 launch of
Atlantis with the Magellan-Venus probe would also have to be
delayed, officials said.
   The three turbopumps became questionable when engineers
discovered two tiny cracks in a bearing unit in one of Atlantis'
pumps after it completed the second post-Challenger mission in
December.
   The engineers believe the cracks were caused by stress corrosion
resulting from moisture trapped inside the bearing housing during
the manufacturing process. But they are not certain how the moisture
penetrated the metal.
   Officials became concerned when it was learned that two of
Discovery's pump bearings had gone through the same manufacturing
process as the cracked one.
   They decided at Wednesday's meeting to remove all three pumps and
replace them with new, carefully-inspected units.
   The turbopumps operate in flight at extremely high speeds,
pressures and temperatures, and a failure of one of them could set
off a fatal engine explosion. The cracks on Atlantis were too small
to cause trouble, but if such cracks widened and split the bearing
unit, it could be dangerous, NASA said.
   The agency has said the Atlantis mission in April has priority
over the launch of Discovery with its communications satellite and
that it would scrub the Discovery flight until later in the year if
it can't get off the pad by about March 15.
   That's because the Atlantis astronauts have only a 25-day launch
window that is favorable for dispatching Magellan to Venus. Earth
and Venus will not be in proper alignment again until 1991.
   NASA said it could delay the Atlantis flight a few days, but
that's something it would not like to do. It would like to preserve
the entire launch window in case of problems.
   Only one shuttle launch pad is currently available. A second is
being refurbished.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890201-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 2323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     02-01 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudanese Cabinet Reshuffled; Fundamentalists Retain Seats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi on Wednesday
announced a new government with Moslem fundamentalists retaining two
key posts, indicating a continued tough stance against southern
Christian and animist rebels.
   Hassan Turabi, leader of the fundamentalist National Islamic
Front, was named foreign minister and deputy premier, and a member
of his party, Hafez Sheikh Zaki, justice minister and attorney
general, the official Sudan News Agency reported.
   The Islamic Front's retention of the foreign and justice
portfolios gives it an influential voice in any peace talks with the
rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, a predominantly Christian and
animist group that opposes Islamic law.
   Five of the 10 new appointments went to Mahdi's Umma Party, the
principal coalition partner, four to the Islamic Front and one to a
southern party.
   Defense Minister Abdul-Majid Khalil of the Umma Party retained
his post.
   The new 24-member coalition comprises 11 Umma ministers, seven
from the National Islamic Front, five from small southern parties
and one from the Sudan National Party of western Sudan, the news
agency said.
   Turabi, who was justice minister and acting foreign minister, was
among seven ministers whose resignations were accepted Tuesday by
Sudan's five-member State Council, which acts as a collective
presidency.
   It is Mahdi's fourth government since he became the first elected
leader in 16 years in April 1986. The military ousted longtime
strongman Gaafar Nimeiri a year earlier.
   The lingering civil war in the south, famine and drought, then
floods, have destablilized the country. Sudanese staged strikes and
demonstrations in December to protest government price increases.
   The latest shakeup was prompted when the Democratic Unionist
Party, the second-largest in the Constituent Assembly, quit the
coalition last month. The party signed a peace accord in November
with rebel leader John Garang, a renegade army colonel.
   The agreement's provisions included suspension of Islamic law
during peace negotiations.
   Turabi, the premier's brother-in-law, has been at the center of
debate over the tentative peace agreement and controversy over the
fate of Islamic law, or Sharia, which Nimeiri decreed in September
1983.
   Mahdi has spoken of possible amendments to Islamic law, and this
would give the Justice Ministry, still held by the National Islamic
Front, a key drafting role.
</TEXT>
