<FIRST>u w AM-Lujan     02-01 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lujan,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Approves Lujan Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manuel Lujan, President Bush's choice for
Interior secretary, won unanimous approval for the Cabinet post
Wednesday in a vote by the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee.
   The committee approved Lujan's nomination by a 19-0 vote in a
session lasting less than 30 minutes. The former New Mexico
congressman is expected to win swift approval by the full Senate.
   Lujan, 60, who spent 20 years as a member of the House, breezed
through a hearing of the panel last week. Both Republicans and
Democrats had praised him.
   During the hearing, Lujan said he and Bush are ``committed to
protecting and enhancing'' the natural resources while allowing
needed development.
   Lujan's nomination has only received a lukewarm response from
environmental groups, however. They have raised concern about the
former congressman's voting record on environmental matters.
   During two decades in Congress, Lujan received consistently low
ratings from the League of Conservation Voters, the lobbying arm of
the major environmental organizations. The group said Lujan voted in
favor of pro-environmental legislation only twice out of 16 test
votes cast.
   At the same time, he has been characterized as a pragmatist and
strong advocate for the varying interests of the West.
</TEXT>
