<FIRST>r a AM-Sheriff-Bombing     02-01 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sheriff-Bombing,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Say Someone Paid To Have Louisiana Sheriff Bombed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men accused of detonating a remote-control
bomb that seriously wounded a sheriff were to be paid $20,000 for
killing him, according to a federal document unsealed Wednesday.
   The six-page federal complaint was made public one day after
Marshall K. McClendon, 42, of Slaughter and John Tullier Jr, 23, of
St. Amant were arrested in connection with the Dec. 15 bombing.
   Lafourche Parish Sheriff Duffy Breaux nearly died from shock and
blood loss when his foot was nearly severed in the blast, doctors
say. One of his deputies was also injured.
   ``A few days before Christmas, McClendon and Tullier went to
Baton Rouge to get paid for the bombing. They returned to
McClendon's barn with $8,000 cash. They were to receive an
additional $12,000 for a total of $20,000 for the completed job,''
the complaint said.
   The information was provided by an unidentified source who knew
both men and had talked with them about the bombing, according to an
affidavit that was part of the complaint. The document does not say
who wanted Breaux dead or why.
   More arrests are expected, said Mike Hall, special agent in
charge of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms office in New
Orleans.
   The source cited in the complaint said McClendon claimed to have
placed the bomb in a paper bag next to the sheriff's car. McClendon
said he set off the bomb after he saw Breaux approach the bag and
kick it, the affidavit said.
   The complaint said BATF experts in Atlanta determined that the
bomb was a wooden box encasing two pipes loaded with explosives,
nails and bullets. It appeared to have been detonated by a model
airplane remote control device.
   According to federal agents, McClendon is a former police officer
in New Orleans and Baton Rouge. He also held a Lafourche Parish
Sheriff's Office commission and was involved with a drug task force
in the parish in the early 1970s.
   Tullier was described as an unemployed instrument fitter.
   In a brief hearing in Baton Rouge Wednesday, a magistrate ordered
the two men sent to New Orleans for a bond hearing to be held in the
next 10 days.
   If convicted on bombing and conspiracy charges, each man could
get up to 25 years in prison and a $25,000 fine, said Stewart Allen,
another ATF agent.
   Breaux, 60, and Deputy Daniel Leche, 62, were injured as they
left a Christmas party for senior citizens at a civic center.
   Doctors were able to reconnect Breaux's foot and predicted he
would regain 90 percent use of it within a year. He was discharged
from the hospital last month. Leche was released after two days in
the hospital.
   In addition to the federal charges, Lafourche Parish prosecutors
Wednesday charged the men with two counts each of attempted murder.
U.S. Attorney Ray Lamonica of Baton Rouge said the federal charges
would be addressed first.
</TEXT>
