<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Sick 2ndLd-Writethru a0718 02-01 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Sick, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0718,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ailing Bush Cancels Speech, Cuts Short Another</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 5th graf with 3 grafs of Bush and First Lady comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, offering ``a thousand apologies
for the way I sound,'' canceled one speech and drastically shortened
another Wednesday as he continued to battle a bad case of laryngitis.
   Bush, who has had a cold for about a week and whose voice has
been steadily deteriorating, canceled a speech before the National
Association of Religious Broadcasters at a downtown hotel.
   Later in the day, he lasted less than a minute in an appearance
before a business group at the Executive Office Building next to the
White House before turning the microphone over to Chief of Staff
John Sununu, who continued the speech in his behalf.
   White House deputy press secretary Roman Popadiuk said Bush
backed out of the first speech because ``it was advisable that he
rest his voice at this time.''
   But in the evening, Bush was well enough to host a a reception
for more than 400 diplomatic heads of mission, standing for more
than an hour in a lengthy receiving line and then mingling briefly
with the guests.
   Bush told reporters he was feeling much better after having taken
antibiotics for an ear condition, and was now only suffering from a
hoarse voice.
   ``It's nice,'' said his wife, Barbara. ``He doesn't yell around
the house.''
   Hoarse voice aside, Bush was animated in his brief appearance
before the annual meeting of the National Association of
Wholesaler-Distributors.
   ``Thank you all very much for being here and a thousand apologies
for the way I sound,'' Bush said.
   Victor Kanners, chairman of the organization, told Bush: ``Don't
worry about it. We've learned to read your lips.''
   Sununu, delivering Bush's speech, appealed to the organization to
help rally support within the business community for the
yet-to-be-announced deficit reduction proposals that Bush will
outline to Congress on Feb. 9.
   He also thanked the group for its early endorsement of Bush's
presidential candidacy.
   Bush's voice has been getting worse by the day.
   At a speech Tuesday in Norfolk, Va., Bush sounded very raspy.
Later, he joked that he had been ``just croaking away'' and had
worried during the speech that he would not be able to complete it.
   Despite his cold, Bush went to work about 7:15 a.m. Wednesday and
had a series of appointments extending past 5 p.m. Bush and his
wife, Barbara, were to host a black-tie reception for the diplomatic
corps at the White House.
   Meanwhile, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater, who has
been complaining of flu-like symptoms, called in sick Wednesday
after leaving work early on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
