<FIRST>u i AM-KabulDiplomats 1stLd-Writethru   02-01 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kabul Diplomats, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0695,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Departing U.S. Diplomat Says Kabul May Fall By July</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Afghan envoy in Britain saying
government troops have unused arsenal, Salang battle was caused by rebel's
refusal to open highway; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Western and neutral diplomats in
Afghanistan believe President Najib's government will fall by July
without Soviet military support, the senior envoy from the closed
U.S. Embassy in Kabul said Wednesday.
   ``There's no support there'' among the people, Jon D. Glassman
told a news conference the day after the last 11 U.S. Embassy staff
members left the Afghan capital.
   ``The regime in many senses is like a building without its
girders,'' said Glassman, who was charge d'affaires at the embassy
for the last 18 months. ``I think there's a general consensus among
most informed observers that the life of the regime is likely to be
short.''
   In London, Afghanistan's top diplomat to Britain contended that
government forces have been stockpiling arms to defeat the
insurgents.
   ``Afghanistan will use arms it has so far refrained from using,''
Afghan Charge d'Affaires Ahmad Sarwar told a news conference at the
House of Commons. He would not elaborate.
   The Soviet Union, which sent troops to its southern neighbor nine
years ago to prop up a teetering Marxist client government, is in
the final stages of withdrawing troops who numbered 115,000 a year
ago.
   Only about 15,000 Soviet soldiers remain in Afghanistan,
according to Western and Soviet diplomats. They are to be gone by
Feb. 15 under a U.N.-sponsored accord.
   When asked how long Najib's forces can hold out against Moslem
guerrillas in the snow-covered mountains surrounding Kabul, Glassman
said: ``This is a work for a crystal ball.''
   But he added: ``In Kabul, most of the Western and neutral
diplomats are betting between now and July.''
   The United States closed its embassy on Monday, citing fears that
security will deteriorate because of the Soviet departure. The West
German Embassy shut down Saturday. Several others are expected to
follow suit within a few days and others have sharply reduced the
size of their stafs.
   Sarwar said countries that have shut their missions in Kabul had
not been in danger.
   ``We believe they are leaving as part of psychological warfare
waged against the Afghan people for the last 10 years,'' he said.
``These countries may really wish to turn Kabul ... into a land of
rubble.''
   Glassman rejected those accusations, made previously by other
Afghan government officials. ``I think the evolution of events are
foreordained already by 10 years of war, 10 years of foreign
intervention and the people's objection to that.''
   He said anyone looking for ``physical existence'' that Najib's
government is faltering need only look to the Salang Highway,
Kabul's food and fuel lifeline to the Soviet Union and Afghanistan's
fertile northern plains.
   The road can easily be blocked by the guerrillas, he said.
   On Jan. 23, Soviet and Afghan government forces launched what the
U.S. State Department described as a ``scorched earth'' policy on
villages along the Salang Highway, the only land route for Soviet
troops leaving Kabul.
   Diplomatic and guerrilla sources said hundreds of Afghan
villagers died in the coordinated campaign of bombing raids,
artillery attacks, missiles and ground assaults.
   Sarwar said the battle with the guerrilla forces of rebel
commander Ahmad Masoud followed a refusal by Masoud to keep the
highway open.
   ``It has proved to our people who our real friends are,'' Sarwar
said of the battle.
   ``Our friendship with the Soviet Union will continue on a much
warmer and wider scale,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
