<FIRST>r a AM-DEA-Corruption     02-01 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DEA-Corruption,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Former DEA Agents Charged With Drug Dealing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former Drug Enforcement Administration
agents, one of whom remains a fugitive, were charged Wednesday with
dealing in large quantities of cocaine and heroin and stealing drugs
from the DEA vault.
   The ex-agents previously had been charged with conspiring to
launder more than $600,000 through Swiss banks. That money was
believed connected to drug trafficking, but no drug charges had been
filed previously.
   Also Wednesday federal authorities posted a $20,000 reward for
information leading to the arrest of former agent Darnell Garcia,
41, of Palos Verdes, who has been on the run since two other agents
were arrested Nov. 22.
   Those agents, John Jackson, 39, of Claremont and Wayne
Countryman, 45, of Walnut pleaded innocent Dec. 19 to
money-laundering conspiracy and tax evasion charges. They face trial
later this year, and may be arraigned on the new charges Thursday.
   The new, 32-count indictment charges the three with dealing in
kilograms of heroin and ``hundreds of kilograms'' of cocaine. It
accuses Garcia and Jackson of stealing heroin from the DEA vault
Oct. 5, 1984 and Garcia of taking 3 pounds of heroin from the vault
Jan. 30, 1985.
   They also are accused of working with known drug dealers Mahlon
Steward and Conway and Ron Waddy. The Waddys, associated with jailed
drug kingpin Elrader Browning Jr., allegedly were hidden by Garcia
and Jackson for three days in June 1987 in an apartment rented by
the former agents.
   Garcia is charged with alerting Ron Waddy later in June 1987 that
he might soon be arrested. Prosecutors have said Garcia also is
suspected to alerting Browning, who last year was convicted of
running a California-to-Michigan cocaine and heroin ring.
   An arrest warrant also was issued Wednesday for a man named
Sherman Lair, charged in the indictment with helping the agents
distribute drugs in Los Angeles, New York, Detroit, Chicago and
elsewhere.
   Barbara Jackson, the wife of the accused former agent, also is
charged in the indictment with helping her husband launder money
through Swiss banks. She was to be summoned to court without arrest.
   Garcia, who investigators thought had fled to Europe, was seen in
early January in suburban North Hollywood, posing as an agent on a
stakeout. In another incident, he apparently used an assumed name
and posed as a DEA agent to ask Los Angeles police officers to help
him search for a man. They consented, but no one was found.
   The previous seven-count indictment, issued Dec. 7, charged the
ex-agents with hiding unreported income by transferring large
amounts of U.S. currency to Switzerland between 1984 and 1987.
   Garcia's girlfriend, Maria Zuniga, 33, has been charged with
lying to a federal grand jury when she said she had no knowledge
that Garcia maintained overseas bank accounts.
   Jackson, an agent from 1972 until his resignation in 1987, has
been held without bail, while Countryman, an agent from 1977 until
being granted disability retirement in 1986, is free on $120,000
bail.
   Garcia was an agent from 1978 until resigning in August 1987.
</TEXT>
