<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Accuses Honduras Of Attacking, Extends Cease-Fire, Lifts
Radio Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Honduras accused of attacking
border post. Pick up 4th pvs, `Each side...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist government reported
Honduran troops attacked a border post Wednesday. Officials extended
a unilateral cease-fire with U.S.-backed rebels and allowed two
radio news programs to return to the air.
   The Defense Ministry said Honduran troops used mortar, rocket and
rifle fire to attack a Nicaraguan army border post at Aguas
Calientes in the northern province of Nuevo Segovia. A ministry
statement did not say if there were casualties.
   Nicaraguan troops obeyed standing orders not to return fire, a
ministry spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The Honduran government had no immediate reaction.
   President Daniel Ortega's office said Tuesday the one-month truce
extension is intended ``to make it easier for counterrevolutionary
groups to put down their weapons, accept amnesty and join the normal
life'' of the country.
   Nicaragua's Sandinista government and rebels, known as Contras,
agreed on a temporary cease-fire in March 1988. Since the failure in
June of talks to convert the agreement into a permanent truce, the
Sandinistas have declared unilateral cease-fires.
   Each side accuses the other of violations.
   The last clash was Jan. 28, when a youth and two children were
killed in Chontales province, about 125 miles east of Managua. The
Defense Ministry said they were caught in the crossfire.
   The peace talks were held as part of an agreement Nicaragua and
four other Central American countries signed in August 1987. Its
provisions include greater democracy, amnesties, a ban on use of
territory of one country by rebels of another and internal
reconciliations.
   The Interior Ministry said it had authorized two radio newscasts
to return to the air Wednesday.
   The government canceled the Radio Mundial newscast Oct. 13 for
allegedly carrying out ``a defamatory campaign against the
government.'' A program on Radio Corporacion was canceled Oct. 31
for allegedly broadcasting false information critical of the
government.
</TEXT>
