<HEAD>US, Honduras Paratroopers Begin Joint Exercises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with gunmen firing on human rights
leader's business. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Honduran paratroopers began
a month of exercises Wednesday as part of joint military maneuvers
scheduled to last into July.
   Troops from the 82nd Airborne Division at Fort Bragg, N.C., and
about 500 Hondurans were taking part at Palmerola air base, 50 miles
northwest of Tegucigalpa.
   Between 400 and 500 U.S. troops have been rotating into Honduras
every two weeks for the exercises since the beginning of January.
   The operations include building schools, community buildings and
a road.
   The countries have conducted frequent joint exercises in Honduras
since 1982.
   Also Wednesday, police said gunmen fired on a business owned by
Ramon Custodio Lopez, president of the Honduran Human Rights
Commission. The office was vacant at the time of the attack and no
one was hurt.
   The clandestine Anticommunist Action Alliance threatened to kill
Custodio Lopez and four other rights activists for the Jan. 25
assassination of former armed forces commander Gen. Gustavo Adolfo
Alvarez Martinez, who helped Nicaraguan rebel forces in the early
1980s.
