<FIRST>u i AM-Quayle 2ndLd-writethru a0740 02-01 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-writethru, a0740,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: to udpate, 2 new grafs at end</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle, arriving
Wednesday on his first visit to Latin America, discussed anti-drug
efforts with Colombia's president, declared staunch U.S. opposition
to any Latin ``debtor cartel'' and got a birthday serenade from U.S.
Embassy workers.
   The vice president arrived a day before inaugural ceremonies for
Venezuela's new president, Carlos Andres Perez. His first of several
scheduled bilateral sessions was with Virgilio Barco of Colombia.
   Quayle mostly listened as Barco talked about how much Colombia is
doing to combat drugs and guerrillas, ``and how much help they need
from the United States,'' said Quayle's press secretary, David
Beckwith.
   He said Quayle congratulated Barco on ``those courageous steps''
but pointed out that U.S. resources to help out are limited.
   Following the meeting, Quayle commented, ``We had a very good
discussion. ... I've got a very good feel'' for the Colombians'
views.
   Later Quayle met with Perez, and was to meet with outgoing
president Jaime Lusinchi before attending a reception for U.S. and
Venezuelan business leaders at the residence of Ambassador Otto
Reich.
   Quayle told reporters he viewed his trip, the first foreign
diplomatic mission for the Bush administration and Quayle's first
visit to Latin America, as a chance to meet with foreign leaders,
``to eyeball them, to get a feel where they're coming from on some
of these sensitive issues.''
   Later, addressing about 200 employees at the U.S. Embassy, he
said he had come ``to show the interest of the Bush administration
that we have in Latin America and to show our enthusiasm for the
development of democracy in Central and South America and the
Caribbean.''
   The embassy workers presented him with a birthday cake decorated
with a U.S. flag and also a cupcake that they said symbolized the
tight federal budget at home. They sang happy birthday to the vice
president, who turns 42 on Saturday.
   Entering the busy capital by motorcade, Quayle created a
cacophony of horn-honking when he decided to stop and buy some
bananas, guavas and mangoes at a small corner fruit market.
   ``Stimulating the economy already,'' he joked to reporters as he
left the market, having bought two bags of fruit.
   Quayle said on arrival that his primary mission was to be ``a
cheerleader for democracy.''
   But the massive debts owed by Venezuela and other Latin countries
was expected to dominate much of the discussion among some two dozen
heads of state attending the inauguration.
   Quayle indicated the United States is maintaining a hard line on
so-called debtor cartel movements to form a unified organization of
Third World nations that face huge national debts.
   Speaking to reporters aboard Air Force Two just before landing in
Caracas, Quayle said such ideas are ``counterproductive.''
   ``We're absolutely opposed to the idea of a debtor's cartel,''
Quayle said. ``Our strong position is that a debtor cartel is a
non-starter.''
   Venezuela's new president, Perez, has indicated he will take a
leadership role on the Latin debt issue and has rejected a
coordinated effort in which the Latin countries would deal with
their creditors.
   Venezuela's debt is about $30.3 billion. On Dec. 31 the country
joined many other debtor governments and suspended payments on the
principal of most of that debt.
   Latin American countries owe more than $440 billion combined.
   Quayle said that during his talks with Perez and other leaders
the debt issue would certainly come up and he would voice U.S.
opposition to any cartel efforts.
   Quayle told reporters that he wasn't bringing ``a new initiative
from the United States'' on the debt issue. ``I will be there to
listen to their concerns.''
   He said the Bush administration is willing to hear suggestions by
the Latin leaders about how to solve the debt question.
   After their meeting, Quayle and Perez said they discussed the
debt situation, but gave no specifics.
   Quayle called the talk ``frank and candid,'' saying, ``I'm much
more informed and I appreciate the meeting.''
   They said the subject of Nicaragua also came up. Perez, who
supported the leftist Sandinistas in their 1979 overthrow of
Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza, has indicated he wants to take
a leadership role in helping to resolve the Nicaragua's current
strife and further the regional peace efforts spearheaded by Costa
Rican president Oscar Arias.
   A source close to Quayle said Perez and Quayle had a lively
discussion during which they agreed to disagree on the debt
question, but agreed on the need work for democracy in Nicaragua and
Panama.
   Quayle's national security adviser, Carnes Lord, said the Bush
administration is not rejecting any coordinated effort by the Latin
Americans to address their creditors. The administration would balk
at formation of an organization that would amount to a cartel, but
might be open to suggestions on other kinds of multilateral meetings.
</TEXT>
