<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Feb. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declaring ``faith must be accompanied by
concrete actions,'' Pope John Paul II in his annual Lenten message
urges all Christians to undertake more initiatives to help ``those
who suffer from hunger.''
   Lent, a penitential season leading to Easter and recalling the 40
days Jesus fasted in the wilderness, begins Feb. 8 on Ash Wednesday.
   The pope's message, released here and in Vatican City, called for
sharing of ``goods with those who have none'' and strengthening of
programs to make people ``self-sufficient in providing their own
food.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Lutherans in the world increased
182,334 in 1988 to a total of 59,745,877, reports the Lutheran World
Federation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Long Island Episcopal Diocese, which
since 1976 has spurned the denomination's policy of ordaining women,
now plans to ordain three Feb. 18.
   The diocese's new Coadjutor Bishop Orris G. Walker Jr. said he
will conduct the ceremony, involving three women who have been
eligible for it for several years. Bishop Robert C. Witcher had
declined to ordain women.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPLHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eternity, an evangelical monthly founded 38
years ago by the late Presbyterian Pastor Donald Grey Barnhouse,
ceased publication this month with its January issue
   It said circulation and advertising revenues weren't meeting the
costs.
   Executive Editor Donald McCrory said subscribers will begin
receiving World, a ``sister publication'' that also seeks to ``bring
biblical principles to bear on the reporting of current news.''
   World is a weekly published in Ashville, N.C., by God's World
Publications.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greater representation of blacks at every
level of Southern Baptist life was urged at a denominational
conference on race by the Rev. Richard Land, new head of the
denomination's moral-concerns agency.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholics and Lutherans in Chicago have
announced an agreement on a covenant, pledging them to deeper
relationships and mutual prayers for unity.
   Chicago's Catholic Cardinal Joseph Bernardin and Lutheran Bishop
Sherman G. Hicks said the covenant would be formally signed in May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop K. H. Ting, president of the China
Christian Council, says there now are about 5 million Protestants in
China, six times the number there in 1949 when communists took over
the government.
   Ting, a senior leader of the church in China, gave the figure in
an interview in Bridge, a Christian bimonthly here.
   He says new churches are opening at the rate of about three every
two days, and there now are about 5,000 of them.
   Estimates have put the number of Catholics at about 3 million.
</TEXT>
