<FIRST>s a BC-HotelEvictions Adv05   02-01 1140</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hotel Evictions, Adv 05,1170</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Once-Grand Carillon Crumbles As Elderly Tenants Ponder Their Fate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Jose and Juanita Pichardo, Cuban
immigrants in their mid-60s, owning a tiny beachfront room for their
golden years was the payback for 30 years of hard work and modest
living in New York City.
   Hedy Werner wanted a retirement free of mortgage payments and
troubles when she paid nearly $30,000 cash for a room on the 12th
floor of the Carillon Hotel. Now she says her money went to
``gangsters.''
   The dreams of nearly 300 people who say they thought they were
buying security in the form of rooms at the once-grand hotel soured
almost as fast as developer Isaac Gamel sold 72-year subleases on
rooms in 1983.
   Rooms were bought for as little as $20,000 as an investment
believed to be secure through 2055.
   Five years later, the 17-story, 600-room hotel on Miami Beach is
mired in lawsuits, bankruptcies and foreclosures, back under control
of its original property holder, Main Realty, and the tenants face
eviction.
   Main Realty slipped eviction notices under tenants' doors in
November, setting a Jan. 2 deadline. Tenants on Dec. 20 sued all the
principals in the Carillon. In late December the landlord agreed not
to take any action until the case is heard in court, expected
sometime late this year.
   Despite the reprieve, many tenants are worried and confused, and
feel deceived. Many of the elderly residents could lose their
investments, and _ because they are living on fixed incomes _ fear
for their future.
   ``To live here was to live on top of the world,'' Pichardo, 67,
said wistfully as he walked across the hotel's virtually empty pool
deck.
   Juanita Pichardo recalls when the couple used most of their
savings to buy a small room overlooking the pool for $27,000. ``The
hotel was beautiful and everything was working. It had entertainment
at night _ bingo, movies, orchestras on the weekend. Now I realize
it was too good to be true.''
   At the height of what usually is a bustling winter season, only a
handful of residents _ with their own chairs since the hotel removed
nearly all of the chaise lounges _ sit around a sediment-filled
pool. Birds splash the water since the pool was shut down by the
county health department.
   The resort, whose hotel license hasn't been renewed pending
further inquiry by the state, is a haven for crack cocaine addicts;
the rooftop once used as a luxury health spa is littered and reeks
of urine.
   Two full-service outdoor bars are stripped bare, sheets cover
missing chandeliers in the cavernous Art Deco lobby and the
restaurant has long been closed. Residents complain of a faulty
phone system, unreliable elevators, leaky pipes, graffiti and
garbage-strewn stairwells.
   Street people rove the 1957 white-and-aqua-trimmed resort, which
has been cited for multiple code and fire violations.
   ``A lot of older ladies are afraid to come out at night,'' said
Bart Steinman, who rents a room. ``When they bought the place, they
were promised the world. Basically, they're living in an abandoned
building.''
   Jose and Juanita Pichardo, a retired bartender and seamstress,
live on Social Security of $650 a month and some interest income.
Their mortgage payments are $393 a month, plus $224 a month for
maintenance.
   ``It's a very bad situation,'' Mrs. Pichardo said. ``Really, I am
a good fighter. But some days, I just get disgusted.''
   The stressful situation recently landed tenant association
president Lee DuLimba in the hospital with a burst ulcer.
   ``These people come in, abuse the law 100 percent and get away
with it,'' said DuLimba, who has spent the past 2{ years fighting to
improve conditions at the rat-and-roach infested hotel. He says his
life has been threatened, and two bullets from a .44 Magnum were put
through his front door.
   Joseph Ganguzza, the tenants' attorney, says unsophisticated
investors were taken in a murky real estate venture that never was
economically viable. He and tenants also say the city has taken no
serious enforcement action despite the building having been written
up for violations dozens of times.
   ``It's a regular stop,'' said senior license inspector Janice Tye.
   City inspectors acknowledge that even though the hotel's owners
have not been in compliance, they apparently have not paid fines.
   ``The whole problem stems from changes in ownership'' that make
enforcement difficult, said fire inspector Russell White.
   The tenants' $5 million lawsuit seeks an injunction against the
evictions, and damages for fraud, Ganguzza said. Defendants are Main
Realty Inc., which owned the property originally and holds it again;
Carol Management Corp., which leased from them; and Gamel _ who had
purchsed the rights to lease property _ among other individuals and
companies associated with the Carillon.
   Main Realty says tenants face eviction because of hundreds of
thousands of dollars in back rent and maintenance fees. Ganguzza
maintains the tenants have paid all along; where that money went is
part of the dispute.
   The problem is not new to South Florida, but Ganguzza said this
complex case is fairly unusual. ``Of course, elderly people are more
vulnerable to these type of schemes,'' he said.
   Gamel's attorney, Michael A. Hanzman, said his client was
sympathetic to the problems at the Carillon but wasn't to blame.
   ``It appears as though a large majority of the problems ... are
the result of actions that were taken by parties who operated the
hotel after Mr. Gamel sold his interest in the master lease'' in May
1987, though operating control was transferred in mid-1986, Hanzman
said.
   Ed Quinton III, attorney for Main Realty, had no comment on the
suit.
   Meanwhile, rumors swirl and the air hangs heavy at the Carillon
as tenants ponder their futures.
   ``I have no money. I have nobody. No relatives, no friends,
nothing,'' said 76-year-old Ms. Werner, a native of Hungary who
survived the Holocaust and the disappearance of her only child only
to give her money to ``gangsters.''
   Sheldon and Sheila Fiedler of Westchester, N.Y, won't even risk
renting the two rooms they bought after an elderly woman they had
rented to successfully sued them in small claims court over poor
hotel services.
   The economic crimes division of the state attorney's office is
investigating complaints at the Carillon, but could provide no
further details. DuLimba said the state attorney's office indicated
``there was possibly a big case here,'' but he said virtually
nothing has been done to help tenants.
   While some believe the complex case will take a long time to
resolve and that it's unlikely a judge would make an unpopular
decision to go ahead with evictions, others aren't as optimistic.
   ``If I could,'' said Mrs. Pichardo, ``I'd leave in a minute.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
