<DOCNO> AP890201-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-DroughtWatch Adv05-2Takes   02-01 1122</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drought Watch, Adv 05-2 Takes,1158</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Region to Region, It's Premature to Predict Drought But Not Too Soon
to Worry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Do this winter's mild, dry conditions in many parts of the nation
bode ill for the 1989 growing season? Is the unusual weather causing
problems already? It depends on where the questions are asked, and
of whom. Here are the findings of Associated Press reporters who
surveyed each region.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Corn Belt</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The fear of a second drought looms over pockets of the still
parched Corn Belt, where it's premature to predict another year of
pain, but not too early to worry about whether a mild winter will
bring farmers a harsh spring.
   Though thousands of acres of Midwest farm fields were ravaged by
the drought of '88, much of the eastern Corn Belt _ an area east of
the Mississippi River _ is in moderately good shape because of
abundant rain last fall.
   ``We've come a long way from where we were at the end of the
growing season,'' said Norton Strommen, chief meteorologist for the
U.S. Agriculture Department. ``It will be very important to see what
happens in the next three months filling in holes where it remains
dry.''
   Experts say west-central Illinois, eastern Iowa, northern
Missouri and southern Minnesota have yet to recover from the drought.
   The difference in Corn Belt conditions is reflected in
precipitation since Oct. 1. The western section received 74 percent
of normal precipitation, while the eastern Corn Belt received 119
percent, said Peter Leavitt, executive vice president of the Weather
Services Corporation in Massachusetts.
   Even with above average rains, conditions are so dry it'll take
time for the baked earth to return to rich black prairie soil.
Though Iowa had normal moisture since August, it still had only
21.64 inches of precipitation in 1988, the lowest level since 1910,
said state climatologist Harry Hillaker.
   ``It's going to take six to 12 months of normal rain to get
things back to the way it should be,'' he said.
   Dry weather not only affects corn, but another major Midwest crop
_ soybeans, which in 1988 were at their lowest production level
since 1976: 1.54 billion bushels.
   Beyond crops, the unusually warm, snow-scarce winter has
disappointed Wisconsin snowmobilers, postponed some farm equipment
purchases and led some Iowa towns to dig new wells.
   Still, experts say there's no reason to panic _ now.
   ``It's too early to worry about not having a crop,'' said Neil
Harl, an Iowa State University economics professor. ``But it's not
too early to worry about the consequences if you did.''
   _ By Sharon Cohen, Midwest regional reporter, based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Northeast</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   It's been a hard winter for Virginia Cochran, owner of a
Richmond, Vt., ski area. Not because of winter weather, but because
of the lack of it.
   ``I thought last year was bad in terms of lack of snow,'' she
said, ``but compared to this year, it was pretty good.''
   Scarcity of snow isn't a worry just to small ski operators.
Officials throughout the Northeast are keeping a nervous eye on
half-filled water reservoirs. Farmers fret about soil moisture.
Businesses selling snowmobiles and snowplows are hurting.
   ``This is disastrous,'' said Steve Kitchen, who has sold half the
usual number of snow tires at his Biddeford, Maine, service station.
   The winter of 1988-89 is likely to be remembered as the Winter of
No Snow.
   ``This has been the driest January in 104 years,'' said Richard
Mamrosh, a National Weather Service meteorologist in Burlington, Vt.
Vermont's Champlain Valley has had 19.9 inches of snow compared to
the normal average of 42 inches.
   The story is the same from Maine as far south as Maryland.
``Generally, we have had below normal snowfall,'' said Frank
Lucadamo, a hydrologist with the weather service's Northeast River
Forecast Center. ``If this continues we could see some problems.''
   Problems are already evident. Officials in Massachusetts, New
York and New Jersey have issued warnings about water supplies.
Reservoirs that supply some big Eastern cities are about 30 percent
below normal levels.
   ``Not only are we well below what we normally are, but there is
no snow upstate and you rely on the melt off of that snowpack in the
spring,'' said Tina Casey, a spokeswoman for the New York City
Department of Environmental Protection.
   The lack of a snowpack has had a wide range of effects. The
Finance Authority of Maine plans to provide $1 million in emergency
loans to struggling shopkeepers who can't find buyers for snow
machines. Farmers in New Hampshire fear the lack of snow cover will
kill off alfalfa fields.
   Buffalo, N.Y.'s city boosters are having problems organizing the
city's annual winter festival. ``We might as well call it
``Summerfest,'' said Robert Carr, a spokesman for the Greater
Buffalo Chamber of Commerce.
   _ By Fred Bayles, national writer, based in Boston.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Great Plains</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   As the drought of 1988 becomes the drought of '89, the nation's
breadbasket is worried about producing half a loaf this year.
   Last year's drought hit hard at the Great Plains states, which
produce most of the hard red winter wheat, the primary grain in
bread.
   Lack of moisture this winter in the heartland has agronomists and
statisticians nervous because another below-average crop could
further deplete America's grain reserves and raise food prices.
   Planted in the fall, winter wheat lies dormant until spring, when
it matures and ripens. It is harvested in the summer.
   Farmers in Kansas, the country's No. 1 wheat-growing state, and
Nebraska, Colorado, Montana, and the Dakotas all say they've been
short-changed on moisture since 1980, with last year's drought the
worst on record for many of them.
   In the past few months rain and snowfall have been sparse and
spotty. Eastern Montana and North Dakota are a little better off
than the last two years, Kansas and Nebraska are a little worse.
Colorado is about even. In South Dakota, which lost 68 percent of
its wheat crop last year, the autumn rains didn't come.
   ``At the end of the year we were about seven inches behind in
annual precipitation,'' said Eldon Thiessen, deputy statistician for
the Kansas Agricultural Statistics office. ``The ground was so dry
this fall the wheat never developed a good root system. The soil is
so loose that if the wind starts to blow the crop will be
destroyed.''
   Sumner County, Kan., annually produces more wheat than any other
county in the nation. Last year its farmers harvested 13.8 million
bushels, but county extension agent Gerald LeValley says an
unusually warm winter, lack of snow and rain and the appearance of
bugs in January all have him worried.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890201-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-DroughtWatch Adv05-1stAdd   02-01 1132</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drought Watch, Adv 05-1st Add,1174</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: him worried.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reggie Wyckoff, the new president of the 60,000-member National
Association of Wheatgrowers, fears his fellow farmers are on the
brink of another season of drought. With a few exceptions,
``everybody is dry,'' said Wyckoff, of Genoa, Colo.
   David Nielsen of the U.S. Department of Agriculture's research
station in Akron, Colo., said: ``The wheat doesn't look good but we
could make that up in one or two good snowstorms.''
   Lenis Nelson, a University of Nebraska agronomy professor, says
parts of his state need four to six inches of extra rainfall just to
break even and recharge the subsoil.
   ``You never get quite as much water as you need, so drought is
one of those things that's hard to determine,'' he said. ``But once
you're suffering you know you're in one.''
   _ By Tad Bartimus, Mountain States regional reporter, based in
Denver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The West</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Winter storms veering to the north have taken the edge off the
Pacific Northwest's drought, but only at the expense of California
and Nevada, where forecasters fear a third parched year.
   In California, two dry months have dashed hopes raised by heavy
November rains. Statewide, precipitation is 80 percent of normal,
and water runoff into rivers is less than 50 percent of normal, said
Bill Helms, state Water Resources Department spokesman. Reservoirs
are at their lowest since 1977.
   February and March, which usually provide nearly a third of the
year's rain and snow, will need 125 percent of normal precipitation
to make up the shortfall, he said.
   If runoff remains low, water to irrigated farmland may be cut by
up to 40 percent this summer, he said.
   ``The last two years have been critically dry. Last year, we
survived by drawing deeply into our reserves. This year we don't
have the reserves,'' Helms said.
   In San Francisco, where lawns have gone unwatered and fountains
are dry per order of the water department, officials plan to
continue conservation measures instituted last year.
   In northern Nevada, ``things are looking pretty bleak,'' said
state climatologist John James. January precipitation was about 20
percent of normal, he said.
   Last summer, Nevada's drought cut off water to some irrigated
fields, killed fish in overheated streams, and cut into recreation
business around a lowered Lake Tahoe.
   In Utah, a cold and dry January has dimmed hopes that were raised
by a snowy December.
   In Washington, Oregon and Idaho, several northward-tracking
storms off the Pacific Ocean have dumped enough snow to make water
officials breathe easier. But they say below-average snows in
February and March could erase any gains made so far.
   _ By David Foster, Northwest regional reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Southwest</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   While other Southwest states have had a warmer, drier winter than
normal, Arizona has had unusual shots of colder air, more rain and
even a mild citrus freeze.
   ``Between Christmas and the middle of January, we had below
normal temperatures and above normal percipitation _ and that's
related to the East Coast being warmer and drier,'' said Craig
Ellis, a National Weather Service meteorologist in Phoenix.
   Phoenix has had almost double its usual rainfall for January _
but that's still just a little more than an inch. Temperatures have
averaged near-normal, but there have been unusual cold snaps because
of a shift in the jet stream across the country.
   The extent of damage from a citrus freeze hasn't been determined,
said Bob Gronowski, a Commission on Agriculture supervisor. ``The
overall problem was not disastrous, but there was damage,'' he said.
   New Mexico, Texas, Oklahoma, Arkansas and Louisiana have all had
milder winters.
   Albuquerque had only 5 percent of its normal rainfall in
December, and January was well below normal in most areas of the
state, meteorologist Boyd White said.
   A recent survey of mountain snow-pack depths, however, found
near-normal levels.
   In west Texas, millions of acres of winter wheat are in terrible
shape, drought expert Dan Krieg said, and the lack of moisture poses
problems for the summer growing season as well.
   ``We have no subsoil moisture and so we're going into the crop
season with a severe water deficit. The top six feet are literally
air dry,'' said Krieg, a professor at Texas Tech University.
   The warm, dry winter will spawn a dust problem when spring winds
arrive, Krieg said.
   In Oklahoma City, December temperatures averaged 4 degrees warmer
than usual, and remained above normal for 20 of the first 25 days of
January, meteorologist Bill Bunting said.
   Little Rock has seen temperatures about 2 degrees above normal.
New Orleans' January high temperatures averaged close to 60 degrees
_ 7 degrees above normal, and rainfall measured half the usual level.
   _ By Scott McCartney, Southwest regional reporter, based in
Dallas.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Southeast</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This winter has been unusually warm in the Southeast, prompting
fruit trees to bud early and causing fears of damage if a freeze
comes, but rainfall levels throughout the region generally have been
normal.
   ``Our topsoil moisture levels are in the best shape they've been
in for years,'' said Charles Brantner, a U.S. Department of
Agriculture weather statistician based in Tennessee, a state hit
hard by last year's drought.
   He added, ``Our stock ponds have been replenished by the good
rains we had last fall. ``And things are continuing to look good so
far this year; our pastures are doing well and the winter wheat crop
is thriving.''
   However, the warmer temperatures, averaging between 3 and 8
degrees above normal since the beginning of winter, are beginning to
worry fruit growers in some areas of the Southeast.
   Growers across the region, and especially in Georgia and South
Carolina _ two states that produce much of the nation's peach crop _
are keeping a close eye on their trees.
   ``In Alabama we've already gotten some reports of early blooms,''
said J.T. ``Duffy'' Barr, the USDA weather statistician for that
state. ``The growers are worried that a cold snap will move in and
kill all those early blooms.''
   Ski resort operators in North Carolina say the days there also
have been warmer than usual. But they add that the nights have been
cold enough to allow them to keep their slopes covered with man-made
snow.
   J.B. Kelly, ticketing manager at the Beech Mountain resort near
Boone, N.C., said sales have held up so far despite the warm weather.
   Overall, climatologists and weather watchers say topsoil moisture
levels are in good shape in the Southeast but that they could use
more slow, soaking rains to replenish the subsoil levels. They also
say planting conditions should be good this spring, barring a sudden
change in the weather.
   _ By Strat Douthat, Southeast regional reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 5</NOTE>
