<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-RiverWatch Adv05   02-01 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-River Watch, Adv 05,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drought Fears Have River Watchers Preparing For Worst</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Drought Watch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Towboat operators are uneasy. So are New York stock traders,
German manufacturers and Japanese grain importers whose fortunes
hinge on whether a repeat of the drought will disrupt barge traffic
on the Mississippi River.
   ``Everybody's a little apprehensive,'' said Jim Tuttle, a
hydrologist with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers who is keeping a
wary eye on snowpack and water buildup in the upper Great Plains.
   ``But we're much, much better prepared. If it does happen again,
it will be less traumatic,'' Tuttle said.
   River forecasters say the next six weeks will be critical to
spring river levels. Most worrisome is below-normal snowfall in the
Dakotas, Iowa and other states in the upper Missouri River Valley.
   Things seem OK for now in the Upper Mississippi, Ohio and
Tennessee Valleys, Tuttle said.
   Meanwhile, engineers hoping to head off trouble after record low
water levels last summer are using four dredges to scrape rock
ledges and shoals out of the channel between St. Louis and Cairo,
Ill.
   ``Normally, we wouldn't have any dredges out now. This is the
first time since the 1930s we've had more than three dredges out at
this time. We want to be ready,'' said Clyde Wilkes of the Corps of
Engineers at St. Louis.
   The 2,348-mile long Mississippi is a natural superhighway into
the U.S. heartland, carrying 400 million tons of goods yearly.
   It hauls 57 percent of the nation's grain, 40 percent of its oil
products and 20 percent of its coal, plus fertilizer, cement,
chemicals, auto parts and other bulk.
   The Corps of Engineers keeps a 9-foot deep, 300-foot wide channel
for barges. But the drought closed the river in spots for 96 days
until giant scoops cleared away sediment.
   The worst bottlenecks were in late June at Memphis, Tenn., and
the mouth of the Ohio River, when 130 towboats came to a standstill
for three days. The cargo on their barges could have filled a convoy
of 18-wheelers stretching from New Orleans to Portland, Ore.
   The lowest water levels since records were first kept in 1872
were set in Memphis and two other spots in July.
   Losses for the year were estimated from $65 million to $200
million in a survey by barge operators.
   ``The drought came out faster and more furious than anyone could
have imagined. It was never so low for so long,'' said Jeffrey
Smith, vice president of the American Waterways Operators.
   ``It was a very difficult year that could have been a
catastrophe,'' Smith said. ``This year, we're prepared for the
worst.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
