<FIRST>r f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock     02-01 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Sues Shamrock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. has intensified its battle
against hostile suitor Shamrock Holdings Inc. with the filing of a
suit charging that Shamrock broke federal securities laws when it
solicited proxies from Polaroid shareholders.
   Polaroid's suit, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Boston,
came one day after Shamrock sued the instant photography pioneer to
block a proposed $1.1 billion stock buyback.
   Polaroid charged that Shamrock and other participants in the
hostile bid illegally sought proxy votes because they failed to
formally notify the Securities and Exchange Commission of their
plans, Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips said.
   Polaroid's suit also charged that Shamrock, a television and
radio concern owned by the Roy E. Disney family, made false and
misleading statements in soliciting shareholder proxies.
   Shamrock's $45-a-share offer for Polaroid _ which Polaroid's
board has rejected as inadequate _ values the Cambridge-based
company at $3.2 billion.
   On Monday, Polaroid announced its stock buyback proposal and said
it was also planning to issue $300 million in convertible preferred
stock to an investor group, Corporate Partners L.P.
   Analysts said the plans were a defensive move against the
Burbank, Calif.-based Shamrock, which responded by suing Polaroid in
Delaware State Court. Polaroid is incorporated in Delaware.
   Shamrock charged in a statement that Polaroid's directors
``breached their fiduciary duties by issuing additional, dilutive
voting securities to persons friendly to management in the face of
Shamrock's announced intention to wage a proxy contest at Polaroid's
upcoming annual meeting.''
   Shamrock's suit asked the court to bar the proposed buyback and
stock issue.
   However, Polaroid said the sale of the preferred stock to
Corporate Partners had already been completed. In an affidavit,
Polaroid attorney Melvin L. Bedrick said stock certificates were
delivered Monday to Corporate Partners, the transaction was recorded
and payment was made to Polaroid.
   Late Tuesday, Judge Carolyn Berger of the Delaware Court of
Chancery deferred Shamrock's request that she stop Polaroid from
selling stock to Corporate Partners. She gave Shamrock time to
determine whether outstanding conditions remained that would mean
the deal between Polaroid and Corporate Partners was not actually
completed.
   The judge also denied Shamrock's request that Polaroid be
required to give five days' notice regarding repurchase of its
common stock.
   Shamrock spokesman Michael Sitrick said the company was studying
the ruling and did not have any comment.
   The two sides are already battling in the Delaware courts over
Polaroid's employee stock ownership plan. Shamrock is appealing a
decision that upheld the plan.
   If the plan is invalidated, Shamrock says it will boost its offer
to $3.36 billion, or $47 per share.
   Shamrock has indicated it will wage a proxy fight for control of
Polaroid's board at the company's annual meeting in May and, if
successful, would force the sale of Polaroid either under its offer
or any higher third-party bid.
   Polaroid closed Tuesday at $41.62{, up $1 in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
