<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Casinos     02-01 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Casinos,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Asks To Bar Drexel From Casino Business Pending License Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The involvement of Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. in the Wall Street insider trading scandal is costing the firm,
at least temporarily, its lucrative business with New Jersey's
casino industry.
   Officials asked the state Casino Control Commission to suspend
the investment firm pending a decision on Drexel's application for a
license to do business with the Atlantic City casinos, Anthony J.
Parrillo, director of the New Jersey Division of Gaming Enforcement,
said Tuesday.
   State law prohibits people or companies facing criminal charges
from doing business with the casinos, Parrillo said.
   Because of the huge volume of business Drexel conducts with New
Jersey's heavily-regulated gambling industry, the state asked Drexel
in 1987 to apply for a license and undergo the required scrutiny.
   Drexel has earned fees totaling more than $120 million by
marketing securities valued at more than $3 billion for Atlantic
City casinos in recent years, said Parrillo. The firm itself says it
has raised more than $2.5 billion in permanent capital for the
industry.
   Drexel agreed Dec. 21 to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a
record $650 million in fines and restitution to settle the sweeping
securities fraud case brought against it by the U.S. Justice
Department.
   The six charges were filed last week. Most of them concern
Drexel's relationship with Ivan F. Boesky, the former takeover
speculator who turned state's evidence in late 1986 after admitting
to extensive insider stock trading.
   ``While criminal charges are outstanding and the (state's
licensing) investigation continues, any doubt with respect to
licensees should be resolved'' before Drexel is allowed to continue
dealing with the casinos, Parrillo said.
   The gaming division is the investigative arm of the state
attorney general's office that deals with the casino industry.
   Drexel _ the nation's fifth-largest investment firm _ issued a
statement Tuesday expressing confidence the matter would be resolved
soon.
   ``Based on steps Drexel is taking and new procedures we will be
instituting both at our own initiative and in coordination with
various regulatory agencies, we believe that we will be able to
qualify for licensure shortly,'' Drexel stated.
   Drexel spokesman Steve Anreder said he could not detail those
steps or how they could resolve the pending criminal charges, but he
said the firm believed those matters could be addressed.
   Parrillo said the Casino Control Commission had set no hearing
date to consider the suspension or to resolve Drexel's bid for a
license.
   Drexel has been involved with more than half of New Jersey's
casinos since the state legalized gambling in Atlantic City a decade
ago, Parrillo said.
   According to the state's 26-page complaint, Drexel has given
financial advice and raised capital for the holding companies of
such casinos as Caesars Atlantic City, the Golden Nugget and Del
Webb's Claridge Casino Hotel.
   Drexel also has been retained by the company belonging to
entertainer Merv Griffin in its acquisition of Resorts International
Inc.
   One of the six charges filed last week against Drexel involve
Golden Nugget Inc., a former Atlantic City casino owner. Drexel
allegedly committed mail fraud to manipulate MCA Inc. common stock
during Golden Nugget's sale of its MCA holdings.
   Golden Nugget sold its casino to Bally Manufacturing Corp. in
March 1987.
   Though Drexel was the first, the state has since asked three
other investment companies that do business with the casinos to
apply for licenses, Parrillo said. They are Bear Stearns &amp; Co. Inc.,
Merrill Lynch Pierce Fenner &amp; Smith Inc. and Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Those applications are pending before the Casino Control
Commission, Parrillo said.
</TEXT>
