<FIRST>d f PM-Rudy'sLastDay     02-01 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rudy's Last Day,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giuliani Keeps Busy on Last Day as U.S. Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now its just Mr. Rudolph W. Giuliani.
   Today is the first day of the former U.S. attorney's new career
as an ordinary citizen.
   On Tuesday, Giuliani said he planned to spend ``an extra hour
playing with my son,'' Andrew, 3, followed by breakfast with a
prospective employer.
   Giuliani kept busy right up to the end of his last day in office
by attending a Washington news conference, but only after Justice
Department officials vouched for him with wary security guards.
   Neither Giuliani nor his interim successor as Manhattan's U.S.
attorney, Benito Romano, had their credentials with them when they
showed up at the Justice Department.
   The New York prosecutors had to wait for other government
officials to come downstairs and identify them for security guards,
said a chuckling Giuliani, often called the best known prosecutor in
the country.
   The Washington press session, was called by Attorney General
Richard Thornburgh to announce the formation of white-collar crime
task forces at U.S. attorney offices around the country.
   ``This is exactly what we need and what we've needed for some
time,'' said Giuliani, who suggested the idea about a
year-and-a-half ago.
   The Southern District of New York, which Giuliani has headed
since 1983, will gain six attorneys assigned full-time to the task
force.
   Outside the news conference, Giuliani who made headlines
nationwide with his vigorous prosecution on Wall Street crooks, New
York mobsters and political grafters, drew a crowd of reporters,
eager to learn more about his future plans.
   As he has done for months, Giuliani _ often mentioned as a
possible Republican mayoral candidate _ spoke much but gave away
little.
   Asked whether he had problems with the demands of the politics _
the glad-handing and parades, Giuliani said with a grin: ``I love
parades. I don't know about all the rest of politics but I love
parades.''
   ``It seems to me a better idea that given the point that I was
at, to put all these things off until the day that I'm a private
citizen,'' he said. ``I can feel a lot more comfortable about it
starting tomorrow. And I'll be glad to tell you, starting tomorrow,
the factors that are involved in deciding what I'm going to do.''
   But when a reporter asked, ``How can we reach you, where will you
be tomorrow?'' all he said was, ``Pounding the pavement.''
</TEXT>
