<DOCNO> AP890201-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 0841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Atari-Nintendo     02-01 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Atari-Nintendo,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atari Files $250 Million Antitrust Suit Against Nintendo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atari Corp. has filed a $250 million
lawsuit against Nintendo Co. Ltd., accusing the Japanese video game
giant of monopolizing the market with restrictions on its licensed
game creators.
   The antitrust suit, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, alleges
that Nintendo forbids its developers from selling adaptations of
their games to other video game companies.
   ``Developers are faced with the choice between selling games only
to Nintendo customers or not selling,'' according to Atari's
complaint.
   That restriction causes the creators of video games ``to yield to
coercion from Nintendo, so that Atari and other manufacturers of
video game consoles are unable to obtain many popular games for use
on their own systems,'' the suit claims.
   The Sunnyvale, Calif.-based Atari is seeking to end Nintendo's
alleged practice of prohibiting game developers from writing video
games for anyone else, said Joshua Tropper, Atari's general counsel.
   The suit, which also names as a defendant Nintendo's U.S.
subsidiary, Nintendo of America Inc., is the latest development in a
long dispute between Nintendo and American makers and distributors
of video games over the $2.3 billion annual market.
   In December, Atari Games of Milpitas, Calif., which is not
related to Atari Corp., filed a $100 million suit against Nintendo,
accusing the company of unfair competition.
   Early last month, Nintendo sued Atari Games, accusing the company
of making and selling unauthorized video-game cartridges.
