<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Boeing     02-01 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Boeing,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wiring Checks Ordered For British Boeing Airplanes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Civil Aviation Authority said Wednesday that
124 Boeing airplanes in Britain must undergo the same detailed
safety inspections ordered for similar airplanes in the United
States.
   The British order, like that issued by the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration, affects all Boeing aircraft built since Dec. 31,
1980.
   British Airways has the most Boeing aircraft in the country, 61,
but the order also affects 12 smaller domestic and international
airlines, said a CAA spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with
British custom.
   The American agency told U.S. airlines Tuesday to inspect all
their 741 newer Boeing 737s, 747s, 757s and 767s after problems were
discovered in 17 aircraft.
   The order requires the airlines to inspect the planes' engines
and cargo compartment fire detection, warning and extinguishing
systems for crossed wiring or plumbing.
   ``In cases like this the FAA always pass on the directive to us
and we pass it on to the airlines,'' said the CAA spokesman.
   The new order follows earlier FAA and CAA directives ordering
inspections of specific systems in certain types of aircraft
following the Jan. 8 crash of a British Midland Boeing 737 in
central England that killed 46 people.
   That plane landed with its left engine on fire and its right
engine shut down. The cause of the crash is still under
investigation.
   Airlines have 25 days to complete the inspections in Britain and
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
