<SECOND>BC-Delta-Akron,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Firm Moving From Far East To Akron</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a switch from the trend toward offshore
assembly, a company that makes personal computers in the Far East
has decided to move its operations to Akron, officials confirmed
today.
   Delta Computer Corp., which will lease space once occupied by
B.F. Goodrich Co., said the move to the United States would help it
control quality and reduce shipping time.
   Eugene Taylor, the company president, said the 3-year-old
company's products currently are made and assembled in Taiwan, Korea
and Hong Kong.
   The company plans to market a soft disk drive with about 60 times
the normal storage capacity of currently marketed floppy disks.
   Operations are scheduled to begin in about eight weeks. About 100
people are expected to be hired by May. If the new disk drive is
successful, Taylor said, the company might have 1,500 to 2,000
employees in about 18 months.
</TEXT>
