<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Hyundai-Chrysler     02-01 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hyundai-Chrysler,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler To Market Hyundais In U.S. Beginning In 1991</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Hyundai Motor Co., South Korea's biggest
automaker, will sell 30,000 autos a year in the United States
through Chrysler Corp. beginning in l991, a Hyundai spokesman said
Wednesday.
   Hyundai will sell, through Chrysler's Eagle Division, a 4-door
sedan with a 2,400-cubic centimeter engine that will be assembled at
its newly opened plant in Bromont, Quebec.
   Hyundai has not decided yet whether the model will be the Sonata,
currently on sale in the United States, or a completely new model.
   Hyundai's Canadian plant, the first Korean auto assembly plant
outside Korea, has been producing Sonatas since Jan. 13 and will
produce about 30,000 Sonatas this year.
   The capacity will increase to 100,000 units by l991. Some 50,000
autos will be sold in the United States directly by Hyundai Motor
America and 20,000 units will be sold in Canada.
   With the alliance between Hyundai and Chrysler, all three major
South Korean automakers will be teamed up with the Big Three U.S.
automakers. Daewoo Motor is 50 percent owned by General Motors Corp.
and Kia Motors is 10 percent owned by Ford Motor Co.
   GM's Pontiac Division now markets Daewoo's LeMans in the United
States, and Ford sells Kia's Festiva.
   Chrysler owns 21.6 percent of Japan's Mitsubishi Motors Corp.,
which in turn owns 7.5 percent of Hyundai.
   The No. 3 U.S. automaker's Eagle division already sells the
Premier sedan designed by France's Regie Nationale des Usines
Renault and built in Canada, and the Summit subcompact built by
Mitsubishi in Japan.
   The Hyundai spokesman said he hoped the cooperation with Chrysler
would enhance Hyundai's presence in North America. Hyundai
successfully entered the North American market with its
subcompact-type Excels, but is trying to move upward with the
compact-type Sonatas.
</TEXT>
