<FIRST>u f PM-HoughtonMifflin 1stLd-Writethru f0006 02-01 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Houghton Mifflin, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0006,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bass Group Discloses 5.6 Percent Stake in Houghton-Mifflin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 4 new grafs to update with today's stock price. Picks
up 5th graf pvs, The Bass ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock of textbook publisher Houghton Mifflin Co.
extended its rise today after surging in the previous session
following the disclosure that a group led by Texan Robert M. Bass
boosted its stake to 5.6 percent.
   The Bass Group said Tuesday in disclosing its holdings that its
latest purchase was for investment purposes. Houghton Mifflin
pointed out that Bass had been an investor in the company for some
time and said it found nothing unusual about the filing.
   But Wall Streeters remembered that it was the Bass Group's bid
last May that started another publishing giant, Macmillan Inc., on
the path to a takeover at a price about 80 percent higher than its
stock had been trading.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading today, Houghton Mifflin rose
another $1.50 a share to $46.75 after Tuesday's advance of $8.87{ a
share. At today's midmorning price, the company's 14 million shares
are valued at about $650 million.
   The Bass disclosure follows two years of sweeping changes in the
publishing business that has seen Macmillan fall to British
publisher Robert Maxwell, Harper &amp; Row Publishers Inc. yield to
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. and Grolier Inc. sell to Hachette SA of
France.
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc., another publishing giant,
underwent a costly recapitalization in 1987 to avoid being acquired
by Maxwell.
   Alan Kassan, who follows publishing companies for Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., said Bass demonstrated his interest in the publishing
business with his initial Macmillan bid and his earlier acquisition
of Bell &amp; Howell Co., an information services and publishing concern
based near Chicago.
   ``I don't know what his intentions are, but he has the interest
and the deep pockets to acquire the whole thing if he so chose,''
Kassan said.
   Bert Boksen, who follows media companies for Raymond James &amp;
Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla., said Houghton Mifflin could
command a price in the mid-$50 a share range should a buyout effort
be made.
   A woman answering the telephone at Bass's offices in Fort Worth,
Texas, said it was company policy not to comment on its business
plans.
   Boston-based Houghton Mifflin is a leading educational publisher
and also publishes general interest books and educational and
word-processing software.
   It ranked fourth in the nation behind Harcourt, Gulf &amp; Western's
Simon &amp; Schuster and Macmillan based on 1987 educational revenue,
according to the trade newsletter Educational Marketer, published by
Knowledge Industry Publications Inc. in White Plains, N.Y.
   Shearson's Kassan said Houghton Mifflin has been a well-run
company with ``a fair earnings performance'' over the past two years.
   Hougton Mifflin earned $24.1 million, or $1.70 a share, on
revenue of $368.3 million in 1988.
   Nonetheless, Kassan said the company is vulnerable to a takeover
because it has a relatively small amount of its stock in the hands
of company insiders and is ``clearly a leader'' in the growing
lementary school reading market.
   In its filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the
Bass Group said it purchased 161,200 shares of Houghton Mifflin
stock between Jan. 10 and Jan. 27 at a prices ranging from $34.21 to
$36.80 a share.
   It said the purchase leaves it with 790,200 common shares of
Houghton Mifflin, or 5.6 percent of its 14 million shares.
   In its statement, Houghton Mifflin said, ``We do not see anything
unusual in the Bass Group's filing. Houghton Mifflin has other large
stockholders, most of whom have been investors for a long time.''
   Paul D. Weaver, secretary for the company, declined comment when
asked if the company's board had met to discuss the matter.
   The company adopted a poison-pill takeover defense plan in
December.
   Last May, the Bass Group proposed to acquire Macmillan for $64 a
share at a time when the company's stock had been trading at about
$50 a share. Maxwell acquired Macmillan last fall at a price of
$90.25 a share, or about $2.5 billion.
</TEXT>
