<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Computer     02-01 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Computer,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compaq Achieves Another Milestone: $2 Billion In Revenue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp. said Wednesday it recorded an 88 percent
profit increase in the last quarter of 1988, capping a year in which
the personal computer maker became the first start-up company to
achieve $2 billion in revenue in as little as six years.
   Just one year earlier, Houston-based Compaq attained $1 billion
in revenue faster than any company built from scratch. It previously
ascended to the ranks of the Fortune 500 in record time.
   ``Strong worldwide sales of our entire product line contributed
both to the year's and to the quarter's strong performance,'' Rod
Canion, the president and chief executive, said in a statement.
   International sales, excluding Canada, contributed 39 percent of
Compaq's yearly revenue, the company said.
   Compaq, founded early in 1982, grew up as a maker of personal
computers compatible with International Business Machines Corp.'s
line. It reached adulthood in 1987 when IBM switched to its Personal
System-2 line and Compaq chose to stick with the old standard.
   A front-page headline in a recent issue of Info World, a trade
publication, said, ``Compaq Vying To Become the IBM of the '90s.''
   That is somewhat of an overstatement: IBM remains nearly 30 times
the size of Compaq, and its revenue growth alone last year was twice
Compaq's overall revenue.
   Still, at least in the field of personal computers Compaq is
trying to portray itself as the preserver of industry standards, a
role once held by IBM. But IBM remains a formidable rival.
   Compaq's latest challenge is that IBM's new PC line is slowly but
surely expanding its share of the market, while the extension to the
old IBM standard promoted by Compaq and other IBM rivals is still on
the drawing boards.
   Canion and his partners began designing their first personal
computer in February 1982. Sales began in 1983. When the year was
completed they had tallied sales of $111.2 million, an American
business record.
   Compaq reached the Fortune 500 in 1985 and achieved its first
billion-dollar year in 1987.
   Compaq said its earnings in the quarter rose to $91.9 million, or
$2.18 a share, from $49 million, or $1.25 a share, a year earlier.
Revenue jumped 55 percent to $668 million from $432 million a year
earlier.
   For all of 1988, Compaq said its earnings rose 87 percent to $255
million from $136 million a year earlier. Earnings per share rose to
$6.30 from $3.59, or to $6.27 from $3.57 on a fully diluted basis;
that is, assuming conversion into common stock of all convertible
securities. Revenue rose 69 percent to $2.07 billion from $1.22
billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
