<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Malaysia-Cars     02-01 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-Cars,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Further Delays Expected in Malaysian Car Exports to United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to sell a Malaysian-built car
in the United States have bogged down due to problems with a U.S.
distributor and delays stemming from required regulatory
modifications to the vehicle.
   Through its government-backed Perusahan Otomobil National Ltd.
(PROTON), Malaysia already has begun exporting locally made cars to
Britain.
   The first 600 Proton Sagas left Tuesday for Britain, and Proton
Cars United Kingdom Ltd. expects to sell 6,000 in the first nine
months after the vehicle's March 16 introduction, the firm's
managing director, Peter King, said at a sendoff ceremony at Port
Klang, near Kuala Lumpur.
   Malaysia already has sold a few thousand Proton Sagas in Sri
Lanka, Malta, Ireland, New Zealand and Bangladesh and originally
hoped to begin U.S. exports last year.
   But modifications needed to meet U.S. standards caused a
postponement and further delays are likely while problems involving
a U.S. distributor are worked out, industry sources said.
   Jamil Mohamad Jan, chairman of Proton, said Tuesday the company
might seek arbitration or sue its U.S. distributor, Proton America
Inc., alleging breach of contract.
   Last week, Yugo America Inc., its Global Motors Inc. and its
Proton America affiliate filed for protection from creditors under
U.S. bankruptcy law.
   Proton terminated its distributorship agreement with PAI recently
because the distributor had failed to obtain necessary federal and
state approvals for importing the Saga into the United States by
Nov. 18, 1988, the national news agency Bernama reported.
   Under a November 1987 agreement, PAI was to have imported a
minimum of 30,000 cars in the first year, and Malaysian Proton
officials hoped shipments eventually would rise to 100,000 a year.
   Asked if another company would be appointed distributor for the
car in the United States, Jamil replied that Proton first would have
to settle its legal matters with PAI.
   The regulatory modifications also present an obstacle. Jamil said
it took Proton 17 months to modify the Proton Saga to meet British
regulations.
   Proton officials had estimated it would cost Proton $10 million
to modify plant facilities to make cars that would meet American
specifications and another $20 million for advertising.
   The Proton Saga engine and gearbox are made by Japan's
Mitsubishi, but most of its other parts are made in Malaysia.
   The car comes in 1.3- and 1.5-liter engine versions and retails
in Malaysia for $9,159 to $11,723, depending on equipment.
   The car has been a pet project of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
and the company has been operating at a loss. But Jamil said Proton
was expected to report a profit of between $2.56 million and $2.93
million for the year ending March 31, 1989.
   The plant was established at a cost of more than $120 million,
and first year sales in 1985 amounted to 7,494 cars, 11 percent of
all passenger cars sold in Malaysia.
   Last year, 42,500 Proton Sagas were sold here, accounting for 73
percent of the Malaysian market.
   Deputy Prime Minister Abdul Ghafar Baba said Tuesday that because
of increasing demand, annual production would be increased in
October to 110,000 cars from the current 56,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
