<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-01 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Drop In Reversal Of Previous Day's Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures led a selloff Wednesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade's grain and soybean markets, reversing some
of the strong gains tallied in the previous session due to supply
concerns.
   The decline in the wheat market was triggered in part by an
Agriculture Department adjustment that effectively moved the USDA
average cash price for wheat 6 cents closer to $4.23 a bushel, a
level that would free farmers to sell on the open market wheat they
have been storing as part of the government price-support program.
   ``There was quite a bit of selling on the assumption that once
the trigger level is reached, there will be a major sell-off,'' said
Katharina Zimmer, grain market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc. in New York.
   ``But today's slump, of course, means we are moving further away
from it,'' she said.
   Analysts cited profit-taking as a reason for steep losses in the
soybean market, where heavy selling late in the session erased more
than half of Tuesday's advance.
   At the close, wheat was 5} cents to 7{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.31{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 3 cents lower with March at $2.73{ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents
to 5 cents lower with March at $2.17 a bushel; soybeans were 4}
cents to 9\ cents lower with March at $7.68 a bushel.
</TEXT>
