<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-USX     02-01 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Better Times Ahead, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Chairman David M. Roderick Wednesday
predicted that profits during the last year of his leadership will
surpass the healthy returns posted in 1988 by the streamlined oil
and steel company.
   ``We just feel extremely confident that 1989 will be a better
profit year,'' Roderick said at his last quarterly news conference
before his mandatory rtirement May 31 at age 65. ``That's usually a
prediction that I avoid making. So obviously I have a very high
level of confidence.''
   Higher prices for crude oil, natural gas and steel, coupled with
greater sales volume and lower operating costs companywide will
enable USX to surpass the 1988 profits it announced Tuesday, he said.
   The company had 1988 net income of $756 million, or $2.62 per
share, more than triple the $219 million, or 54 cents per share,
reported for 1987. Sales rose from $14.9 billion to $16.9 billion.
   The 1988 performance was led by a turnaround in steel operations,
which posted operating profits of $501 million, compared with $125
million in 1987.
   Roderick said he disagrees with predictions of a slump in steel
late this year.
   ``Everybody's anticipating a slowdown in the second half. They've
been saying that for five consecutive years. They've been wrong five
consecutive years,'' he said.
   The chairman also is more optimistic about steel industry
shipments than even the company's official prediction of 76 million
tons.
   ``My own opinion is it's going to be closer to 77 or 78'' million
tons because of continued strength in capital spending, the Gross
National Product and employment, he said.
   U.S. steel exports should double from about 500,000 tons last
year to a million tons in 1989, Roderick said.
   In energy operations, the company's Marathon Oil Co. subsidiary
should benefit from higher crude oil prices, lower exploration costs
and the renewal of business in Libya. Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp. unit
should enjoy higher natural gas prices and greater sales volume, he
said.
   As it did in 1988, the company will end 1989 with $1 billion or
more in excess cash, he said.
   If President Bush fails to keep a campaign promise to renew steel
import quotas, unfair foreign competition could upset expectations,
Roderick said.
   ``If anybody has any illusions that these foreign countries
(don't) continue to subsidize, forget it. They're doing it on a
massive scale,'' he said. ``In South America, if they weren't
subsidized, they's all go belly up.''
   He said the European Common Market recently permitted the Italian
government to grant $6 billion in subsidies to that nation's steel
industry.
   Steel shipments by USX will increase from 12.2 million tons in
1988 to 13 million tons or more this year, he said.
   The gains are expected even though 1988 operating profits were
only around $45 per ton when Roderick had predicted $60 per ton.
   He blamed the collapse of demand for tubular steel used in oil
and gas exploration, an unintended rise in steelmaking costs,
equipment problems, and accounting errors. Most of those problems
will disappear in 1989, Roderick said.
   USX President Charles Corry, elected this week to succeed
Roderick on June 1, said one of the biggest challenges facing him
concerns the ability of the company's smaller, leaner steel
operation to weather a recession.
   ``We haven't tested ourselves in the new configuration yet in a
down cycle,'' Corry said after the news conference. ``I haven't made
up my mind yet whether the steel industry can lose the kind of money
it lost in 1982 and '83'' without companies failing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890201-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     02-01 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Profit Down 8.8 Percent In Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. on Wednesday posted an 8.8
percent decline in its fourth quarter earnings, due partly to a
one-time charge for costs in the implementation of its joint
newspaper operating agreement in Detroit.
   The media company said that in the three months ended Dec. 31 it
had a profit of $45.6 million, or 76 cents a share, compared with
$50 million, or 83 cents a share, in the same period a year earlier.
   Total operating revenue rose to $574.6 million in the quarter
from $527.1 million in fourth quarter 1987.
   Knight-Ridder set aside $13 million for anticipated severance and
other costs related to the joint operating agreement between its
Detroit Free Press and Gannett Co. Inc.'s Detroit News. Opponents of
the partial merger asked a federal appeals court Wednesday to delay
the deal.
   Annual earnings rose to $156.4 million, or $2.76 a share,
compared with $155.2 million, or $2.65 a share, in 1987. Operating
revenue rose to $2.08 billion from $1.97 billion the previous year.
   Robert F. Singleton, Knight-Ridder's chief financial officer,
said unfavorable factors affecting annual results included a decline
in newspaper advertising lineage that affected the entire industry,
an average 13 percent rise in newsprint costs and declining
profitability at its Miami Herald.
   Knight-Ridder's newspaper division, with 30 daily newspapers,
showed an operating profit of $299.73 million, down 8.1 percent from
$326.19 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
