<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-01 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose in moderate trading
Wednesday, buoyed by technical factors and growing investor
confidence in OPEC, market watchers said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled
48 cents higher at $17.51 a barrel after falling 26 cents in the
previous session. Other contract months also rose.
   Among refined products, the March contract for unleaded gasoline
rose 1.34 cents to close the day at 49.63 cents a gallon, while
domestic heating oil increased 1.04 cents to 50.44 cents a gallon.
Other contract months also advanced.
   Analysts said that after a weak start prices rose despite the
lack of new news to spur prices.
   ``There was no real fundamental change in the market,'' said
Richard Redoglia, a trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures. ``The
market is going through a consolidation phase.''
   The American Petroleum Institute's weekly report on oil supplies
was neutral to bearish for prices, traders said. The report,
released after the close of trading on Tuesday, showed crude stocks
were down slightly while gasoline supplies rose and heating oil was
mostly unchanged.
   Analysts said prices got some strength from continued investor
confidence that OPEC will follow through on its pledge to lower
production.
   The agreement by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, which took effect Jan. 1 and extends for six months, set
a quota of 18.5 million barrels a day, more than 3 million barrels a
day less than the cartel was producing late last year.
   Crude oil prices have risen more than $3 a barrel since the new
quota was announced last November. Prices had fallen sharply during
most of 1988.
   ``There was nothing fundamentally new today other than growing
confidence that OPEC is serious about what it wanted to do,'' said
Bob Baker, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
