<FIRST>u f AM-Pepperell 1stLd-Writethru f0159 02-01 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0159,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farley Raises Offer For Textile Giant Pepperell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with closing stock price, SUBS 4th graf, ``On Wall...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle for textile giant West Point-Pepperell
Inc. heated up Wednesday as Farley Inc. sweetened its hostile tender
offer to $1.53 billion.
   Farley, based in Chicago, said it would pay $52 per share in cash
for Pepperell stock, up from its initial $48-per-share, or $1.4
billion, offer on Oct. 24. The bid, which had been set to expire at
midnight Wednesday, also was extended until midnight Feb. 15.
   A Pepperell spokesman said the company would have no comment on
the latest offer. ``We have not yet received this proposal and the
board of directors will consider it in due course,'' he said.
   On Wall Street, meanwhile, trading in Pepperell stock was active.
It closed at $53.25 a share Wednesday, up $2.50.
   Pepperell, the nation's largest publicly traded textile company,
manufactures such products as Martex sheets and towels and Gold Toe
socks.
   Farley, one of the nation's largest privately owned
conglomerates, controls Fruit of the Loom Inc., the nation's biggest
underwear manufacturer, and Acme Boot Co. Inc., whose brands include
Acme and Dingo boots.
   In a statement from its Chicago headquarters, Farley said the
increased bid ``once again demonstrates our resolve to acquire West
Point-Pepperell.''
   The offer is conditional on receiving, or owning outright,
two-thirds of the outstanding shares. The conglomerate already
controls 2.9 million shares and has received offers for another 15.7
million, which together account for about of 62 percent of Pepperell
stock.
   The move is the latest in a series of events that began last
Friday, when Pepperell _ which has consistently fought Farley _ said
it was talking with third parties who might be interested in
purchasing the West Point, Ga.-based company.
   In a filing with the Security and Exchange Commission, Pepperell
said it was not for sale, but ``has entered into preliminary
negotiations with various third parties who have expressed an
interest in a transaction involving the company.''
   Pepperell also suggested it might undertake a recapitalization,
which analysts believe would leave the company in the hands of
current management.
   Patricia Ryan, an analyst with Raymond James &amp; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla., said Farley's announcement Wednesday likely was a
direct response to Pepperell's search for a ``white knight.''
   Pepperell has claimed from the beginning that Farley's offer was
an attempt to purchase the company before its stock could reflect
last year's acquisition of the bulk of competitor J.P. Stevens &amp; Co.
Inc., giving Pepperell about a quarter of the nation's home fashion
textile market.
   Ms. Ryan and other analysts estimated Pepperell's stock is worth
in the $55 range.
   Analysts long have expected a higher offer in the Pepperell deal,
which also has been caught up in court and legislative battles since
its inception.
   Pepperell's board voted in November to resist Farley's overture.
It went to the extent of holding a football-style pep rally at a
high school stadium in Lanett, Ala., where Chairman Joseph L. Lanier
Jr. told a cheering crowd, ``Our determination is to whip Farley. We
are going to fight Farley until hell freezes over, and then we are
going to fight him on the ice.''
   After Farley won a U.S. District Court ruling that some of
Pepperell's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defenses were not allowed
by state law, a state legislator introduced a bill in Georgia's
General Assembly that would speed up the effective date of laws
allowing the provisions.
   The bill won approval in the Georgia's House and currently is
awaiting action in the Senate, where a committee has recommended
approval.
   Pepperell has appealed the District Court ruling to the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, where a decision is pending.
   Also pending is a ruling from U.S. District Judge G. Ernest
Tidwell on Farley's claim that the state's anti-takeover law is
unconstitutional.
   Farley's offer includes conditions that Pepperell's anti-takeover
defenses be voided.
</TEXT>
