<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-01 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Plunge As Chilean Refinery Strike Is Averted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices tumbled Wednesday following news that a
labor agreement had averted a strike at a large, state-owned Chilean
copper refinery.
   On other markets, precious metals rebounded, grains and soybeans
fell; energy futures rose; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Copper settled 1.05 cents to 6.60 cents lower on New York's
Commodity Exchange, with the contract for delivery in March at
$1.363 a pound.
   The sell-off was triggered mainly by reports that workers at
Chile's Empresa Nacional de Mineria smelter-refinery had reached a
settlement with the government, eliminating prospects for a strike
on Friday.
   The facility refines 200,000 metric tons of copper per year, or
about 15 percent of the total production in the world's leading
copper-producing country.
   ``That's a lot of copper,'' said Craig Sloane, a metals-market
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``If that
refinery wasn't operational it would be a significant factor in the
market.''
   Chile's copper production already has been crippled by the Jan.
13 shutdown of smelting operations at Codelco's Chuquicamata mine,
the world's largest copper mine.
   The smelter was shut down after an explosion and is not expected
to resume operations for another month.
   Mechanical and labor problems in Chile, Peru and some of Africa's
major copper-producing nation's have contributed to recent strong
gains in the copper market. The spot price of copper on the
Commodity Exchange reached a record $1.6475 a pound on Dec. 8.
   Gold and silver futures prices advanced moderately on the
Commodity Exchange after four days of sharp losses that had sent
prices to their lowest levels since last October.
   Gold settled $1.40 to $2.10 higher with February at $393.70 a
troy ounce; silver was 3.5 cents to 4.4 cents higher with February
at $5.835 a troy ounce.
   Wheat futures led a sell-off on the Chicago Board of Trade's
grain and soybean markets, reversing some of the strong gains
tallied in the previous session and highlighting supply concerns.
   The decline in the wheat market was triggered in part by an
Agriculture Department adjustment that effectively moved the USDA
average cash price for wheat 6 cents closer to $4.23 a bushel, a
level that would free farmers to sell on the open market wheat they
have been storing as part of the government price-support program.
   Traders sold wheat contracts in anticipation of a major sell-off
if the $4.23 level is reached and new supplies come onto the market.
   Analysts cited profit-taking as a reason for steep losses in the
soybean market, where heavy selling late in the session erased more
than half of Tuesday's advance.
   Wheat settled 6 cents to 8} cents lower with March at $4.31} a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 2} cents lower with March at $2.73{ a
bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 5 cents lower with March at $2.17 a
bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 9{ cents lower with March at $7.67{
a bushel.
   Energy futures prices rose in moderate trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, buoyed by technical factors and growing
investor confidence in OPEC.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .48 cent to .59 cent
higher with March at $17.51 a barrel; heating oil was 1.04 cents to
1.27 cents higher with March at 50.44 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.34 cents to 1.74 cents higher with March at 49.63
cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
with support stemming from fears of weight losses and deaths from
bitterly cold weather in the Great Plains, and selling linked to
profit-taking after a recent run-up in prices.
   Hog futures prices rose on fears that cold weather in the Midwest
would slow the movement of hogs to market, while pork-belly futures
fell on scattered profit-taking.
   Live cattle settled .12 cent lower to .35 cent higher with
February at 75.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .28
cent higher with March at 84.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .12
cent to .50 cent higher with February at 43.62 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .30 cent lower to .93 cent higher with February at
39.45 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
