<FIRST>r f AM-J.C.Penney-Insurance     02-01 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-J.C. Penney-Insurance,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retailer To Drop Insurance Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTERVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. announced Wednesday
that it is negotiating with several major insurance companies to
sell its JCPenney Casualty Insurance Co.
   JCPenney Casualty markets auto, homeowners and other insurance
through centers in company stores and direct-response mail campaigns
in 21 states.
   The division is based in Westerville, a suburb of Columbus.
   Joseph J. DeMelio, vice president and director of insurance for
JCPenney Casualty, indicated the company decided to leave the
casualty business because it did not combine well with family
apparel and home furnishings in stores.
   ``While we did see encouraging results for our insurance
products, the synergy that we envisioned ... did not materialize,''
DeMelio said in a written announcement.
   DeMelio said the company would continue to honor its insurance
commitments during the negotiations. J.C. Penney Co. will continue
to operate the JCPenney Life Insurance Co., which offers life,
health and credit insurance through direct response.
   Tillinghast and Co., an insurance industry consulting firm, has
been hired to assist J.C. Penney Co. in the negotiations.
</TEXT>
