<FIRST>r f AM-Coastal-TexasEastern     02-01 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coastal-Texas Eastern,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Eastern Refuses Offer to Postpone Litigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp. said Wednesday it rejected an
offer to postpone all litigation stemming from Coastal Corp.'s $2.6
billion takeover bid because Coastal was ``demanding an advantage''
over other possible buyers.
   Coastal officials said they offered not to purchase any Texas
Eastern stock before March 15. In exchange, Coastal sought a
guarantee it would be treated fairly in the bidding process and that
Texas Eastern would erect no new obstacles to a tender offer after
that date.
   ``We are disappointed that Texas Eastern refused to agree to
treat Coastal fairly and not to enact any new poison pill,'' Coastal
President James R. Paul said.
   In response, Texas Eastern said the company is ``perfectly
willing to include Coastal in the bidding process for Texas Eastern
on the same basis as other bidders.''
   ``However, Coastal was demanding an advantage over other bidders
and attempting to limit our ability to properly act in the best
interest of our shareholders,'' the statement said.
   Texas Eastern's board last Sunday rejected Coastal's $42-a-share
offer as inadequate and urged shareholders to wait for a better
price.
   Litigation relating to Coastal's attempted takeover has spread to
three courts, including the U.S. District Court in Houston where
Coastal sought to block Texas Eastern from enacting its poison pill
plan elsewhere.
</TEXT>
