<DOCNO> AP890201-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FuelEconomy     02-01 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fuel Economy,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Abolish Fuel-Economy Standards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to abolish federal fuel-economy
standards was introduced Wednesday by Rep. Bob Carr, D-Mich., who
argued that the rules cause the economy to suffer in Michigan and
the nation.
   Carr's bill, which he first introduced last year, would end the
corporate average fuel-economy regulations that require automakers
to attain a certain minimum gasoline mileage on average throughout
their fleets of passenger cars.
   ``CAFE is a government regulation that is simply not needed,''
said Carr. ``The time has come to put it aside. Without such a
change, the two largest domestic automakers face the unfortunate
prospect of having to limit or stop selling some of the most popular
cars in America today.''
   The fuel-economy standard for 1989 models is 26.5 miles per
gallon, a slightly more stringent level than the 26 mpg standard in
effect from 1986 through 1988 but below the 27.5 mpg set as a goal
by fuel-conservation legislation.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration is considering
what standard to set for 1990 models. President Bush's new
transportation secretary, Samuel Skinner, told a Senate committee
this week he would review any mileage standard set by NHTSA.
   Carr's bill died last year without action by the House Energy and
Commerce Committee, whose chairman, Rep. John Dingell, also a
Michigan Democrat, has said the fuel-economy standards appeared to
be working fairly well.
   Dingell has yet to take a position on the new legislation Carr
introduced Wednesday, the committee staff said.
   ``It's an educational process,'' said Jeff Eller, a Carr aide,
when asked about prospects for the bill this year. ``We now have a
base of members who understand why CAFE should be abolished.''
   General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. have argued for an end to
the fuel-economy standards, saying it forces them to produce smaller
cars the buying public doesn't want in order to bring their fleets
within the mileage requirements.
   The result, they have said, is layoffs at large-car assembly
plants and a lessened ability of U.S. automakers to compete with
small-body imports.
   Chrysler Corp., with a higher proportion of smaller vehicles in
its lineup, has said it can meet the 27.5 mpg standard envisioned by
the law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
