<FIRST>r f BC-Drexel-SEC     02-01 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drexel-SEC,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Drexel Asked Nine Congressmen to Pressure SEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. reportedly has
asked nine California members of Congress to pressure the Securities
and Exchange Commission into reducing proposed settlement terms in
its fraud case.
   Mayor Tom Bradley was a key player in the lobbying effort, the
Los Angeles Times reported Wednesday, by persuading the
congressional delegation from California to intervene on behalf of
Drexel.
   The result was three similarly worded letters from members of
Congress to SEC Chairman David Ruder demanding that the agency
abandon efforts to force Drexel to move its high-yield bond
department from Beverly Hills to the firm's New York headquarters,
the Times said.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif.,
each wrote letters on Drexel's behalf and Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Los
Angeles, wrote a third letter signed by six other Los Angeles-area
lawmakers, the report said.
   The six congressmen were identified as Reps. Howard Berman, Mel
Levine, David Dreier, Carlos Moorhead, Julian C. Dixon and Augustus
F. Hawkins.
   At least seven of the nine members of Congress have received
campaign contributions or honorariums from Drexel, the Times said.
   Drexel representatives asked the three members of Congress to
express objections to an SEC demand that the firm move its so-called
``junk bond'' high-yield operation which had been headed by Michael
Milken, the key target of the federal fraud investigation.
   The firm has said that dismantling the junk bond unit would
severely hurt Drexel's leading role in the lucrative market for
these securities, commonly used to finance takeovers or finance
growth of small and medium-size takeovers.
   Drexel agreed Dec. 21 to pay the government $650 million in fines
and restitution and plead guilty to six felonies to settle
accusations of securities fraud.
   The plea bargain also requires Drexel to settle related
litigation with the SEC, which filed civil fraud charges against the
firm last Sept. 7.
