<DOCNO> AP890201-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ConsumerConfidence     02-01 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Confidence,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Consumer Confidence Dropped In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. consumer confidence in the economy, which
sharply improved in December, relinquished some of the gain in
January, the Conference Board reported Wednesday.
   The board's Consumer Confidence Index, a mathematical calculation
designed to reflect sentiment about buying plans and borrowing,
retreated to 115.3 last month, a four-point loss from a month
earlier.
   ``The modest decline in the measure of confidence in January
represents some cooling of the enthusiasm registered in December
following the presidential election,'' said Fabian Linden, head of
the board's consumer research unit. ``Still, while the most recent
readings represent some retreat from the month before, they remain
comfortably strong.''
   At the same time, Linden said, the January decline shows ``there
apparently is some moderate apprehension about the future, as the
nation's prime economic problems _ the two deficits and the savings
and loan crisis _ increasingly become major issues in the public
debate.''
   The index is derived from a monthly survey, covering 5,000
households nationwide, conducted for the board by the National
Family Opinion of Toledo, Ohio. The index uses a 1985 base of 100.
   Buying plans fell for all major categories included in the
survey. Plans to buy cars fell to 6.8 percent from 7.4 percent a
month earlier. Concern about rising interest rates contributed to a
1 percentage point drop in home-buying plans to 2.8 percent.
   The Conference Board is a New York-based network of executives
that supports management and economic research.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
