<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-AlleghenyInternational     02-01 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Allegheny International,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales, Profits Decline; More Trouble Exposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Appliance maker Allegheny International Inc.
said Wednesday that competitive pressure on its sales volume and
prices caused its first-quarter profits to fall 75 percent.
   The company, which is reorganizing under federal bankruptcy laws
and which has attracted the interest of potential buyers, earned
$1.8 million during its first quarter, down from $7.2 million a year
earlier.
   Allegheny International's first-quarter profit translated to a
per-share loss after dividend requirements. It also suffered a
per-share loss in the first quarter a year ago.
   Sales at the appliance and consumer products company dropped 13
percent to $227 million from $256.2 million.
   A group led by the investment firm Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette
Securities Corp. has offered to buy Allegheny International for $812
million.
   However, Allegheny International has disagreed with the terms of
a buyout agreement it reached with DLJ, and it has asked a federal
bankruptcy judge to void the proposed transaction.
   Last week the company filed a proposed plan of reorganization,
which if approved in bankruptcy court would lead to the sale of the
Sunbeam-Oster appliance division.
   The Pittsburgh-based company would retain its businesses in
outdoor furniture, electric blankets, clocks, weather instruments
and scales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
